(17, 1, '2010-12-09 08:36:29', '2010-12-09 08:36:29', '<p>UMBAUGH does not collect personally identifiable information (i.e., information that can be used to identify or contact you, such as your name, email address, or mailing address) from you unless you voluntarily choose to submit that information.</p>\r\n<h2>Information Safety</h2>\r\n<p>While UMBAUGH strives to safeguard your personal information, data transmission over the Internet, including e-mail, cannot be guaranteed to be 100% secure. Therefore, UMBAUGH cannot ensure or warrant the security of any information you transmit, and any information you transmit is done at your own risk. UMBAUGH cannot be responsible for disclosures of your personal information due to errors in transmission or unauthorized acts of third parties, and encourages you to exercise prudence in selecting the information you send via the Internet, including via e-mail.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Contact Information</h2>\r\n<p>If you would like to contact us with questions or comments concerning the privacy of your information, or if you believe that UMBAUGH has not adhered to this Privacy Statement, please notify us. This Privacy Statement may occasionally change, so please refer to this page periodically to check for updates. We welcome your questions and comments.</p>\r\n', 'Privacy Policy', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'privacy-policy', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:30:30', '2011-01-25 18:30:30', '', 0, 'http://localhost/umbaugh/?page_id=17', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(812, 5, '2011-01-25 21:54:01', '2011-01-25 21:54:01', '<em>(Part 2 of a 2-part series)</em>\n\nLocal government officials in many communities are finding it increasingly difficult to fund public safety services with existing levels of revenues and property tax.  Establishing a fire territory is an option that can provide a new revenue stream for fire services. If your community is considering establishing a fire territory, it is a good idea to begin the process now to meet the statutory deadline of March 1, 2010 to have a fire territory beginning in 2011.\n\nThe following are excerpts from an interview with James VanGorder. Chief VanGorder has been a fire chief in Zionsville since 1997 for both the volunteer fire department and the Town''s fire department. In 2007, he was appointed to his current position as the full-time fire chief of the Zionsville Fire Territory.\n\n<strong>Q:</strong> What are positive and negative changes that have occurred since the fire territory was established?\n\n<strong>A:</strong> A positive change is that the fire department was able to move from a part-time, standby department to a full-time department with 40 employees.  The one negative thing was the removal of the three-year operating levy phase-in, which took away some flexibility for future fire territories.\n\n<strong>Q:</strong> Did you meet much resistance from fire fighters or taxpayers while forming the fire territory?\n\n<strong>A:</strong> The response was mostly favorable.  We conducted 13 public meetings to present the Department''s strategic plan and the financial/taxpayer impact of the territory.  It was important to keep all parties well educated and well informed.  In addition to the public meetings, we held bi-monthly working group meetings with Fire Department, Town and Township officials.  In the end, everyone agreed that a fire territory was a good idea and the benefits outweighed the costs.\n\n<strong>Q:</strong> What are major issues to consider when forming a fire territory?\n\n<strong>A:</strong> Two major issues we faced were the formation of the fire territory board and the position of fire chief.  Since those were concerns of both parties, we confronted those issues up front and resolved them in a professional manner by listening and working together to come up with a mutually agreeable solution.\n\nFiguring out who was to be on the fire territory board was a difficult decision because there were only two taxing units involved and three positions to fill.  After much discussion, we decided to have one person represent each taxing unit and the third board member would be mutually agreed upon.  If we could not agree on the appointee, the Town and the Township would alternate in choosing the board member.\n\nThere were concerns that one taxing unit would have all control over the fire chief position.  To resolve the problem, we included a section in the establishing ordinance which said the fire chief could be removed at any time by majority vote of the fire territory board.\n\nTo read the first part of Chief VanGorder''s interview, see the November 11 issue of Footnotes.  Umbaugh has assisted many local entities with feasibility studies to determine if a fire territory would be advantageous.  We understand the nuances, government levy issues, tips to make a new arrangement successful and pitfalls to avoid.', 'Don''t Burn Through the Deadline to Establish A Fire Territory For 2011: Key Perspectives from a Fire Chief', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '593-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-25 21:54:01', '2011-01-25 21:54:01', '', 593, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/593-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
