(526, 3, '2009-07-22 19:12:19', '2009-07-22 19:12:19', 'Units of local government are in the middle of setting annual budgets.  It is always a stressful time, but it may be even more stressful this year because of the number of changes to funding and revenue streams â€“ creating a host of ''unknowns'' as you prepare your financial roadmap for the coming year.  The following assumptions will help you turn those ''unknowns'' into numbers you can live with.\r\n\r\n<strong>Assumption #1:  Your budget must be done on time.</strong>\r\n\r\nLegislative changes that became effective July 1 have changed the timeline for submitting budgets.  Work back from the November 3 deadline and ensure you give yourself enough time to meet all the target dates in the approval process:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Deadline for 1st publication â€“ September 2</li>\r\n	<li>Deadline for 2nd publication â€“ September 9</li>\r\n	<li>Deadline for Submission of budget to County Council â€“ September 17 (no later than 45 days before the taxing unit adopts its budget)</li>\r\n	<li>Deadline for County Council to review taxing unit''s budget â€“ October 17</li>\r\n	<li>Deadline for public hearing â€“ October 22</li>\r\n	<li>Deadline for budget adoption â€“ November 1</li>\r\n	<li>Deadline to submit budget documents to the County Auditor â€“ November 3</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Assumption #2: What''s my 2010 Estimated Assessed Value?</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you are fortunate enough to be in an area where the 2009 certified assessed value (AV) is available, multiply it by 75% for the estimated 2010 assessed value.\r\n\r\nIf 2008 is the most recent certified assessed value available, multiply the 2008 certified AV by 75%, and then multiply that number by 75% again.  It should provide a reasonably accurate assumption.\r\n\r\n<strong>Assumption #3: What numbers do I use for Local Option Income Tax (CAGIT, COIT, and EDIT?</strong>\r\n\r\nFor the last half of 2009, divide the 2009 certified amount by 2. (The certified amounts are located on the 2009 1782 notice and the DLGF Web site.)\r\n\r\nFor 2010, use the 2008 certified amounts located on the DLGF Web site.\r\n\r\n<strong>Assumption #4: What are my Circuit Breaker Credits (property tax losses)?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe 2009 and 2010 cash flows should have a line item directly below the property taxes in the revenue section called "Estimated Circuit Breaker Credits."  You can use the estimates from the LSA report dated March 23, 2009.  If you think the LSA number may not be accurate for your area, we at Umbaugh can prepare a custom report based on your situation.\r\n\r\n<strong>Assumption #5:  What number do I use for State Pension Reimbursement?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe State will forward you an estimate of pension relief for 2009.  Note that the State combines police and fire pension relief into one total amount.  You will need to allocate the distribution to police and fire individually based on the percentage of 2008 actual disbursements for police and fire.\r\n\r\nPension relief for 2010 is based on estimated 2009 expenditures for police and fire pension.  Pension distributions from the state are typically posted by the taxing unit on July 1 and Oct. 1.  You will need to check this in order to complete column A of Budget Form 2 accurately.\r\n\r\n<strong>Assumption #6:  What number do I use for Three-Year Growth Appeals?</strong>\r\n\r\nHB1001 specifies that the amount of the supplemental homestead standard deduction applied to 2009 assessed values must be added back to determine eligibility for a three-year growth appeal.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have additional questions about making up your budget, please contact us.</em>', 'In the middle of preparing your budget?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'in-the-middle-of-preparing-your-budget', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:25:03', '2011-01-25 16:25:03', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=526', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(416, 3, '2011-01-07 14:35:50', '2011-01-07 14:35:50', '<h2>Our Services for Local Government</h2>\r\n                    <p><strong>Financial Management</strong> - No one who works in local government would say that financial management is "simple."   Your constituents never think about how time consuming your day-to-day tasks are.  Umbaugh can help you with:</p>\r\n                        <ul class="left">\r\n                            <li>Audit Preparation</li>\r\n                            <li>CAFR Preparation</li>\r\n                            <li>Financial Reporting</li>\r\n                            <li>Tax Revenue Analysis and Management</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        \r\n                        <ul class="right">\r\n                            <li>Budget Preparation Assistance</li>\r\n                            <li>Comprehensive Financial Planning</li>\r\n                            <li>GASB 34 Compliance</li>\r\n                            <li>User Fee Development</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n\r\n	                    <p>As you look for every <strong>cost savings and efficiency</strong>, we can also provide:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>Consolidation Planning and Implementation</li>\r\n                                <li>Negotiating Inter-Governmental Agreements</li>\r\n                                <li>Performance Management Studies</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n\r\n	                    <p>If you are considering a new accounting system, let us relieve your nightmares and worry of system selection (What if it doesn''t work?  What if we lose our data?) with:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>Accounting Systems Consulting</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                    \r\n	                    <p><strong>Capital Planning</strong> - Every unit of government has projects that need to be done â€“ and equipment that needs to be upgraded or replaced.  It''s tempting to defer projects and delay expenses, but that could catch up to you someday with a big bill â€“ or a service failure.  We all know it''s better to plan ahead.  Umbaugh can help you with:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>Debt Management Studies</li>\r\n                                <li>Project Planning and Financial Development</li>\r\n                                <li>Refinancing of Existing Debt</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            \r\n                            <ul class="right">\r\n                                <li>Long-Range Capital Planning and Implementation</li>\r\n                                <li>Developing and Evaluating Funding Alternatives</li>\r\n                                <li>Financial Presentations to Elected Officials and the Public</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                    \r\n	                    <p><strong>Bond Issuance</strong> - Bond issues are not something you do every day, and you''ve got to get it right. The stakes are literally too high to risk a mistake or miss an opportunity to save. Since Umbaugh is an independent advisor, our only priority is doing what''s best for the local governments we represent. We can provide:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>Official Statements and Bond Sale Preparations</li>\r\n                                <li>Presentations to Bond Ratings Agencies</li>\r\n                                <li>Evaluation of Bond Insurance Proposals</li>\r\n                                <li>Competitive Bond Sales and Electronic</li>\r\n                                <li>Bidding Services</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            \r\n                            <ul class="right">\r\n                                <li>Negotiated Bond Sales and Private Placements</li>\r\n                                <li>Coordination of Bond Closings</li>\r\n                                <li>Assistance to the Trustee bank</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                    \r\n	                    <p><strong>Post Issuance</strong> - Unfortunately, the paperwork does not go away after the bonds are sold.  You as the bond issuer have a great deal of responsibility for reporting and compliance, at a time when you''d much rather be paying attention to your bond-funded project.  Umbaugh can take those worries off your plate as well with:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>In-Progress Construction Reports</li>\r\n                                <li>Arbitrage Rebate Calculations</li>\r\n                                <li>Continuing Disclosure Filings</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            \r\n                            <ul class="right">\r\n                                <li>Post Issuance Compliance</li>\r\n                                <li>Escrow Verifications</li>\r\n                                <li>Parity Reports</li>\r\n                            </ul>', 'Local Governments', 'Operating a local governmental unit always has challenges and opportunities. You may be looking for new efficiencies, projecting changes in tax revenue, finding new revenue sources, working on long-range planning, funding buildings and improvements, or structuring the most advantageous economic development package. Our years of experience in helping others in similar situations make us uniquely qualified to help you today -- and with tomorrow''s challenges.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '206-revision-12', '', '', '2011-01-07 14:35:50', '2011-01-07 14:35:50', '', 206, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/206-revision-12', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
