(796, 5, '2011-01-18 21:45:11', '2011-01-18 21:45:11', '<p>In the April 1 issue of Footnotes, we explored options for funding the required match for projects that qualify for federal stimulus money.  Since few communities have excess cash balances right now, the remaining option is new debt.  Each of the two forms of new debt -- revenue supported bonds and property tax supported debt â€“ have different options and advantages.</p>\r\n<p><em>Fifth article in a series.</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Revenue Supported Bonds</strong> â€“ Revenue bonds are the ones most commonly used for utility projects.  Payments on these bonds come from utility user fees, income taxes (CAGIT, CEDIT or COIT), tax increment financing, food and beverage taxes, innkeeper''s taxes, wheel and surtaxes and other limited tax levies "inside the freeze." </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The disadvantages: Because revenue bonds are supported by limited revenue, they generally have higher interest rates and lower credit ratings.  They typically require funding a debt service reserve or other credit enhancement.  You may be required to pledge additional security, which can come from multiple revenue sources.</li>\r\n	<li>The advantage: Revenue supported bonds are not subject to a petition-remonstrance process, a referendum or the tax caps.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Property Tax Supported Debt</strong> â€“ As the name implies, payments for these bonds come from property tax levy, and it can be "outside the freeze."</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The disadvantages: Property tax supported debt, depending on the size of the issue, may be subject to the petition-remonstrance process or a referendum.  These bonds are also subject to the constitutional debt limit. </li>\r\n	<li>The advantages:  Because of their full faith and credit pledge, these bonds have the highest credit rating and lowest interest rates available.  If approved by a referendum, they are not subject to the property tax caps.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Regardless of which form of financing you choose for your project, it will take time to arrange it.  Since priority will be given to "shovel ready" projects, it is wise to get started early. If you are considering a stimulus fund project, get your team on board and start planning. There will be ordinances and resolutions to adopt and notices to issue â€“ and you may need to allow sufficient periods of time for remonstrance, petitions or a referendum.  Your team needs to include an engineer, a grant administrator, a financial advisor and bond and local counsel.</p>\r\n<p>In addition to having your much-needed projects at least partially funded by stimulus money, there is more good news for those who successfully pursue new debt: there are many options for selling the bonds and interest rates are near historic lows.</p>', 'Choosing the best matching funds option for your stimulus projects', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '562-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 21:45:11', '2011-01-18 21:45:11', '', 562, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/562-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
