(482, 3, '2000-09-02 19:21:58', '2000-09-02 19:21:58', 'Numerous factors caused the financial markets to nearly come to a complete halt in October, 2008.  Many believe the meltdown of residential mortgages was the key to the market collapse and subsequent credit freeze.  Packaged mortgage debt, or Collateralized Debt Obligations, had become a significant portion of many institutional investorsâ€™ investment portfolios, including insurance giants like AIG and financial-services firms such as Lehman Brothers.\r\n\r\nBecause of the sudden disintegration of their assets last fall, major institutions were no longer purchasing municipal bonds.  Investors with solid balance sheets flew to safety and began investing almost exclusively in US Treasury instruments.  As investors sought to protect their principal without regard to interest earnings, Treasury yields fell to historic lows. During December of 2008 the three-month Treasury yield fell to 0% on three separate occasions.\r\n\r\nAs the dust settled on the collapse and investors who remained solvent realized that the likelihood of default on municipal bonds is extremely low, we the bond market began to ease.  However, the market had changed.  There were far fewer institutional investors with funds available to purchase municipal bonds, and retail investors (individuals) began to play a larger role.  Because many banks were not making a profit, the demand for tax-exempt bond purchases was reduced.\r\n\r\nAlong with AIG and Lehman Brothers, municipal bond insurance providers experienced massive losses in assets due to the meltdown of residential mortgages.  All but two of the major municipal bond insurers have lost their AAA rating from Standard &amp; Poorâ€™s, and all of them have lost their Aaa rating from Moodyâ€™s.  In 2007, roughly half of all municipal bond sales were insured.  Through July of 2009, only 11% of sales have been insured.  The absence of insurers with highest quality ratings has left issuers without this option for enhancing the credit on their bonds.\r\n\r\nSmaller bond issues are commonly sold without a bond rating, but larger issues can benefit from an investment grade rating of A or higher.  The cost of the rating will be offset by lower interest costs.  For example, an issuer of a 20-year $5 million bond with a â€œAAâ€ rating would save nearly $1 million in interest compared to the same bond with a â€œBBBâ€ rating.  With the various market changes, the differential in interest rates has widened from those credits receiving a â€œAAâ€ rating or better compared to â€œAâ€ or lower.\r\n<div>\r\n<p id="internal-source-marker_0.6613685386255383">Standard &amp; Poorâ€™s, Moodyâ€™s and Fitch have all sharpened their focus on financial management in past months. Â As part of the rating process, the rating agencies thoroughly review the credit worthiness of the local government. Â While economic factors may be outside your control, following best practices within your finance department can help increase an otherwise average bond rating. Â Â For example, providing long-term financial planning and adopting a fund balance reserve policy or debt policy can demonstrate your organizationâ€™s financial flexibility and ability to weather the financial storm.</p>\r\nIf you have questions about or need assistance issuing bonds, or if you want advice about best practices, contact us.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'A Year of Change for the Municipal Bond Market', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'a-year-of-change-for-the-municipal-bond-market', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:04:32', '2011-01-25 16:04:32', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=482', 0, 'post', '', 0),
