(720, 3, '2011-01-19 19:10:55', '2011-01-19 19:10:55', '<p>Laws governing referendum, petition and remonstrance procedures for controlled projects changed again in the 2009 session of the Indiana General Assembly.  Most of the changes merely fine tuned and clarified the process, but some provisions will make getting approval for building projects different going forward.</p>\r\n<p>The main changes are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>We will no longer see special elections spread throughout the year as we experienced in 2009.</strong>  Referenda will be considered at the next primary, general or municipal election.  If there is no primary, general or municipal election in the year after a public question becomes eligible to be on the ballot, the political subdivision may request a special election on the first Tuesday after the first Monday in May or November. The fiscal body of a political subdivision requesting a special election must pay the costs of holding a special election.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>The wording of the ballot question has been spelled out more clearly, and it must include the project cost and tax increase amount.</strong>  The amendment for ballot question reads:</li>\r\n	<blockquote>"Shall __________ (insert name of the political subdivision) issue bonds or enter into a least to finance ___________ (insert a brief description of the controlled project), which is estimated to cost not more than _________ (insert the total cost of the project) and is estimated to increase the property tax rate for debt service by _________ (insert increase in tax rate as determined by the department of local government finance)?"</blockquote>\r\n	<p>The exact wording of the question must be approved by the County Election Board(s) for that jurisdiction.</p>\r\n	<li><strong>A political subdivision may withdraw a public question from the ballot.</strong></li>\r\n	<li>The law allows the county election board to defer action on a petition submitted shortly before a regularly scheduled election until after the election.  Under this revision, <strong>the time period before an election when action can be deferred has been lengthened from 35 days to 45 days.</strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>The definitions of registered voter and eligible voter were clarified.</strong>  Formerly, an individual was eligible to vote on the public question if he was registered to vote in the political subdivision 30 days before the date of the election.\r\n		<br /><br />The law now says that an eligible voter is one who is eligible to vote in the political subdivision in which the public question will be held, pursuant to State Statute.  Further, to be eligible to vote, the individual must reside within the boundaries of the political subdivision for which the public question is being considered.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>The revisions spell out what information a political subdivision must make available to the public at the preliminary determination hearing.</strong>  This includes not only the maximum term, annual lease rental, principal amount and purpose of the proposed project, but also includes the indebtedness of "overlapping" taxing units.</li>\r\n	<li>The political subdivision must submit certain information regarding the referendum project to the Department of Local Government Finance at least 30 days before the election for posting on the DLGF Web site.  This information includes:\r\n    	<ul>\r\n            <li>The cost per square foot of any buildings being constructed as part of the controlled project.</li>\r\n            <li>The effect that approval of the controlled project would have on the political subdivision''s property tax rate.</li>\r\n            <li>The maximum term of the bonds or lease.</li>\r\n            <li>The estimated interest rates that will be paid and the total interest costs associated with the bonds or lease.</li>\r\n            <li>The purpose of the bonds or lease.</li>\r\n            <li>In the case of a controlled project proposed by a school corporation:\r\n            	<ul>\r\n                    <li>The current and proposed square footage of school building space per student;</li>\r\n                    <li>Enrollment patterns within the school corporation; and</li>\r\n                    <li>The age and condition of the current school facilities.</li>\r\n				</ul>\r\n             </li>\r\n			<li><strong>A political subdivision itself may introduce a public question on the ballot without a taxpayer petition under certain circumstances.</strong></li>\r\n			<li><strong>An elected or appointed official of a political subdivision may personally advocate for or against a position on the petition or remonstrance or a local public question as long as it is not done using public funds.</strong></li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>A student may use school equipment or facilities to report or editorialize about a local public question as part of news coverage of the referendum by student newspaper or broadcast.</p>\r\n<p>The above information is in part based upon a memo of the DLGF Commissioner dated August 7, 2009.</p>\r\n<p>Umbaugh is currently working with four school districts that have referenda on the November 3 ballot: Batesville Community School Corporation, Southwest Dubois County School Corporation, Tell City-Troy Township School Corporation and the MSD of Perry Township.</p>\r\n<p>If you have questions or need assistance with financing a controlled project, please contact us.</p>', 'Changes To Indiana Law Affect Approval Process for Shool and Local Government Building Projects', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '610-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 19:10:55', '2011-01-19 19:10:55', '', 610, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/610-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(485, 3, '2009-08-19 15:42:51', '2009-08-19 15:42:51', 'As we look at ways local governments can provide local services using less revenue, managing your capital needs is an essential tool for government efficiency because capital projects can be such a large expenditure.\r\n\r\nStart by looking at the big picture.  Develop a capital plan that includes all major improvements and related costs expected over the next five to ten years.  Although you may not be able to accomplish all projects on the optimal schedule â€“ and there may be additional unexpected projects crop up â€“ having all of the potential projects on your capital plan gives you a road map to guide the planning process.\r\n\r\nInclude a review of your current debt repayment obligations in that capital plan.  These payments must be made, so they will figure into the amount of resources you have for new projects. As you review current debts, consider whether you should take this opportunity to refinance or restructure existing bonds to save money.  Plot a timetable showing when existing bonds will be retired.  If you can schedule payments for new projects to begin as other bonds are paid off, that provides an opportunity to fund projects without using more of your current revenue.\r\n\r\nMany long-lived assets can be financed through issuing debt rather than by paying for them out of current income.  Local governmental units often prefer to avoid borrowing because they don''t like to incur interest expense.  Rather than applying this "pay as you go" philosophy, financing on a "pay as you use" basis pays for the asset as taxpayers use it over the next 20 years or so.  It is a fair way to match the benefit of the asset with the taxpayers who will actually use it.   Financing these assets with debt reduces the amount of current taxes needed to pay for public infrastructure.  Bond financing approved by a referendum may give you the additional advantage of having those bond repayments outside of property tax caps.\r\n\r\nOnce you have your capital plan, review and update it annually to adjust for changing needs and circumstances.\r\n\r\nOur next article in the strategies for government efficiency series will cover how to grow your tax base to bring in more revenue.\r\n\r\nIf you have questions or need assistance with managing your capital needs, please contact us.', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency Part 4: Managing Your Capital Needs', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'strategies-for-government-efficiency-part-4', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:13:33', '2011-01-25 16:13:33', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=485', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(486, 3, '2011-01-18 15:42:21', '2011-01-18 15:42:21', '<p>As we look at ways local governments can provide local services using less revenue, managing your capital needs is an essential tool for government efficiency because capital projects can be such a large expenditure.</p>\n<p>Start by looking at the big picture.  Develop a capital plan that includes all major improvements and related costs expected over the next five to ten years.  Although you may not be able to accomplish all projects on the optimal schedule â€“ and there may be additional unexpected projects crop up â€“ having all of the potential projects on your capital plan gives you a road map to guide the planning process.</p>\n<p>Include a review of your current debt repayment obligations in that capital plan.  These payments must be made, so they will figure into the amount of resources you have for new projects. As you review current debts, consider whether you should take this opportunity to refinance or restructure existing bonds to save money.  Plot a timetable showing when existing bonds will be retired.  If you can schedule payments for new projects to begin as other bonds are paid off, that provides an opportunity to fund projects without using more of your current revenue.</p>\n<p>Many long-lived assets can be financed through issuing debt rather than by paying for them out of current income.  Local governmental units often prefer to avoid borrowing because they don''t like to incur interest expense.  Rather than applying this "pay as you go" philosophy, financing on a "pay as you use" basis pays for the asset as taxpayers use it over the next 20 years or so.  It is a fair way to match the benefit of the asset with the taxpayers who will actually use it.   Financing these assets with debt reduces the amount of current taxes needed to pay for public infrastructure.  Bond financing approved by a referendum may give you the additional advantage of having those bond repayments outside of property tax caps.</p>\n<p>Once you have your capital plan, review and update it annually to adjust for changing needs and circumstances.</p>\n<p>Our next article in the strategies for government efficiency series will cover how to grow your tax base to bring in more revenue.  </p>\n<p>If you have questions or need assistance with managing your capital needs, please contact us.</p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency part 4', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '485-revision', '', '', '2011-01-18 15:42:21', '2011-01-18 15:42:21', '', 485, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/485-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(487, 3, '2009-08-29 15:50:23', '2009-08-29 15:50:23', 'Does the term "non-binding review and recommendation" sound pretty futile? It doesn''t have to be.\r\n\r\nWhen the Indiana General Assembly changed the property tax system over the last few sessions and enacted Circuit Breaker property tax caps, budgets for units of local government became more interdependent.  At the same time, the changes increased the role of County Councils in the process of budget approvals and setting tax rates.\r\n\r\nAll civil taxing units â€“ and that can be a large number depending on the county â€“ must file their proposed tax rate, levy and budget with the County Council for review and a non-binding recommendation.\r\n\r\nThe county fiscal body then has 15 days to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>review the proposed budget, estimated tax rate and levy</li>\r\n	<li>issue a non-binding recommendation to each civil taxing unit that includes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>comparison of any increase in the unit''s budget or tax levy to the average increase in state and county nonfarm personal income for the preceding six calendar years</li>\r\n	<li>increases in the budgets and tax levies of other civil taxing units in the county.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe Department of Local Government Finance (DLGF) has developed forms that counties may use on a voluntary basis to make these comparisons.\r\n\r\nThe review for each civil taxing unit could be very perfunctory -- or County Councils may elect to use this process as an opportunity to facilitate meaningful collaboration on a budget.\r\n\r\nThese recommended steps will help County Councils make this process meaningful:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Contact each unit to discuss and ask questions about their budgets.</strong> You''re not doing this to be intrusive or question the validity of their budget.  You''re trying to share meaningful information about changes in debt structure, anticipated debt issuance and expected material changes in local assessed valuation.  You''re also gathering information to develop a model to estimate what the Circuit Breaker impacts will be for each unit.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Develop a county-wide model showing the impact of Circuit Breaker credits.</strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Convene a meeting to share the results with all civil taxing units</strong> BEFORE the budgets are finalized, giving everyone a chance to regroup with the benefit of complete information.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Reach out to school districts</strong>.  Although they are not civil taxing units and are not required to submit their budgets, school districts are impacted by the Circuit Breaker and other units'' tax rates.  When you include school districts in the process, it fosters cooperation among the interdependent taxing units.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Identify controlled funds</strong> and determine, based on the levy growth quotient, what the reduction in each levy or budget is likely to be along with the resulting reduction to the tax rate.  Another less-time-consuming alternative is to look for increases in non-controlled levies (i.e. debt service) because they cannot be cut.</li>\r\n	<li>Use the non-binding recommendation to <strong>point out to each taxing unit where they exceed the growth quotient</strong>, and how they compare to other budget/levy changes, and how they compare with nonfarm income changes.  If necessary, include a general statement that their budget is like to be cut and by how much.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Remind those submitting from appointed boards</strong> (usually libraries) where the levies exceed the average growth quotient that their budget is not subject to the non-binding review, but must be adopted by the appropriate fiscal body (city/town or county).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn the end, each County Council''s decision on how proactive to be in the non-binding review and recommendation process largely will depend on how much time they are willing to devote to the process.  It could very well be time well spent in terms of their county''s economic health.\r\n\r\nIf your county needs assistance in the budget review and recommendation process, please contact.', 'County budget review: futile or meaningful?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'county-budget-review-futile-or-meaningful', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:10:30', '2011-01-25 16:10:30', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=487', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(488, 3, '2011-01-18 15:50:18', '2011-01-18 15:50:18', '<p>Does the term "non-binding review and recommendation" sound pretty futile? It doesn''t have to be.</p>\n<p>When the Indiana General Assembly changed the property tax system over the last few sessions and enacted Circuit Breaker property tax caps, budgets for units of local government became more interdependent.  At the same time, the changes increased the role of County Councils in the process of budget approvals and setting tax rates.</p>\n<p>All civil taxing units â€“ and that can be a large number depending on the county â€“ must file their proposed tax rate, levy and budget with the County Council for review and a non-binding recommendation.</p>\n<p>The county fiscal body then has 15 days to:</p>\n	<ul>\n    	<li>review the proposed budget, estimated tax rate and levy</li>\n		<li>issue a non-binding recommendation to each civil taxing unit that includes:\n			<ul>\n				<li>comparison of any increase in the unit''s budget or tax levy to the average increase in state and county nonfarm personal income for the preceding six calendar years</li>\n				<li>increases in the budgets and tax levies of other civil taxing units in the county.</li>\n        	</ul>\n    	</li>\n	</ul>\n    \n<p>The Department of Local Government Finance (DLGF) has developed forms that counties may use on a voluntary basis to make these comparisons.</p>\n<p>The review for each civil taxing unit could be very perfunctory -- or County Councils may elect to use this process as an opportunity to facilitate meaningful collaboration on a budget.</p>\n<p>These recommended steps will help County Councils make this process meaningful:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Contact each unit to discuss and ask questions about their budgets.</strong> You''re not doing this to be intrusive or question the validity of their budget.  You''re trying to share meaningful information about changes in debt structure, anticipated debt issuance and expected material changes in local assessed valuation.  You''re also gathering information to develop a model to estimate what the Circuit Breaker impacts will be for each unit.</li>\n    <li><strong>Develop a county-wide model showing the impact of Circuit Breaker credits.</strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Convene a meeting to share the results with all civil taxing units</strong> BEFORE the budgets are finalized, giving everyone a chance to regroup with the benefit of complete information.</li>\n	<li><strong>Reach out to school districts</strong>.  Although they are not civil taxing units and are not required to submit their budgets, school districts are impacted by the Circuit Breaker and other units'' tax rates.  When you include school districts in the process, it fosters cooperation among the interdependent taxing units.</li>\n	<li><strong>Identify controlled funds</strong> and determine, based on the levy growth quotient, what the reduction in each levy or budget is likely to be along with the resulting reduction to the tax rate.  Another less-time-consuming alternative is to look for increases in non-controlled levies (i.e. debt service) because they cannot be cut.</li>\n	<li>Use the non-binding recommendation to <strong>point out to each taxing unit where they exceed the growth quotient</strong>, and how they compare to other budget/levy changes, and how they compare with nonfarm income changes.  If necessary, include a general statement that their budget is like to be cut and by how much.</li>\n	<li><strong>Remind those submitting from appointed boards</strong> (usually libraries) where the levies exceed the average growth quotient that their budget is not subject to the non-binding review, but must be adopted by the appropriate fiscal body (city/town or county).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In the end, each County Council''s decision on how proactive to be in the non-binding review and recommendation process largely will depend on how much time they are willing to devote to the process.  It could very well be time well spent in terms of their county''s economic health.</p>\n<p>If your county needs assistance in the budget review and recommendation process, please contact.</p>', 'County budget review: futile or meaningful?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '487-revision', '', '', '2011-01-18 15:50:18', '2011-01-18 15:50:18', '', 487, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/487-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
