(489, 3, '2009-08-05 16:03:04', '2009-08-05 16:03:04', '<div>\r\n<p id="internal-source-marker_0.8404643973335624">Part 3 in a series</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nIn the first article of this series on Strategies for Government Efficiency, we listed five strategies that must be included:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>managing revenues efficiently,</li>\r\n	<li>finding opportunities for cost efficiencies,</li>\r\n	<li>providing services efficiently through consolidation,</li>\r\n	<li>managing capital expenditures and</li>\r\n	<li>growing your tax base.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThis article covers finding opportunities for cost efficiencies.\r\n\r\nIf dealing with reduced revenue means you must reduce the cost of providing services, you can do that by:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>improving efficiencies,</li>\r\n	<li>reducing the quality of services and/or</li>\r\n	<li>cutting public services.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNormally we dislike the second and third alternatives above, because constituents have become accustomed to a certain level of service.  But don''t totally discount reducing or cutting services.  This is a good time for all stakeholders to evaluate such questions as what crime rate is acceptable, how quickly do we really need to fill potholes, and can we tolerate a longer fire response time?  The answers will vary from community to community.  Answering these and other questions about local services will give you a strategic planning framework for making difficult decisions to reduce the quality of services, reduce the level of public services or to increase taxes.  (We''ll have more on strategic planning in future issues.)\r\n\r\nOther counties have found creative approaches that may work in your area.  Their cost efficiency solutions include four-day work weeks and/or special summer shifts, self-insurance programs, wellness programs, coordinating city police and county sheriff responsibilities, centralized purchasing, energy audits, in-house construction inspection and working with judges to manage jail capacity.\r\n\r\nAs you look for ways to reduce costs, reducing the number of employees is always something to consider.  In a previous issue of Footnotes, we reviewed the costs of downsizing.  Please refer to the June 10 issue on our Web site if staff reductions are being considered in your cost efficiency plan.\r\n\r\nAs you look for cost efficiencies, resist the immediate temptation to simply slash services without adequate thought to the consequences.  If reducing services destroys the quality of life that attracts people to your area, people move away and you don''t attract new employers.  You will have to strike the right balance for your community, and that''s why strategically planning these efficiencies is so important.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance dealing with reduced funding, please contact us.</em>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: Finding Opportunities for Cost Efficiencies', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'strategies-for-government-efficiency-part-3', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:19:58', '2011-01-25 16:19:58', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=489', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(490, 3, '2011-01-18 16:00:37', '2011-01-18 16:00:37', '<p>In the first article of this series on Strategies for Government Efficiency, we listed five strategies that must be included:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>managing revenues efficiently,</li>\n    <li>finding opportunities for cost efficiencies,</li>\n    <li>providing services efficiently through consolidation,</li>\n    <li>managing capital expenditures and</li>\n    <li>growing your tax base.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This article covers finding opportunities for cost efficiencies.</p>\n\n<p>If dealing with reduced revenue means you must reduce the cost of providing services, you can do that by:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>improving efficiencies,</li>\n    <li>reducing the quality of services and/or</li>\n    <li>cutting public services.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Normally we dislike the second and third alternatives above, because constituents have become accustomed to a certain level of service.  But don''t totally discount reducing or cutting services.  This is a good time for all stakeholders to evaluate such questions as what crime rate is acceptable, how quickly do we really need to fill potholes, and can we tolerate a longer fire response time?  The answers will vary from community to community.  Answering these and other questions about local services will give you a strategic planning framework for making difficult decisions to reduce the quality of services, reduce the level of public services or to increase taxes.  (We''ll have more on strategic planning in future issues.)</p>\n<p>Other counties have found creative approaches that may work in your area.  Their cost efficiency solutions include four-day work weeks and/or special summer shifts, self-insurance programs, wellness programs, coordinating city police and county sheriff responsibilities, centralized purchasing, energy audits, in-house construction inspection and working with judges to manage jail capacity.</p>\n<p>As you look for ways to reduce costs, reducing the number of employees is always something to consider.  In a previous issue of Footnotes, we reviewed the costs of downsizing.  Please refer to the June 10 issue on our Web site if staff reductions are being considered in your cost efficiency plan.</p>\n<p>As you look for cost efficiencies, resist the immediate temptation to simply slash services without adequate thought to the consequences.  If reducing services destroys the quality of life that attracts people to your area, people move away and you don''t attract new employers.  You will have to strike the right balance for your community, and that''s why strategically planning these efficiencies is so important.</p>\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance dealing with reduced funding, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: Finding Opportunities for Cost Efficiencies Part 3', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '489-revision', '', '', '2011-01-18 16:00:37', '2011-01-18 16:00:37', '', 489, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/489-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(494, 3, '2009-07-22 16:08:37', '2009-07-22 16:08:37', 'Across Indiana, local governmental entities are facing a <strong>half billion dollar reduction</strong> in income due to property tax caps, and additional reductions from the expansion of the homestead exemption and lower income tax collections in a down economy.  Finding new efficiencies to operate on less income is much more than simply cutting your budget, you also must manage revenues efficiently.\r\n\r\nEnacting new local option income taxes (LOIT) to replace property taxes, can reduce the amount of property tax lost to the tap caps by lowering property tax levies and total tax rates.\r\n\r\n<em>Part 2</em>\r\n\r\nAs an example, the chart at left shows the effect of circuit breaker tax credits. In this sample, local governments will lose $2.5 million using current property values.  With property values increasing as in the past, the loss to circuit breaker credits is reduced to $2.2 million.  But remember that property values can trend downward as well as upward.  If property values decrease, the loss from property taxes could be greater.\r\n\r\nIn this same scenario, if the local government enacts a .5% LOIT rate that generates $2.8 million in revenue, the loss from property tax caps is reduced to $1.1 million if the LOIT-funded property tax relief is distributed just to qualified residential properties and to $1.3 million if distributed uniformly.\r\n\r\n<hr />When combined with property tax relief, a new LOIT can also provide new money for public safety.  A public safety LOIT of .25% can generate an estimated $1.4 million in our example.\r\n\r\nChanging the mix of local income taxes may increase total revenues available to taxing units without increasing the total income tax rate. Changes to local income taxes that may increase spendable tax revenue without increasing income tax rates include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Eliminating the local COIT Homestead Credit.  Some of these local credits were enacted before the state adopted credits, so the local credits may no longer be needed in your area.  The final chart at right shows the potential effect of eliminating COIT Homestead Credits.  The $3+ million in increased COIT revenue is partially offset by the decrease in property tax revenues as circuit breaker credits increase, but it still produces additional revenue of nearly $1.5 million.</li>\r\n	<li>Replacing a portion of a CAGIT tax, designed for property tax relief, with an EDIT tax, producing new spendable revenue.</li>\r\n	<li>Shifting LOIT credits from Homestead Credits to either qualified residential credits or uniform credits.  Oftentimes, circuit breaker tax credits benefit do not benefit the majority of homeowners.</li>\r\n	<li>Eliminating the CEDIT inventory replacement rate used for additional homestead credits in exchange for other local option income taxes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBecause many of these revenues are interdependent, finding the right mix of local income taxes will require running some "what if" scenarios for your area.\r\n\r\nThe next article in this series will cover opportunities for cost efficiency.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance dealing with reduced funding, please contact us.</em>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: Managing Revenues Efficiently', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'strategies-for-government-efficiency-part-2', '', '', '2011-01-25 20:48:43', '2011-01-25 20:48:43', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=494', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(491, 3, '2011-01-18 15:42:51', '2011-01-18 15:42:51', '<p>As we look at ways local governments can provide local services using less revenue, managing your capital needs is an essential tool for government efficiency because capital projects can be such a large expenditure.</p>\r\n<p>Start by looking at the big picture.  Develop a capital plan that includes all major improvements and related costs expected over the next five to ten years.  Although you may not be able to accomplish all projects on the optimal schedule â€“ and there may be additional unexpected projects crop up â€“ having all of the potential projects on your capital plan gives you a road map to guide the planning process.</p>\r\n<p>Include a review of your current debt repayment obligations in that capital plan.  These payments must be made, so they will figure into the amount of resources you have for new projects. As you review current debts, consider whether you should take this opportunity to refinance or restructure existing bonds to save money.  Plot a timetable showing when existing bonds will be retired.  If you can schedule payments for new projects to begin as other bonds are paid off, that provides an opportunity to fund projects without using more of your current revenue.</p>\r\n<p>Many long-lived assets can be financed through issuing debt rather than by paying for them out of current income.  Local governmental units often prefer to avoid borrowing because they don''t like to incur interest expense.  Rather than applying this "pay as you go" philosophy, financing on a "pay as you use" basis pays for the asset as taxpayers use it over the next 20 years or so.  It is a fair way to match the benefit of the asset with the taxpayers who will actually use it.   Financing these assets with debt reduces the amount of current taxes needed to pay for public infrastructure.  Bond financing approved by a referendum may give you the additional advantage of having those bond repayments outside of property tax caps.</p>\r\n<p>Once you have your capital plan, review and update it annually to adjust for changing needs and circumstances.</p>\r\n<p>Our next article in the strategies for government efficiency series will cover how to grow your tax base to bring in more revenue.  </p>\r\n<p>If you have questions or need assistance with managing your capital needs, please contact us.</p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency part 4', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '485-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 15:42:51', '2011-01-18 15:42:51', '', 485, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/485-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
