(523, 3, '2009-08-05 18:14:24', '2009-08-05 18:14:24', 'As officials look for ways to streamline local government, many will consider consolidation.  Saving money, however, is not the only potential advantage of consolidation.\r\n\r\nConsolidation may also allow you to better manage and control growth and development through unified planning and zoning, and it can identify your borders by thwarting the possible encroachment on unincorporated areas by other taxing units.  It also promotes better coordination with schools and county government and eliminates the complexity of multiple taxing units.  Consolidation is also intended to create greater transparency in government.\r\n\r\nIn the cost efficiency category, consolidation can provide a broader tax base for funding and may allow areas to share resources to enhance the ability to provide services.  The cost-efficiency benefits were among the reasons the Government Modernization Act was passed in 2006 to allow voluntary consolidation of local governments.  Initiatives from the Kernan-Shepard report also encourage consolidation.\r\n\r\nAs you might expect, some issues may arise when you consider consolidation:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>It may cause changes in Council districts.</li>\r\n	<li>Representatives from all entities being consolidated may have different goals and agendas.</li>\r\n	<li>The consolidation may result in "stranded" debt; each issuing body will be responsible for its pre-existing debt and will need a mechanism to fund payments.</li>\r\n	<li>You will need to determine where services will be allocated.</li>\r\n	<li>You will need to address whether municipal ordinances are applicable to "rural" areas.</li>\r\n	<li>Finally, it may be possible that despite increased operational efficiencies the consolidation does not translate into cost savings.  If they do not, the consolidation is less appealing to taxpayers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUnder the Indiana Government Modernization Act, reorganization may be initiated by adoption of a resolution by the legislative body of a political subdivision or a written petition signed by at least five percent of voters filed with the clerk of the political subdivision.  The law further requires:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Legislative bodies to conduct hearings and adopt resolutions to participate in the reorganization.</li>\r\n	<li>Preparation of a comprehensive reorganization plan.</li>\r\n	<li>Consideration of the plan by the legislative bodies of the participating units,</li>\r\n	<li>Filing the plan with the county recorder, the DLGF, the Department of Education (if applicable), and the clerk of circuit court (if applicable).</li>\r\n	<li>Placing a public question on the ballot by the county election board for consideration by voters.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUnder the Indiana Government Modernization Act, reorganization may be initiated by adoption of a resolution by the legislative body of a political subdivision or a written petition signed by at least five percent of voters filed with the clerk of the political subdivision.  The law further requires:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Legislative bodies to conduct hearings and adopt resolutions to participate in the reorganization.</li>\r\n	<li>The appointment of a reorganization committee either in accordance with an agreement adopted by the participating units or a committee made up of three members appointed by the executive of each participating unit (with no more than two of their three appointments from the same political party).</li>\r\n	<li>Preparation of a comprehensive reorganization plan.</li>\r\n	<li>Consideration of the plan by the legislative bodies of the participating units,</li>\r\n	<li>Filing the plan with the county recorder, the DLGF, the Department of Education (if applicable), and the clerk of circuit court (if applicable).</li>\r\n	<li>Placing a public question on the ballot by the county election board for consideration by voters.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe new entity would also likely need to appeal to the DLGF for revisions to its levy.\r\n\r\nThe possibility of creating a reorganized political subdivision can be a daunting task with complex financial implications.   If you have questions or need assistance with considering consolidation, please contact us.', 'Consolidation â€“ A Viable Option?', '<p>As officials look for ways to streamline local government, many will consider consolidation.  Saving money, however, is not the only potential advantage of consolidation.</p>\r\n<p>Consolidation may also allow you to better manage and control growth and development through unified planning and zoning, and it can identify your borders by thwarting the possible encroachment on unincorporated areas by other taxing units.  It also promotes better coordination with schools and county government and eliminates the complexity of multiple taxing units.  Consolidation is also intended to create greater transparency in government.</p>', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'consolidation-a-viable-option', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:22:49', '2011-01-25 16:22:49', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=523', 0, 'post', '', 0),
