(778, 5, '2011-01-18 19:18:21', '2011-01-18 19:18:21', 'Units of local government are in the middle of setting annual budgets.  It is always a stressful time, but it may be even more stressful this year because of the number of changes to funding and revenue streams â€“ creating a host of ''unknowns'' as you prepare your financial roadmap for the coming year.  The following assumptions will help you turn those ''unknowns'' into numbers you can live with.\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #1:  Your budget must be done on time.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Legislative changes that became effective July 1 have changed the timeline for submitting budgets.  Work back from the November 3 deadline and ensure you give yourself enough time to meet all the target dates in the approval process:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Deadline for 1st publication â€“ September 2</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for 2nd publication â€“ September 9</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for Submission of budget to County Council â€“ September 17 (no later than 45 days before the taxing unit adopts its budget)</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for County Council to review taxing unit''s budget â€“ October 17</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for public hearing â€“ October 22</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for budget adoption â€“ November 1</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline to submit budget documents to the County Auditor â€“ November 3</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #2: What''s my 2010 Estimated Assessed Value?</strong></p>\r\n<p>If you are fortunate enough to be in an area where the 2009 certified assessed value (AV) is available, multiply it by 75% for the estimated 2010 assessed value.</p>\r\n<p>If 2008 is the most recent certified assessed value available, multiply the 2008 certified AV by 75%, and then multiply that number by 75% again.  It should provide a reasonably accurate assumption.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #3: What numbers do I use for Local Option Income Tax (CAGIT, COIT, and EDIT?</strong></p>\r\n<p>For the last half of 2009, divide the 2009 certified amount by 2. (The certified amounts are located on the 2009 1782 notice and the DLGF Web site.)</p>\r\n<p>For 2010, use the 2008 certified amounts located on the DLGF Web site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #4: What are my Circuit Breaker Credits (property tax losses)?</strong></p>\r\n<p>The 2009 and 2010 cash flows should have a line item directly below the property taxes in the revenue section called "Estimated Circuit Breaker Credits."  You can use the estimates from the LSA report dated March 23, 2009.  If you think the LSA number may not be accurate for your area, we at Umbaugh can prepare a custom report based on your situation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #5:  What number do I use for State Pension Reimbursement?</strong></p>\r\n<p>The State will forward you an estimate of pension relief for 2009.  Note that the State combines police and fire pension relief into one total amount.  You will need to allocate the distribution to police and fire individually based on the percentage of 2008 actual disbursements for police and fire.</p>\r\n<p>Pension relief for 2010 is based on estimated 2009 expenditures for police and fire pension.  Pension distributions from the state are typically posted by the taxing unit on July 1 and Oct. 1.  You will need to check this in order to complete column A of Budget Form 2 accurately.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #6:  What number do I use for Three-Year Growth Appeals?</strong></p>\r\n<p>HB1001 specifies that the amount of the supplemental homestead standard deduction applied to 2009 assessed values must be added back to determine eligibility for a three-year growth appeal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>If you have additional questions about making up your budget, please contact us.</em></p>', 'In the middle of preparing your budget?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '526-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-18 19:18:21', '2011-01-18 19:18:21', '', 526, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/526-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
