(779, 5, '2011-01-18 18:07:14', '2011-01-18 18:07:14', '<p>Can local governments continue to provide the same level of service with a <strong>half billion dollar reduction</strong> in income?  That is the question local entities should ask as they plan services and budgets for the future.</p>\r\n<p>Unfortunately the $500 million reduction in statewide property tax collections projected by the Legislative Services Agency is just the reduction from the full implementation of property tax caps.  Actual revenue losses for local governments will be greater for a number of reasons, including:</p>\r\n<ul>	\r\n    <li>Expansion of the homestead exemption -- The new state 35 percent homestead exemption is reducing property tax revenues from fixed rate funds, such as cumulative capital development funds, by 10 to 25 percent</li>\r\n	<li>Reduction in income tax collections -- The State of Indiana reports that individual income tax collections declined by 23 percent for the first four months of 2009.  Your county income taxes are based upon the same taxable income as the State''s.  Assuming that revenue from local income taxes in your area will be similarly affected, that gives you less revenue for operating costs and capital expenditures.  It also gives you less revenue for property tax relief. And we know that less money for property tax relief means higher property taxes and more tax revenue lost to the property tax caps.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In addition, depending on your situation, your tax revenue may be affected by:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>trending â€“ which can go down as well as up,</li>\r\n    <li>delays in collecting and distributing property taxes, and</li>\r\n    <li>property tax delinquencies.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Strong cash reserves can help withstand these fluctuations, so managing your reserves is crucial.</p>\r\n<p>Nearly every unit of government is facing the challenge of how to do more (or even just stay the same) with less revenue.  The debate always focuses on efficiency.  But what does efficiency really mean?  It means much more than simply cutting your budget. Strategies for Government Efficiency must include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>managing revenues efficiently,</li>\r\n	<li>finding opportunities for cost efficiencies,</li>\r\n	<li>providing services efficiently through consolidation,</li>\r\n	<li>managing capital expenditures and</li>\r\n	<li>growing your tax base.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The next article in this series will cover managing revenues efficiently.  We''ll explain how some fine tuning of the mix of local income taxes could help you increase spendable tax revenue without increasing income tax rates.</p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance dealing with reduced funding, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency Part 1: Where Did Our Taxes Go?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '498-revision-7', '', '', '2011-01-18 18:07:14', '2011-01-18 18:07:14', '', 498, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/498-revision-7', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(532, 3, '2011-01-18 19:12:19', '2011-01-18 19:12:19', 'Units of local government are in the middle of setting annual budgets.  It is always a stressful time, but it may be even more stressful this year because of the number of changes to funding and revenue streams â€“ creating a host of ''unknowns'' as you prepare your financial roadmap for the coming year.  The following assumptions will help you turn those ''unknowns'' into numbers you can live with.\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #1:  Your budget must be done on time.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Legislative changes that became effective July 1 have changed the timeline for submitting budgets.  Work back from the November 3 deadline and ensure you give yourself enough time to meet all the target dates in the approval process:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Deadline for 1st publication â€“ September 2</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for 2nd publication â€“ September 9</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for Submission of budget to County Council â€“ September 17 (no later than 45 days before the taxing unit adopts its budget)</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for County Council to review taxing unit''s budget â€“ October 17</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for public hearing â€“ October 22</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline for budget adoption â€“ November 1</li>\r\n    <li>Deadline to submit budget documents to the County Auditor â€“ November 3</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #2: What''s my 2010 Estimated Assessed Value?</strong></p>\r\n<p>If you are fortunate enough to be in an area where the 2009 certified assessed value (AV) is available, multiply it by 75% for the estimated 2010 assessed value.</p>\r\n<p>If 2008 is the most recent certified assessed value available, multiply the 2008 certified AV by 75%, and then multiply that number by 75% again.  It should provide a reasonably accurate assumption.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #3: What numbers do I use for Local Option Income Tax (CAGIT, COIT, and EDIT?</strong></p>\r\n<p>For the last half of 2009, divide the 2009 certified amount by 2. (The certified amounts are located on the 2009 1782 notice and the DLGF Web site.)</p>\r\n<p>For 2010, use the 2008 certified amounts located on the DLGF Web site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #4: What are my Circuit Breaker Credits (property tax losses)?</strong></p>\r\n<p>The 2009 and 2010 cash flows should have a line item directly below the property taxes in the revenue section called "Estimated Circuit Breaker Credits."  You can use the estimates from the LSA report dated March 23, 2009.  If you think the LSA number may not be accurate for your area, we at Umbaugh can prepare a custom report based on your situation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #5:  What number do I use for State Pension Reimbursement?</strong></p>\r\n<p>The State will forward you an estimate of pension relief for 2009.  Note that the State combines police and fire pension relief into one total amount.  You will need to allocate the distribution to police and fire individually based on the percentage of 2008 actual disbursements for police and fire.</p>\r\n<p>Pension relief for 2010 is based on estimated 2009 expenditures for police and fire pension.  Pension distributions from the state are typically posted by the taxing unit on July 1 and Oct. 1.  You will need to check this in order to complete column A of Budget Form 2 accurately.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Assumption #6:  What number do I use for Three-Year Growth Appeals?</strong></p>\r\n<p>HB1001 specifies that the amount of the supplemental homestead standard deduction applied to 2009 assessed values must be added back to determine eligibility for a three-year growth appeal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>If you have additional questions about making up your budget, please contact us.</em></p>', 'In the middle of preparing your budget?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '526-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 19:12:19', '2011-01-18 19:12:19', '', 526, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/526-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
