(538, 3, '2009-06-24 19:38:02', '2009-06-24 19:38:02', 'School districts throughout Indiana may qualify for three financing tools â€“ including two that are interest free â€“ because of the federal stimulus legislation.  The  programs can mean a substantial savings and there are time and/or funding limits for the programs, so school districts need to act quickly.  The three programs are Qualified School Construction Bonds, Qualified Zone Academy Bonds and Build America Bonds.\r\n\r\n<strong>Qualified School Construction Bonds</strong> -- Indiana has received an allotment of $177,861,000 for this zero-interest funding program.  The Indiana Department of Education will make $77,861,000 available to school districts for bond issues of up to $2 million each.  The remaining $100 million will be allocated for bonds between $2 million and $10 million.  IPS qualifies for a separate allocation of $31,181,000 under this program because it is one of 100 largest school corporations in the country.\r\n\r\nAll school corporations with school renovation, repair or modernization plans may apply to the Indiana Department of Education for these funds, but if the project is subject to a referendum or petition process, it must have petition or referendum approval before the application is submitted.  The first round of applications must be received by August 3; a second round of applications is due November 13.\r\n\r\nNew construction, space additions and projects receiving a Qualified Zone Academy Bond allocation (see below) will be considered for the remaining Qualified School Construction Bonds allocation after all other qualified requests have been filled.\r\n\r\nThe Qualified School Construction Bonds are supported through federal tax credits to the bond purchaser. The maximum length of the bonds can be 14 to 15 years.\r\n\r\n<strong>Qualified Zone Academy Bonds</strong> of up to $2 million are available to Indiana schools in economically distressed areas and with curriculum designed through a school/business partnership.  To qualify for a Qualified Zone Academy Bond, at least 35 percent of students must be eligible for free or reduced lunch and the project must have a business "matching" component.  The match consists of written commitments from private entities for contributions equaling at least 10 percent of the bond proceeds; in-kind and volunteer contributions may qualify for the match. Proceeds of the bonds may be used to remodel and repair school facilities, purchase equipment, develop course materials or conduct professional development.\r\n\r\nQualified Zone Academy Bonds are interest free and the bondholder receives a tax credit. This allocation is an ongoing application process with the Indiana Department of Education.\r\n\r\nProjects funded by either Qualified School Construction Bonds or Qualified Zone Academy Bonds are required to abide by the Davis-Bacon Act requiring prevailing wages (i.e. union scale) for construction bidding.\r\n\r\nBuild America Bonds -  Unlike the other two funding mechanisms, Build America Bonds are subject to interest, and in fact, it is taxable interest rather than tax exempt.  The bonds may be sold with either the bondholder receiving the tax credit or the tax credit received as a direct payment to the school corporation. The direct payment option is more advantageous for the school corporation.  After the Build America Bonds are sold at taxable rates, on each interest payment date the school corporation (or trustee bank) receives payment from the US Treasury for 35 percent of the interest due on that date. This is the economic benefit of selling "taxable" bonds with a tax-credit feature.  In general, these bonds may be used for projects that could otherwise be financed with tax-exempt bonds, including construction, renovation, equipment purchases and real estate acquisition.\r\n\r\n<strong>Build America Bonds</strong> are expected to be available through the end of 2010. The maturity schedule on these bonds would be the 20-year normal limit prescribed by Indiana statutes.\r\n\r\nUmbaugh is assisting several clients with applications for the Qualified School Construction Bonds and structuring financings for all three of these stimulus financing tools.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions about whether one or more of these financing tools is applicable for your school renovation or construction project, please contact us.</em>', 'School Facility Projects Qualify for Special Funding Options Through Federal Stimulus Package', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'school-facility-projects-qualify-for-special-funding-options-through-federal-stimulus-package', '', '', '2011-01-25 15:43:09', '2011-01-25 15:43:09', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=538', 0, 'post', '', 0),
