(540, 3, '2011-01-18 19:38:02', '2011-01-18 19:38:02', '<p>School districts throughout Indiana may qualify for three financing tools â€“ including two that are interest free â€“ because of the federal stimulus legislation.  The  programs can mean a substantial savings and there are time and/or funding limits for the programs, so school districts need to act quickly.  The three programs are Qualified School Construction Bonds, Qualified Zone Academy Bonds and Build America Bonds.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Qualified School Construction Bonds</strong> -- Indiana has received an allotment of $177,861,000 for this zero-interest funding program.  The Indiana Department of Education will make $77,861,000 available to school districts for bond issues of up to $2 million each.  The remaining $100 million will be allocated for bonds between $2 million and $10 million.  IPS qualifies for a separate allocation of $31,181,000 under this program because it is one of 100 largest school corporations in the country. </p>\r\n<p>All school corporations with school renovation, repair or modernization plans may apply to the Indiana Department of Education for these funds, but if the project is subject to a referendum or petition process, it must have petition or referendum approval before the application is submitted.  The first round of applications must be received by August 3; a second round of applications is due November 13.</p>\r\n<p>New construction, space additions and projects receiving a Qualified Zone Academy Bond allocation (see below) will be considered for the remaining Qualified School Construction Bonds allocation after all other qualified requests have been filled. </p>\r\n<p>The Qualified School Construction Bonds are supported through federal tax credits to the bond purchaser. The maximum length of the bonds can be 14 to 15 years.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Qualified Zone Academy Bonds</strong> of up to $2 million are available to Indiana schools in economically distressed areas and with curriculum designed through a school/business partnership.  To qualify for a Qualified Zone Academy Bond, at least 35 percent of students must be eligible for free or reduced lunch and the project must have a business "matching" component.  The match consists of written commitments from private entities for contributions equaling at least 10 percent of the bond proceeds; in-kind and volunteer contributions may qualify for the match. Proceeds of the bonds may be used to remodel and repair school facilities, purchase equipment, develop course materials or conduct professional development.</p>\r\n<p>Qualified Zone Academy Bonds are interest free and the bondholder receives a tax credit. This allocation is an ongoing application process with the Indiana Department of Education. </p>\r\n<p>Projects funded by either Qualified School Construction Bonds or Qualified Zone Academy Bonds are required to abide by the Davis-Bacon Act requiring prevailing wages (i.e. union scale) for construction bidding.</p>\r\n<p>Build America Bonds -  Unlike the other two funding mechanisms, Build America Bonds are subject to interest, and in fact, it is taxable interest rather than tax exempt.  The bonds may be sold with either the bondholder receiving the tax credit or the tax credit received as a direct payment to the school corporation. The direct payment option is more advantageous for the school corporation.  After the Build America Bonds are sold at taxable rates, on each interest payment date the school corporation (or trustee bank) receives payment from the US Treasury for 35 percent of the interest due on that date. This is the economic benefit of selling "taxable" bonds with a tax-credit feature.  In general, these bonds may be used for projects that could otherwise be financed with tax-exempt bonds, including construction, renovation, equipment purchases and real estate acquisition.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Build America Bonds</strong> are expected to be available through the end of 2010. The maturity schedule on these bonds would be the 20-year normal limit prescribed by Indiana statutes. </p>\r\n<p>Umbaugh is assisting several clients with applications for the Qualified School Construction Bonds and structuring financings for all three of these stimulus financing tools.</p>\r\n<p>If you have questions about whether one or more of these financing tools is applicable for your school renovation or construction project, please contact us.</p>', 'School Facility Projects Qualify for Special Funding Options Through Federal Stimulus Package', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '538-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 19:38:02', '2011-01-18 19:38:02', '', 538, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/538-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(767, 5, '2011-01-18 18:07:20', '2011-01-18 18:07:20', '<p>Across Indiana, local governmental entities are facing a <strong>half billion dollar reduction</strong> in income due to property tax caps, and additional reductions from the expansion of the homestead exemption and lower income tax collections in a down economy.  Finding new efficiencies to operate on less income is much more than simply cutting your budget, you also must manage revenues efficiently.</p>\r\n<p>Enacting new local option income taxes (LOIT) to replace property taxes, can reduce the amount of property tax lost to the tap caps by lowering property tax levies and total tax rates.  </p>\r\n<p>As an example, the chart at left shows the effect of circuit breaker tax credits. In this sample, local governments will lose $2.5 million using current property values.  With property values increasing as in the past, the loss to circuit breaker credits is reduced to $2.2 million.  But remember that property values can trend downward as well as upward.  If property values decrease, the loss from property taxes could be greater.</p>\r\n<p>In this same scenario, if the local government enacts a .5% LOIT rate that generates $2.8 million in revenue, the loss from property tax caps is reduced to $1.1 million if the LOIT-funded property tax relief is distributed just to qualified residential properties and to $1.3 million if distributed uniformly.</p>\r\n<hr>\r\n<p>When combined with property tax relief, a new LOIT can also provide new money for public safety.  A public safety LOIT of .25% can generate an estimated $1.4 million in our example.  </p>\r\n<p>Changing the mix of local income taxes may increase total revenues available to taxing units without increasing the total income tax rate. Changes to local income taxes that may increase spendable tax revenue without increasing income tax rates include:</p>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Eliminating the local COIT Homestead Credit.  Some of these local credits were enacted before the state adopted credits, so the local credits may no longer be needed in your area.  The final chart at right shows the potential effect of eliminating COIT Homestead Credits.  The $3+ million in increased COIT revenue is partially offset by the decrease in property tax revenues as circuit breaker credits increase, but it still produces additional revenue of nearly $1.5 million.</li>\r\n        <li>Replacing a portion of a CAGIT tax, designed for property tax relief, with an EDIT tax, producing new spendable revenue.</li>\r\n        <li>Shifting LOIT credits from Homestead Credits to either qualified residential credits or uniform credits.  Oftentimes, circuit breaker tax credits benefit do not benefit the majority of homeowners.</li>\r\n        <li>Eliminating the CEDIT inventory replacement rate used for additional homestead credits in exchange for other local option income taxes.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n<p>Because many of these revenues are interdependent, finding the right mix of local income taxes will require running some "what if" scenarios for your area.  </p>\r\n<p>The next article in this series will cover opportunities for cost efficiency.</p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance dealing with reduced funding, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency Part 2: Managing Revenues Efficiently', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '494-revision-6', '', '', '2011-01-18 18:07:20', '2011-01-18 18:07:20', '', 494, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/494-revision-6', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(541, 3, '2009-06-10 19:41:18', '2009-06-10 19:41:18', 'In previous issues of Footnotes we have described a variety of solutions for funding local services, particularly when revenues are reduced.  One solution is to adjust the amount of your Local Option Income Tax (LOIT).  If you need to adjust your LOIT rate, you have a narrow window of opportunity, because, by statute, it must occur between April 1 and July 31.\r\n\r\nEven\r\n\r\nif your LOIT rate has served you well up until now, the current economic landscape may make a rate adjustment an important consideration this year for the following reasons:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Economic conditions will likely reduce revenue, putting additional pressure on your budget</li>\r\n	<li>If your revenue stream is securing debt, reduced revenue may trigger the need for a property tax backup or you may have difficulty in making debt payments.</li>\r\n	<li>Whatever the expected outcomes when you adopted LOITs prior to 2008, HEA1001 has made such a significant change your expected outcomes may not materialize.</li>\r\n	<li>The pending impact of property tax caps in 2009 and 2010 may call for restructuring local income taxes to achieve a more strategic mix â€“ or it may make you consider a new LOIT. For example, many counties have a local homestead credit funded through a LOIT. Homesteads received substantial property tax relief in HEA1001.  Restructuring local income taxes may not only be warranted, restructuring (not necessarily increasing) LOITs may actually reduce the circuit breaker impact.</li>\r\n	<li>Indiana law requires LOIT entities to review each year the method for distributing LOIT property tax relief (in particular the Property Tax Relief LOIT â€“ commonly known as Option B LOIT).  Given the changes HEA1001 will cause from 2009 to 2010, it is very likely your strategy for PTRC allocation should change as well.</li>\r\n	<li>Every governmental unit is concerned about constituents'' combined levels of property and income taxes.  A strategic approach to adjusting or restructuring LOIT will help you achieve the most efficient and effective mix for your situation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<em>If you have any questions or need assistance in determining how adjusting your LOIT rate could affect revenue and your overall tax mix, please contact us.</em>', 'Now Is the Time to Review Local Income Tax Rates', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'now-is-the-time-to-review-local-income-tax-rates', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:37:23', '2011-01-25 16:37:23', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=541', 0, 'post', '', 0),
