(543, 3, '2009-06-10 19:47:39', '2009-06-10 19:47:39', 'Revenues for many cities and towns are, or soon will be, declining from property tax caps, late or unpaid property taxes, reduction in tax base, reduction in income taxes, and reduced utility revenues. The demand for services, however, rarely decreases.\r\n\r\nIt is difficult right now for communities to know with a great degree of certainty what their near-term financial position will be and if that landscape will be sustainable.  Strategic planning is critical to address these questions.\r\n\r\nDownsizing the labor force is one of the first strategic steps that may be considered to reduce operational expenses, since labor and costs related to the workforce make up the majority of most budgets.  The impact of downsizing the workforce is more involved than just eliminating salaries or wages.  Before making any decisions, remember that downsizing has related costs as well, including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Unemployment benefits</li>\r\n	<li>Accrued time, including comp time</li>\r\n	<li>Severance pay</li>\r\n	<li>Outplacement assistance</li>\r\n	<li>Covering the responsibilities of the replaced position (including training costs and overtime)</li>\r\n	<li>Fees for a labor attorney or expanded services from local counsel</li>\r\n	<li>Health insurance â€“ employers are responsible a 65% health insurance subsidy for involuntary terminations from September 2008 through December 2009 due to new COBRA regulations, although the subsidy is later reimbursed through a payroll tax credit (watch the potential cash flow impact).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nStudy these costs before making downsizing decisions to avoid negative, unintended consequences to both the short-term and long-term cash flow.\r\n\r\nAfter evaluating carefully the financial landscape (immediate, next 24 months, and long-term), you can rationally determine if reductions in force (RIF) are needed.  Your will need to address many issues in the planning and implementation of the downsizing, including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Consider what skills will be needed in the future, how top talent can be retained, and if services need to be reduced.</li>\r\n	<li>Establish criteria for downsizing decisions.  Will it be by performance?  By seniority?  The criteria cannot be vague, and they must be defensible.</li>\r\n	<li>Develop a list of individuals identified for a possible RIF and review it to ensure the result is not discriminatory by age, race, gender, religion or disability.  Consult with your legal counsel.</li>\r\n	<li>Under the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act of 1990, workers who waive their Age Discrimination Employment Act (ADEA) rights must do so knowingly and voluntarily, and they must have 45 days to consider the agreement.</li>\r\n	<li>Have an action and communication plan for the RIF that covers when and how employees will be notified, how their work will be concluded, and security measures regarding access to facilities, equipment and computer systems.</li>\r\n	<li>A corresponding plan is needed for employees who remain.  Expect low morale and perhaps reduced productivity as people adjust to the new situation.  Have a retention strategy to minimize the possibility that remaining employees leave because they fear for their own future or feel overwhelmed by additional responsibilities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAs you evaluate cost-reduction options, consider other alternatives to a RIF such as: reducing pay with a corresponding reduction in hours, furloughs, alternative work schedules, instituting a hiring freeze, freezing pay rates, reducing benefits, offering incentives for early retirement, or not filling positions created by normal retirements.  Be sure to involve managers and employees in cost-reduction discussions.  As you evaluate work flow process, you may discover efficiencies that can minimize RIFs.\r\n\r\nThe overall goal is to deliver services to constituents as efficiently as possible.  By evaluating the financial and operational impact of all alternatives, you are poised to make the right strategic decisions.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance in evaluating the cost of downsizing, please contact us.</em>', 'The Cost of Downsizing', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'the-cost-of-downsizing', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:40:08', '2011-01-25 16:40:08', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=543', 0, 'post', '', 0),
