(547, 3, '2009-05-27 20:24:36', '2009-05-27 20:24:36', 'We knew it was coming.  But large decreases in Net Assessed Values (NAV) are still unwelcome news as these numbers are becoming available.\r\n\r\nHEA 1001, passed in the 2008 session of the Indiana General Assembly, expanded the homestead deduction in 2009 by allowing an additional 35 percent reduction.  Here''s a simple example of how that works for a home valued at $100,000:\r\n<table border="1" width="50%">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td></td>\r\n<td>2008</td>\r\n<td>2009</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Gross Assessed Value:\r\nMarket value</td>\r\n<td>$100,000</td>\r\n<td>$100,000</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Standard deduction</td>\r\n<td>$45,000</td>\r\n<td>$45,000</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Supplemental deduction</td>\r\n<td></td>\r\n<td>$19,250</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Net assessed value</td>\r\n<td>$55,000</td>\r\n<td>$35,750</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\nMultiply this decrease for every homestead in your taxing district, and you can begin to comprehend the full effect.  Based on specific studies and analyses around Indiana, taxing units have seen their NAV reduced by 10 to 25 percent, depending on their particular concentration of homesteads.\r\n\r\nIn addition, many taxing units have been significantly affected by AV reductions or negative trending from plant shut downs.\r\n\r\nNAV reduction has several impacts:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>With the new supplemental deduction, tax liability is shifted from homeowners to other taxpayer classes.</li>\r\n	<li>Revenues from rate-controlled funds such as Capital Project Funds and Cumulative Funds are reduced.</li>\r\n	<li>General Obligation bonding capacity is reduced.</li>\r\n	<li>Counties using local option income taxes to provide property tax credits to homesteads are experiencing very low property tax bills â€“ including some reduced to zero.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHow can you prepare for a significant reduction in NAV for 2009?\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Watch the 1782 Notices for possible limitations; the 2008 budget/rate advertisements may not have anticipated the actual reduction in NAV.</li>\r\n	<li>Given the shift in tax liability, you may want to consider restructuring local income taxes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf the reduction in NAV is unwelcome news for your governmental unit, call Umbaugh for information and assistance.', 'What Happened to My 2009 Net Assessed Value?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'what-happened-to-my-2009-net-assessed-value', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:41:41', '2011-01-25 16:41:41', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=547', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(548, 3, '2011-01-18 20:24:28', '2011-01-18 20:24:28', '<p>We knew it was coming.  But large decreases in Net Assessed Values (NAV) are still unwelcome news as these numbers are becoming available.</p>\n<p>HEA 1001, passed in the 2008 session of the Indiana General Assembly, expanded the homestead deduction in 2009 by allowing an additional 35 percent reduction.  Here''s a simple example of how that works for a home valued at $100,000:</p>\n\n<table width="50%" border="0">\n  <tr>\n    <td></td>\n    <td>2008</td>\n    <td>2009</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Gross Assessed Value:<br />Market value</td>\n    <td>$100,000</td>\n    <td>$100,000</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Standard deduction</td>\n    <td>$45,000</td>\n    <td>$45,000</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Supplemental deduction</td>\n    <td></td>\n    <td>$19,250</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>Net assessed value</td>\n    <td>$55,000</td>\n    <td>$35,750</td>\n  </tr>\n</table>\n\n\n\n<p>Multiply this decrease for every homestead in your taxing district, and you can begin to comprehend the full effect.  Based on specific studies and analyses around Indiana, taxing units have seen their NAV reduced by 10 to 25 percent, depending on their particular concentration of homesteads.</p>\n<p>In addition, many taxing units have been significantly affected by AV reductions or negative trending from plant shut downs.</p>\n\n<p>NAV reduction has several impacts:</p>\n<ul>\n    <li>With the new supplemental deduction, tax liability is shifted from homeowners to other taxpayer classes.</li>\n    <li>Revenues from rate-controlled funds such as Capital Project Funds and Cumulative Funds are reduced.</li>\n    <li>General Obligation bonding capacity is reduced.</li>\n    <li>Counties using local option income taxes to provide property tax credits to homesteads are experiencing very low property tax bills â€“ including some reduced to zero.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>How can you prepare for a significant reduction in NAV for 2009?</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>Watch the 1782 Notices for possible limitations; the 2008 budget/rate advertisements may not have anticipated the actual reduction in NAV.</li>\n	<li>Given the shift in tax liability, you may want to consider restructuring local income taxes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If the reduction in NAV is unwelcome news for your governmental unit, call Umbaugh for information and assistance.</p>', 'What Happened to My 2009 Net Assessed Value?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '547-revision', '', '', '2011-01-18 20:24:28', '2011-01-18 20:24:28', '', 547, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/547-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(549, 3, '2011-01-18 20:24:36', '2011-01-18 20:24:36', '<p>We knew it was coming.  But large decreases in Net Assessed Values (NAV) are still unwelcome news as these numbers are becoming available.</p>\r\n<p>HEA 1001, passed in the 2008 session of the Indiana General Assembly, expanded the homestead deduction in 2009 by allowing an additional 35 percent reduction.  Here''s a simple example of how that works for a home valued at $100,000:</p>\r\n\r\n<table width="50%" border="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td></td>\r\n    <td>2008</td>\r\n    <td>2009</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Gross Assessed Value:<br />Market value</td>\r\n    <td>$100,000</td>\r\n    <td>$100,000</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Standard deduction</td>\r\n    <td>$45,000</td>\r\n    <td>$45,000</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Supplemental deduction</td>\r\n    <td></td>\r\n    <td>$19,250</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Net assessed value</td>\r\n    <td>$55,000</td>\r\n    <td>$35,750</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Multiply this decrease for every homestead in your taxing district, and you can begin to comprehend the full effect.  Based on specific studies and analyses around Indiana, taxing units have seen their NAV reduced by 10 to 25 percent, depending on their particular concentration of homesteads.</p>\r\n<p>In addition, many taxing units have been significantly affected by AV reductions or negative trending from plant shut downs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>NAV reduction has several impacts:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>With the new supplemental deduction, tax liability is shifted from homeowners to other taxpayer classes.</li>\r\n    <li>Revenues from rate-controlled funds such as Capital Project Funds and Cumulative Funds are reduced.</li>\r\n    <li>General Obligation bonding capacity is reduced.</li>\r\n    <li>Counties using local option income taxes to provide property tax credits to homesteads are experiencing very low property tax bills â€“ including some reduced to zero.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>How can you prepare for a significant reduction in NAV for 2009?</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Watch the 1782 Notices for possible limitations; the 2008 budget/rate advertisements may not have anticipated the actual reduction in NAV.</li>\r\n	<li>Given the shift in tax liability, you may want to consider restructuring local income taxes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>If the reduction in NAV is unwelcome news for your governmental unit, call Umbaugh for information and assistance.</p>', 'What Happened to My 2009 Net Assessed Value?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '547-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 20:24:36', '2011-01-18 20:24:36', '', 547, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/547-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(550, 3, '2009-05-27 20:28:37', '2009-05-27 20:28:37', 'As the 2010 budget preparation cycle begins, it''s time to think about protecting your maximum levy.  Many taxing units face revenue reductions in 2010 when the property tax caps are fully implemented, and due to overall economic conditions and a reduced tax base from expanded homestead credits.\r\n\r\nMany of your revenue sources are subject to maximum levy limits.  At budget time, you will try to match expenditures to the reduced revenues you expect.  You may be tempted to complete budget forms and approach hearings in ways that would generate a levy below the maximum, but be very careful before you do that.\r\n\r\nUnder current rules and regulations, if you reduce maximum levy, you will not get it back in future years.  Reducing your maximum levy may have a lasting negative impact if you can not reach that levy again\r\n\r\nIn addition, because of the Circuit Breaker legislation, your budget and the property tax revenues you receive are now impacted by the budgets of other taxing units in your tax base.  You will not receive a dollar-for-dollar benefit for reducing revenue loss.\r\n\r\nYour best strategy is to complete budget forms and structure your budget cycle to protect the maximum levy.  Recognize, though, that you will not collect the full levy amount because of the property tax caps.  You will need a second budget that reflects the realistic amount you expect to collect.  The second budget will provide a realistic picture as you determine whether you will need cost reductions and/or alternative revenues.', 'Protecting Your Maximum Levy', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'protecting-your-maximum-levy', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:42:44', '2011-01-25 16:42:44', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=550', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(551, 3, '2011-01-18 20:28:35', '2011-01-18 20:28:35', '<p>As the 2010 budget preparation cycle begins, it''s time to think about protecting your maximum levy.  Many taxing units face revenue reductions in 2010 when the property tax caps are fully implemented, and due to overall economic conditions and a reduced tax base from expanded homestead credits.</p>\n<p>Many of your revenue sources are subject to maximum levy limits.  At budget time, you will try to match expenditures to the reduced revenues you expect.  You may be tempted to complete budget forms and approach hearings in ways that would generate a levy below the maximum, but be very careful before you do that.</p>\n<p>Under current rules and regulations, if you reduce maximum levy, you will not get it back in future years.  Reducing your maximum levy may have a lasting negative impact if you can not reach that levy again</p>\n<p>In addition, because of the Circuit Breaker legislation, your budget and the property tax revenues you receive are now impacted by the budgets of other taxing units in your tax base.  You will not receive a dollar-for-dollar benefit for reducing revenue loss.</p>\n<p>Your best strategy is to complete budget forms and structure your budget cycle to protect the maximum levy.  Recognize, though, that you will not collect the full levy amount because of the property tax caps.  You will need a second budget that reflects the realistic amount you expect to collect.  The second budget will provide a realistic picture as you determine whether you will need cost reductions and/or alternative revenues.</p>', 'Protecting Your Maximum Levy', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '550-revision', '', '', '2011-01-18 20:28:35', '2011-01-18 20:28:35', '', 550, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/550-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(552, 3, '2009-05-13 20:30:09', '2009-05-13 20:30:09', 'Just as it does for individuals and businesses, having money in reserve gives taxing units a sense of comfort. A fund balance is the result of receipts minus disbursements.  You have a positive fund balance when actual receipts are higher than budgeted, actual disbursements are lower than budgeted, or a combination of both.\r\n\r\nThere are a number of reasons why taxing units should maintain adequate fund balances:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Some revenues are not available when needed.  For example, it is not uncommon to experience negative cash flow when property tax disbursements are delayed. It is not possible to delay operating expenses such as payroll until you receive the property tax distribution, so more money is being paid out than is coming in. Fund balances allow you to manage cash flow shortages without depleting cash. Further, using fund balances in this way will avoid the need for short-term borrowing and the associated interest costs.</li>\r\n	<li>Fund balances can be used to respond to unforeseen events or emergencies.  Buildings or equipment may be damaged by a natural disaster or other unexpected event.  An emergency may require more employee overtime expenses than budgeted.  On the positive side, having a fund balance may allow you to take advantage of an unanticipated opportunity, such as purchasing land that becomes available.</li>\r\n	<li>Fund balances enhance your credit worthiness.  Maintaining adequate fund balances is a major factor bond rating agencies consider when they evaluate credit worthiness. Bond rating agencies generally require cash reserves equal to 15 to 20 percent of the general operating budget.  Adequate cash reserves demonstrate financial stability, enhancing the bond rating â€“ and possibly reducing the cost of issuing debt.</li>\r\n	<li>Fund balances may be used to finance capital expenditures.  Building up a fund balance over time may eliminate the need to borrow for capital expenses -- or at least reduce the amount to be borrowed, which reduces interest costs.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWhat is an "adequate" fund balance?  It is not easy to tie it to a particular amount or percentage.  Although 15 to 20 percent is a good rule of thumb, cash needs can vary among taxing units.  An adequate fund balance for your situation is one that provides optimal cash flow for operations.', 'The Importance of Adequate Fund Balances', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'the-importance-of-adequate-fund-balances', '', '', '2011-01-25 15:37:35', '2011-01-25 15:37:35', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=552', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(553, 3, '2011-01-18 20:30:06', '2011-01-18 20:30:06', '<p>Just as it does for individuals and businesses, having money in reserve gives taxing units a sense of comfort. A fund balance is the result of receipts minus disbursements.  You have a positive fund balance when actual receipts are higher than budgeted, actual disbursements are lower than budgeted, or a combination of both. </p>\n<p>There are a number of reasons why taxing units should maintain adequate fund balances:</p>\n<ol>\n	<li>Some revenues are not available when needed.  For example, it is not uncommon to experience negative cash flow when property tax disbursements are delayed. It is not possible to delay operating expenses such as payroll until you receive the property tax distribution, so more money is being paid out than is coming in. Fund balances allow you to manage cash flow shortages without depleting cash. Further, using fund balances in this way will avoid the need for short-term borrowing and the associated interest costs.</li>\n	<li>Fund balances can be used to respond to unforeseen events or emergencies.  Buildings or equipment may be damaged by a natural disaster or other unexpected event.  An emergency may require more employee overtime expenses than budgeted.  On the positive side, having a fund balance may allow you to take advantage of an unanticipated opportunity, such as purchasing land that becomes available.</li>\n	<li>Fund balances enhance your credit worthiness.  Maintaining adequate fund balances is a major factor bond rating agencies consider when they evaluate credit worthiness. Bond rating agencies generally require cash reserves equal to 15 to 20 percent of the general operating budget.  Adequate cash reserves demonstrate financial stability, enhancing the bond rating â€“ and possibly reducing the cost of issuing debt.</li>\n	<li>Fund balances may be used to finance capital expenditures.  Building up a fund balance over time may eliminate the need to borrow for capital expenses -- or at least reduce the amount to be borrowed, which reduces interest costs.  </li>\n</ol>\n<p>What is an "adequate" fund balance?  It is not easy to tie it to a particular amount or percentage.  Although 15 to 20 percent is a good rule of thumb, cash needs can vary among taxing units.  An adequate fund balance for your situation is one that provides optimal cash flow for operations.</p>', 'The Importance of Adequate Fund Balances', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '552-revision', '', '', '2011-01-18 20:30:06', '2011-01-18 20:30:06', '', 552, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/552-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
