(556, 3, '2009-05-13 21:07:17', '2009-05-13 21:07:17', 'Like all of you, we are still waiting for the most important bill of any long legislative session: the budget bill.  The budget will not be finalized until the Indiana General Assembly comes back for a special session â€“ and we don''t know yet when that will be.\r\n\r\nHowever, there were bills passed this session that will affect local governmental entities. We have summarized those bills below.  (Note that some bills are still awaiting the Governor''s signature.)\r\n\r\n<strong>SB 346</strong>:  Beginning July 1, the county auditor will receive a fee of $10 from anyone who files a sales disclosure form for the sale of real property occurring between January 1, 2004 and December 31, 2011.  The auditor will deposit 50 percent in the county sales disclosure fund and 50 percent in the assessment training and administration fund.\r\n\r\n<strong>SB 448</strong>:  This bill creates a new property tax exemption for Indiana businesses dedicated to computing, networking or data storage activities.  A business is eligible for the exemption if it invests at least $10 million in real and personal property located in Indiana after June 30, 2009, its average employee wage is at least 125 percent of the county average and the fiscal body of the county or municipality approves the exemption. The exemption applies only to the enterprise information technology equipment.\r\n\r\n<strong>HB 1071</strong>:  This bill makes the model residence deduction retroactive to 2008-pay-2009. An owner is entitled to a 50 percent deduction from the assessed value for 2008-pay-2009 for a model residence first assessed as: (1) a partially completed structure; or (2) a fully completed structure on the March 1, 2008 assessment date and still a model residence on January 1, 2009.   If the 2008-pay-2009 property taxes have already been paid, the person who paid is entitled to a refund of the overpayment.\r\n\r\n<strong>HB 1094</strong>: This bill makes a real property''s valuation date and assessment date the same beginning in 2010.  County auditors are no longer required to mail an annual information statement to each person liable for property taxes.  Form 11 and the property tax bill must include certain information concerning assessment appeals, including a notice that an appeal requires evidence of the property''s true tax value as of the assessment date.\r\n\r\n<strong>HB 1096</strong>:  This bill allows two ways to apply for a mortgage deduction: (1) the person recording the mortgage, contract or memorandum may file a statement with the county recorder for real property or the county auditor for personal property mobile homes; or (2) the person claiming the mortgage deduction may file a statement with the county auditor.\r\n\r\n<strong>HB 1198</strong>: This bill amended IC 6-1.1-1-11 and 2-7, changing the definition of "personal property," defining "nonbusiness personal property," and addressing levy replacement grants for certain school corporations affected by circuit breaker credits.\r\n\r\n<strong>HB 1230</strong>:  This bill requires that a notice published in a newspaper must also be posted on the newspaper''s Internet Web site, if the newspaper maintains one. The bill eliminates the requirement for a city to publish the ordinance setting elected city officers'' salaries. It requires all political subdivisions with the power to levy a tax and a budget of $300,000 or more to publish an annual report, if not already required under any other statute.\r\n\r\n<strong>HB 1344</strong>:  Standard Deduction:  This bill requires sales disclosure forms and property tax bills to include information about the consequences of claiming more than one standard deduction and the procedures for terminating a standard deduction. The bill establishes other filing requirements for a standard deduction.\r\n\r\n<em>Improper Deductions and Credits</em>: Tax bills for 2010, 2011 and 2012 must include a form for taxpayers to verify certain deductions and credits. The county auditor may terminate deductions or credits for 2012-pay-2013, if an individual does not verify the deductions and credits by January 1, 2013. The county auditor must provide advance notice of a proposed termination.\r\n\r\n<em>Electronic Tax Statements</em>: This bill permits a county legislative body to transmit property tax bills and related information by e-mail.  The county treasurer and county auditor are responsible for administering the program.\r\n\r\n<em>Electronic Tax Payments</em>: The bill allows automatic deductions of payments for property taxes and special assessments from any account held by a financial institution, not just from a checking account. Counties are required to distribute revenue from monthly installment property tax collections to political subdivisions at the normal semi-annual distribution date.\r\n\r\n<strong>HB 1365</strong>:  This allows an owner of permanently flooded land or property accessed by permanently flooded land and not used for agricultural purposes to petition the county assessor for a reassessment.  This is retroactive to January 1, 2008.\r\n\r\n<strong>HB 1432</strong>:  This bill requires the county auditor to distribute local income tax revenue to other taxing units no more than 10 business days after the county treasurer receives the distribution from the state.\r\n\r\nWe are grateful to the Association of Indiana Counties for their legislative summaries, which were used as a resource for this article.  If you need more details on any of these new laws, please contact us.\r\n\r\n<em>In a future issue we''ll bring you news of the budget bill''s implications shortly after the much-anticipated special session concludes.</em>', 'How Did the 2009 General Assembly Affect Your Operations?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'how-did-the-2009-general-assembly-affect-your-operations', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:45:45', '2011-01-25 16:45:45', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=556', 0, 'post', '', 0),
