(564, 3, '2009-04-15 21:48:42', '2009-04-15 21:48:42', 'As local governments continue to feel the pinch from property tax reform and shrinking income tax revenues, they are searching for alternative ways to fund the infrastructure improvements needed for residential and commercial growth.  Local development impact fees have become popular nationwide and within the state as a funding source.\r\n\r\nIndiana enabling legislation defines impact fees as "[A] monetary charge imposed on new development by a unit to defray or mitigate the capital costs of infrastructure that is required by, necessitated by, or needed to serve the new development."  The General Assembly passed the legislation in 1991 and provided guidelines and procedures for local governments to impose impact fees on new development as a way to allow growth to pay for itself.\r\n\r\nNationwide, impact fees are used to pay for schools, libraries, police/fire protection, sewer/water systems, parks and roads.  Indiana allows impact fees to be levied to pay for infrastructure improvements for parks, roads, water, sewers and flood control systems.  Currently, Fishers, Greenwood, Carmel, Noblesville and Zionsville are among the communities using impact fees in a variety of ways.\r\n\r\nCommunities considering impact fees must develop a rational nexus that establishes new growth as the driver for needed infrastructure upgrades.  Once the community establishes that growth projections will necessitate infrastructure improvements, they may move forward to develop an impact fee for specific infrastructure needs.\r\n\r\nThe community must develop a Master Plan that establishes level-of-service guidelines for the specific infrastructure.  The Master Plan includes an analysis of current community levels of service and the current and projected (10-year) deficiencies.  If the Master Plan documents that the projected deficiencies are due to growth in the community, then the rational nexus can be established, paving the way to calculate a legal impact fee.\r\n\r\nImpact fees are paid by the new development, and may be applied only to infrastructure projects made necessary by the new development.  Typically, the fees are collected when the building permit is issued, held in special accounts and disbursed as outlined in the Master Plan.\r\n\r\nWhen local governments use impact fees as an alternative funding source for new development infrastructure improvements, they avoid the problem of requiring existing residents to pay for new development.\r\n\r\nWe are eager to help governments determine the feasibility of using impact fees to meet their funding needs.  Please contact us at footnotes@umbaugh.com for more information.', 'Impact Fees:  Alternative Revenue for Infrastructure Funding', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'impact-fees-alternative-revenue-for-infrastructure-funding', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:48:50', '2011-01-25 16:48:50', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=564', 0, 'post', '', 0),
