(566, 3, '2009-04-01 21:52:26', '2009-04-01 21:52:26', '<em>Fourth article in a series.</em>\r\n\r\nAs details of the stimulus package in the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 have unfolded, it is clear that local communities will need to find local matching funds for their proposed infrastructure projects to improve bridges, roads, transit, energy and local water, wastewater and storm water systems.\r\n\r\nWe expect $4.3 billion for these types of projects in Indiana: $650 million for roads and bridges, $100 million for water quality, $80 million for public transit and $70 million for energy.  Additional dollars from competitive grants may become available.\r\n\r\nWhile you may not have finalized all the funding match details of your proposed projects, you can''t afford to wait until your projects are chosen to start planning for the match. To receive priority consideration, you will need to hit the ground running and have a good idea of the funding mix that will be available.\r\n\r\n<strong>Cash on hand</strong> -- Having cash available for the match is a quick and easy solution, but most communities do not have excess cash balances right now.  Even if you have cash on hand, you may decide that given today''s economic circumstances you''d rather hang on to cash balances to they can be available for other needs.\r\n\r\n<strong>New debt</strong> â€“ If you can''t match the federal stimulus funding with cash, your other option for a match is new debt.  In general, communities cannot simply go to the bank for a loan.  Specific procedures and requirements for issuing new debt are spelled out by various statutes.  There will be ordinances and resolutions to adopt and notices to issue, and you must allow sufficient periods of time for remonstrance, petitions or even a referendum.  Issuing debt is not a quick process, and that''s why you need to plan ahead. Get your team on board early, including an engineer, a grant administrator, a financial advisor and bond and local counsel.\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to stimulus projects, your project will only be "shovel ready" if you are prepared to be "funding match ready" as well.\r\n\r\nIn our next article, we''ll discuss the options and advantages of each of the two forms of new debt, revenue-supported bonds and property tax supported debt.', 'Finding matching funds for your stimulus projects', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'finding-matching-funds-for-your-stimulus-projects', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:51:37', '2011-01-25 16:51:37', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=566', 0, 'post', '', 0),
