(569, 3, '2009-03-18 21:53:57', '2009-03-18 21:53:57', 'The recent changes in our economy have led to lower property values and higher unemployment.  Coupled with Indiana''s new property tax caps, it is fair to say that all taxing units are facing declining revenues -- or soon will be.  For some, these shortfalls will be greater than you expect. So what''s next?  Do we deplete our fund balances?  Do we reduce spending, and, if so how?  Are new user fees a solution?  And what about changes to our local option income taxes.  Should new ones be adopted?\r\n\r\nWe all have many questions.  Unfortunately, there are no easy answers.  Over the coming months, our firm''s partners will provide their thoughts and suggestions for navigating these turbulent waters.  We will discuss the appropriate use of fund balances; how much should we reserve and when is it appropriate to draw down excess funds.  We will take an in-depth look at budget cuts, and how we can tackle this process and still provide the essential services demanded by taxpayers.  We will explore using fees to replace lost income.  What fees make sense and how can we be sure that they are fair?  We will also examine the available variety of local option income taxes.  How can we create local policy to use these taxes for additional revenue and reduce the amount of property taxes lost to the new tax caps?\r\n\r\nWe welcome your suggestions.  Let us know if there are additional topics  you would like to see discussed or if you have successes to share with others.  We are committed to helping you better serve your communities.', 'Declining tax revenues? What next?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'declining-tax-revenues-what-next', '', '', '2011-01-25 15:25:49', '2011-01-25 15:25:49', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=569', 0, 'post', '', 0),
