(756, 5, '2011-01-25 15:25:40', '2011-01-25 15:25:40', 'The recent changes in our economy have led to lower property values and higher unemployment.  Coupled with Indiana''s new property tax caps, it is fair to say that all taxing units are facing declining revenues -- or soon will be.  For some, these shortfalls will be greater than you expect. So what''s next?  Do we deplete our fund balances?  Do we reduce spending, and, if so how?  Are new user fees a solution?  And what about changes to our local option income taxes.  Should new ones be adopted?\n\nWe all have many questions.  Unfortunately, there are no easy answers.  Over the coming months, our firm''s partners will provide their thoughts and suggestions for navigating these turbulent waters.  We will discuss the appropriate use of fund balances; how much should we reserve and when is it appropriate to draw down excess funds.  We will take an in-depth look at budget cuts, and how we can tackle this process and still provide the essential services demanded by taxpayers.  We will explore using fees to replace lost income.  What fees make sense and how can we be sure that they are fair?  We will also examine the available variety of local option income taxes.  How can we create local policy to use these taxes for additional revenue and reduce the amount of property taxes lost to the new tax caps?\n\nWe welcome your suggestions.  Let us know if there are additional topics  you would like to see discussed or if you have successes to share with others.  We are committed to helping you better serve your communities.', 'Declining tax revenues? What next?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '569-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-25 15:25:40', '2011-01-25 15:25:40', '', 569, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/569-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(572, 3, '2009-03-18 21:56:57', '2009-03-18 21:56:57', 'Municipalities may consider annexation for a variety of reasons including: a desire for orderly and planned growth, achieving economic development goals or a need to extend services to individuals or businesses currently outside the municipal boundaries. Although annexation also may be considered as a way to increase revenue, the amount of new revenue your municipality may expect to generate varies depending on assessed value, population and road mileage.\r\n\r\nState revenue distributions such as gasoline and cigarette taxes are wholly or partly based on <strong>population</strong> as determined by the most recent certified census. Some distributions of gasoline taxes are also based on <strong>changes in road mileage</strong> as well as population.  Revenues generated by local option income tax (CAGIT, COIT, LOIT, and EDIT) are based on the taxing unit''s <strong>levy as a percent of total county levies</strong>; therefore, local income tax revenue will increase if the municipality''s levy increases and if there are no other offsetting levy increases by other taxing units in the county.\r\n\r\nAnnexation''s effect on property tax revenues is often misunderstood.  An increase in assessed value or population does not always translate to additional property tax revenue.  Each municipality has a limit for the amount of property tax it may levy for controlled funds.  Over the last few years, the maximum levy growth limit has been 3.7% to 4%. Generally, a municipally cannot raise taxes above the cap without obtaining authorization to levy taxes for a non-controlled fund or filing for an appeal with the DLGF to increase the maximum levy due to a qualifying reason, such as an annexation levy appeal.  A municipality may qualify for an automatic levy adjustment of up to 15% for the ensuing budget year if it annexed land on or before March 1. The percentage of increase is based on the annexed area''s <strong>assessed value</strong> rather than its population or the cost of providing services to the annexed area.\r\n\r\n<em>Umbaugh can help your municipality estimate the additional revenue potential for an annexation as well as the cost of providing services. If you have questions or need assistance, please contact us.</em>', 'Municipal Annexation: Will It Generate the Revenue You Expect?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'municipal-annexation-will-it-generate-the-revenue-you-expect', '', '', '2011-01-25 15:31:09', '2011-01-25 15:31:09', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=572', 0, 'post', '', 0),
