(581, 3, '2011-01-19 14:22:53', '2011-01-19 14:22:53', '<em>Part 1 in a series</em>\r\n\r\nThe Economic Recovery Package â€“ or stimulus package â€“ being debated in Congress right now as part of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 is not just an abstract concept to improve America''s economy.  There are several provisions in the bill that may help local communities rebuild their infrastructure â€“ bridges, roads and local water and wastewater systems.\r\n\r\nThe overall goal of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 is to create immediate and continuing jobs.  At $825 billion ($550 billion in federal spending and $275 billion in tax cuts over the next two years), the legislation would be one of the largest bills ever to move through Congress.  House and Senate leaders have pledged to have it ready for President Obama''s signature by mid-February.\r\n\r\nOf course, provisions of the Economic Recovery Package will change from day to day as the House of Representatives and Senate work to find common ground.  As the bill progresses we will keep you updated in Footnotes about the provisions relevant to local governmental entities.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, this is a good time to review infrastructure needs and potential water and wastewater projects that could benefit your community.  When infrastructure funds become available, you want to be prepared to make your case.  Umbaugh will be happy to work with you to assure your potential projects are feasible and financially sound.\r\n\r\nIn our next issue, we''ll explain how the Economic Recovery Package proposes to fund water and wastewater projects.', 'Stimulus Package May Fund Local Infrastructure', '<p><em>Part 1 in a series</em></p>\r\n<p>The Economic Recovery Package â€“ or stimulus package â€“ being debated in Congress right now as part of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 is not just an abstract concept to improve America''s economy.  There are several provisions in the bill that may help local communities rebuild their infrastructure â€“ bridges, roads and local water and wastewater systems.  </p>\r\n<p>The overall goal of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 is to create immediate and continuing jobs.  At $825 billion ($550 billion in federal spending and $275 billion in tax cuts over the next two years), the legislation would be one of the largest bills ever to move through Congress.  House and Senate leaders have pledged to have it ready for President Obama''s signature by mid-February.</p>\r\n<p>Of course, provisions of the Economic Recovery Package will change from day to day as the House of Representatives and Senate work to find common ground.  As the bill progresses we will keep you updated in Footnotes about the provisions relevant to local governmental entities.</p>\r\n<p>Meanwhile, this is a good time to review infrastructure needs and potential water and wastewater projects that could benefit your community.  When infrastructure funds become available, you want to be prepared to make your case.  Umbaugh will be happy to work with you to assure your potential projects are feasible and financially sound. </p>\r\n<p>In our next issue, we''ll explain how the Economic Recovery Package proposes to fund water and wastewater projects.</p>', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'stimulus-package-may-fund-local-infrastructure', '', '', '2011-01-21 13:15:21', '2011-01-21 13:15:21', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=581', 0, 'post', '', 0),
