(809, 5, '2011-01-19 15:19:56', '2011-01-19 15:19:56', '<p>In an increasingly service-oriented economy, public and private arenas across the country have challenged the traditional Monday-through-Friday work week as a way to enhance services and efficiency.  The same concept could work for units of local government as they face tighter budgets and rising costs for fuel and commuting.  At the same time, an alternative work week can give greater flexibility to your organization and employees and enhance customer service. </p>\r\n<p>Shorter work weeks could consist of four ten-hour days, although that model does not reduce the total number of hours worked.  </p>\r\n<p>Consider whether one of these other alternative work schedule models might be feasible for your local government:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Part-time workers â€“ Increasing the number of part-time employees could reduce salary and benefit costs.</li>\r\n	<li>Temporary workers - Hired for short-term, special projects, temporary workers are paid only when the workload justifies it.</li>\r\n	<li>Flextime â€“ Flextime gives employees flexibility, while making sure necessary hours are covered.</li>\r\n	<li>V-time â€“ V-time is a model where employees voluntarily take a portion of a year off or temporarily change to part-time.</li>\r\n	<li>Job sharing â€“ In this model two part-time employees do the work of one full-time employee.</li>\r\n	<li>Telecommuting â€“ Employees work part or all of the time outside the office.</li>\r\n	<li>Hoteling â€“ In this model, workstations are not assigned to a particular person.  It works well when a number of employees do the majority of their work outside the main office and need a workstation for only a small portion of their work week.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>As you deliberate whether an alternative work week will be beneficial, weigh potential advantages:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Will this plan generate cost savings to the local unit of government?</li>\r\n	<li>Will this plan reduce employees'' commuting costs?</li>\r\n	<li>Will this plan increase employee morale or productivity?</li>\r\n	<li>Could this plan increase customer service by extended our hours of service?</li>\r\n	<li>Could this plan enhance the use of facilities and equipment?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Similarly, you must consider possible challenges and weigh them against the advantages for your local government''s specific circumstances.  Those potential challenges include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>The change may not meet both the organization and employees'' expectations.</li>\r\n    <li>Flexible schedules may leave some employees unsupervised for periods of time.</li>\r\n    <li>Longer work hours could lead to reductions in productivity or customer service.</li>\r\n    <li>Union contracts may prohibit work schedule changes.</li>\r\n    <li>Alternative work schedules may complicate payroll.</li>\r\n    <li>Taxpayers may expect a corresponding reduction in property taxes if the alternative work schedule reduces costs.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>It is wise to consider all of these factors before determining whether an alternative work week would be beneficial for your taxing unit. In an upcoming issue of Footnotes, we will discuss optimal ways to develop and monitor an alternative work week plan.</p>', 'Considering an Alternative Work Week Schedule', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '583-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 15:19:56', '2011-01-19 15:19:56', '', 583, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/583-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
