(595, 3, '2009-11-25 15:29:01', '2009-11-25 15:29:01', '<em>First in a series</em>\r\n\r\nEvery governmental unit would love to know right now exactly what its revenue will be for the coming year -- or even two years.  Having that information would make it easy to create a realistic budget and make plans for providing services.  In the absence of a definite revenue number, we''d settle for a reasonably good estimate.  But income projections these days are wildly fluctuating as well.\r\n\r\nYour first inclination is to blame the people making the projections.  What''s the matter with these so-called experts who can''t make accurate revenue projections for the next quarter, let alone the next biennium?\r\n\r\nAs we all know, these are extraordinary times, and that is making it difficult to predict revenue, especially as local governments project the impact of the new circuit breaker property tax caps that create a hard cap on the total effective tax rate.\r\n\r\nThis article is the first in a series to help you understand why tax revenue projections are changing so rapidly and what you can do about it.\r\n\r\nRevenue projections depend on three basic elements:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Levy â€“ or the amount of property taxes that are going to be collected.</strong> Changes in levy will affect the amounts of credits from the property tax caps either positively or negatively.  If an increase in property tax levy is greater than anticipated, it will increase the tax rate and you will experience a higher loss to caps.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Tax base â€“ or the assessed value.</strong> Any change in tax base that is more than anticipated will affect the calculation of the tax rate.  If you lose more tax base than expected, you''ll have higher tax rates and a higher loss to tax caps.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Use of income taxes to reduce property tax levels.</strong> If you enacted local income taxes to offset property taxes, and those income tax collections are low because of job losses or personal income erosion, property tax rates will go up and losses to property tax caps will increase.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf any one of these three factors is in play, revenue estimates will be affected.  If all three affect your geographic area, it will make revenue estimates for your area that much more volatile.  And it will increase the chances that a statewide analysis may not fit your particular situation.\r\n\r\nThe following articles in this series will explore these three elements in more detail and outline options for anticipating the effect on your operating budgets.\r\n\r\nIf you have questions or need assistance with budget strategies and projecting revenue changes, please contact us.', 'Why are revenue projections so unpredictable?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'why-are-revenue-projections-so-unpredictable', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:36:41', '2011-01-25 18:36:41', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=595', 0, 'post', '', 0),
