(759, 5, '2011-01-24 21:27:43', '2011-01-24 21:27:43', '<p>Municipalities may consider annexation for a variety of reasons including: a desire for orderly and planned growth, achieving economic development goals or a need to extend services to individuals or businesses currently outside the municipal boundaries. Although annexation also may be considered as a way to increase revenue, the amount of new revenue your municipality may expect to generate varies depending on assessed value, population and road mileage.  </p>\r\n<p>State revenue distributions such as gasoline and cigarette taxes are wholly or partly based on <strong>population</strong> as determined by the most recent certified census. Some distributions of gasoline taxes are also based on <strong>changes in road mileage</strong> as well as population.  Revenues generated by local option income tax (CAGIT, COIT, LOIT, and EDIT) are based on the taxing unit''s <strong>levy as a percent of total county levies</strong>; therefore, local income tax revenue will increase if the municipality''s levy increases and if there are no other offsetting levy increases by other taxing units in the county. </p>\r\n<p>Annexation''s effect on property tax revenues is often misunderstood.  An increase in assessed value or population does not always translate to additional property tax revenue.  Each municipality has a limit for the amount of property tax it may levy for controlled funds.  Over the last few years, the maximum levy growth limit has been 3.7% to 4%. Generally, a municipally cannot raise taxes above the cap without obtaining authorization to levy taxes for a non-controlled fund or filing for an appeal with the DLGF to increase the maximum levy due to a qualifying reason, such as an annexation levy appeal.  A municipality may qualify for an automatic levy adjustment of up to 15% for the ensuing budget year if it annexed land on or before March 1. The percentage of increase is based on the annexed area''s <strong>assessed value</strong> rather than its population or the cost of providing services to the annexed area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Umbaugh can help your municipality estimate the additional revenue potential for an annexation as well as the cost of providing services. If you have questions or need assistance, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Municipal Annexation: Will It Generate the Revenue You Expect?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '572-revision-5', '', '', '2011-01-24 21:27:43', '2011-01-24 21:27:43', '', 572, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/572-revision-5', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(600, 3, '2009-11-11 17:46:10', '2009-11-11 17:46:10', 'Part 2\r\n\r\nRecovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds are two new financing tools created by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act â€“ commonly known as the federal stimulus program.  If you missed the general description of these bonds that allow you to finance projects at lower interest costs, please see our October 28 issue of Footnotes.\r\n\r\nBecause these two allocations are available only through the end of 2010, they are most applicable for projects that are already in the planning or approval stages.  All of the normal Indiana statutes for obtaining project approval still apply, including petition and remonstrance or referendum.\r\n\r\nBoth of these new funding mechanisms must be used in areas designated as recovery zones.  County Commissioners have the authority to define the geographic area that constitutes a recovery zone â€“ and some have chosen to designate the entire county.  County Commissioners also have the authority to decide which projects will be allowed to use the county''s allocations for these programs.  If a city or county does not use its full allocation, those allocations may revert to the state for use in other parts of Indiana.\r\n\r\nIf you have a project at the local level you think might be appropriate for Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds or Recovery Zone Facility Bonds, make your County Commissioners aware of it as soon as possible.  They will be reviewing options and making decisions about the allocation, and you want your project to be among those considered.\r\n\r\nIf your particular area has an allocation that is too low for the project (or projects) you have in mind, consider reaching out to your neighboring communities or counties and taking a regional approach to pool your allocations to achieve a project that you could not accomplish individually.\r\n\r\nAs we have all seen, interest rates and bond markets can change very quickly.  Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds may or may not be the most cost-efficient means of financing at any given time, but they should be evaluated when you assemble your project''s funding package.\r\n\r\nWe at Umbaugh can help you determine the allocation amount available for your area, evaluate what projects are appropriate for these bonds, calculate the advantages of various financing mechanisms and help you implement the most cost-effective financing to put your locality on the road to economic recovery.\r\n\r\nIf you have questions about Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds, please contact us.', 'Save Money For a Limited Time Only: Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'save-money-for-a-limited-time-only-recovery-zone-economic-development-bonds-and-recovery-zone-facility-bonds', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:39:08', '2011-01-25 18:39:08', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=600', 0, 'post', '', 0),
