(818, 5, '2011-01-19 18:08:58', '2011-01-19 18:08:58', '<p>Now is a great time to implement a system development charge for your community''s utility systems.</p>\r\n<p>A number of sewer and water utilities have implemented system development charges over the past several years.  Also known as SDCs or availability fees, system development fees provide utilities with a source of funding for future capacity-related improvement projects.  New customers pay the SDC when they connect to the utility system. The funds are then held in a separate account to reduce the amount of debt needed for future improvement projects. This scenario allows "growth to pay for growth." Utilities often face a need to expand treatment facilities because of a growing customer base. An SDC paid by new customers provides funding for the expansion with minimal impact to existing customers.</p>\r\n<p>Why is now a good time to implement an SDC?  The economy is in tatters and customer growth has significantly slowed or stopped altogether.  These negative circumstances actually make it a good time for SDC implementation.  Imposing a charge now means you are not directly  impacting many people as the economy recovers.  You are, however, setting the utility up to reap the benefits of growth once it picks up again. The recession won''t last forever; acting now will position you for the future.</p>\r\n<p>There are three general methods of calculating a SDC. The appropriate method for your utility depends upon the utility''s goals and the status and timing of planning for future improvements.  Contact us at footnotes@umbaugh.com if you have questions or need assistance with implementing an SDC.</p>', 'System Development Charges', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '608-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 18:08:58', '2011-01-19 18:08:58', '', 608, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/608-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(602, 3, '2009-11-11 17:51:35', '2009-11-11 17:51:35', '<strong>(Part 1 of a 2-part series)</strong>\r\n\r\nLocal government officials in many communities are finding it increasingly difficult to fund public safety services with existing levels of revenues and property tax.  Establishing a fire territory is an option that can provide a new revenue stream for fire services. If your community is considering establishing a fire territory, it is a good idea to begin the process now to meet the statutory deadline of March 1, 2010 to have a fire territory beginning in 2011.\r\n\r\nThe following are excerpts from an interview with James VanGorder. Chief VanGorder has been a fire chief in Zionsville since 1997 for both the volunteer fire department and the Town''s fire department. In 2007, he was appointed to his current position as the full-time fire chief of the Zionsville Fire Territory.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q:</strong> Why did the Town form a fire territory?\r\n\r\n<strong>A:</strong> It was formed primarily for two reasons: 1) to provide funding for fire operations in a rapidly growing community that was finding it increasingly difficult to pay for and maintain an acceptable level of fire services and 2) to establish mutual governance and direct oversight of the fire department.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q:</strong> What is the biggest advantage of forming a fire territory?\r\n\r\n<strong>A:</strong> It allows multiple taxing units to participate jointly in oversight and governance of the fire department.  In addition, it allows flexibility in financing operations, governance and long-range planning.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q:</strong> What was your experience with having other taxing units come on board with the fire territory and what advice would you give on this topic?\r\n\r\n<strong>A:</strong> The key is open communication.  Early in the process, the Town and Township officials met to identify concerns, and we worked together as a group to develop creative ways to resolve the issues.  Fortunately, the fire territory law is broad, which allows a great deal of flexibility in structuring the fire territory. A common misconception is that when a fire territory is formed, fire departments are disbanded and volunteer fire contracts are eliminated.  This simply is not true.  The current structure and contractual agreements can remain the same.\r\n\r\nUmbaugh has assisted many local entities with feasibility studies to determine if a fire territory would be advantageous.  We understand the nuances, government levy issues, tips to make a new arrangement successful and pitfalls to avoid.  If you have questions or need assistance, please contact us.', 'Don''t Burn Through The Deadline To Establish A Fire Territory For 2011: Key Perspectives From A Fire Chief', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'don%e2%80%99t-burn-through-the-deadline-to-establish-a-fire-territory-for-2011-2', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:33:46', '2011-01-25 18:33:46', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=602', 0, 'post', '', 0),
