        	<ul>\n                    <li>The current and proposed square footage of school building space per student;</li>\n                    <li>Enrollment patterns within the school corporation; and</li>\n                    <li>The age and condition of the current school facilities.</li>\n				</ul>\n             </li>\n			<li><strong>A political subdivision itself may introduce a public question on the ballot without a taxpayer petition under certain circumstances.</strong></li>\n			<li><strong>An elected or appointed official of a political subdivision may personally advocate for or against a position on the petition or remonstrance or a local public question as long as it is not done using public funds.</strong></li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A student may use school equipment or facilities to report or editorialize about a local public question as part of news coverage of the referendum by student newspaper or broadcast.</p>\n<p>The above information is in part based upon a memo of the DLGF Commissioner dated August 7, 2009.</p>\n<p>Umbaugh is currently working with four school districts that have referenda on the November 3 ballot: Batesville Community School Corporation, Southwest Dubois County School Corporation, Tell City-Troy Township School Corporation and the MSD of Perry Township.</p>\n<p>If you have questions or need assistance with financing a controlled project, please contact us.</p>', 'CHANGES TO INDIANA LAW AFFECT APPROVAL PROCESS FOR  SCHOOL AND LOCAL GOVERNMENT BUILDING PROJECTS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '610-revision', '', '', '2011-01-19 18:54:56', '2011-01-19 18:54:56', '', 610, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/610-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(612, 3, '2009-10-28 19:13:26', '2009-10-28 19:13:26', 'At the risk of sounding like a late-night TV commercial, let me introduce you to a limited-time offer that may have financial benefits for your area.  Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds are two new financing tools created by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act â€“ commonly known as the federal stimulus program.\r\n\r\nThese two financing mechanisms do not provide money for projects, but they may allow you to finance projects at lower interest costs.\r\n\r\nThe U.S. Treasury allocated $313 million in Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and $469 million in Recovery Zone Facility Bonds for Indiana.  They further made allocations to large cities (Indianapolis, Evansville, Fort Wayne and South Bend) and to each county based on impact from the economic down turn as measured by unemployment and foreclosure rates, among other factors.  Eighty nine of Indiana''s 92 counties qualify for these programs and received allocations for each type of financing from the U.S. Treasury.\r\n\r\nRecovery Zone Economic Development Bonds are for public projects.  These bonds are sold at taxable interest rates, but 45% of the interest will be paid by a subsidy from the U.S. Treasury, and 55% is paid by the local governmental unit issuing the bonds.  In the current market, this is a lower effective rate than tax-exempt financing.  They are similar to Build America Bonds, but the Build America Bond interest subsidy is only 35%.\r\n\r\nRecovery Zone Facility Bonds are for private projects.  They are similar to the Industrial Revenue Bonds (IRBs) in that they give private companies access to tax-exempt financing rates.  The main difference from traditional IRBs is that the types of entities eligible for this type of financing is greatly expanded. The most likely use for Recovery Zone Facility Bonds is to finance building or renovating private facilities that will create new jobs.  The local governmental entity is the issuer of the bonds, but the private company provides the security on the bonds.\r\n\r\nIn out next newsletter, we will go into more depth as to how or when these new financing tools should be considered.  In the meantime, if you need information on what allocations your County received or; if you have questions about the use Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds, please contact us.', 'Save Money For a Limited Time Only: Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'save-money-for-a-limited-time-only-recovery-zone-economic-development-bonds-and-recovery-zone-facility-bonds-2', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:46:21', '2011-01-25 18:46:21', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=612', 0, 'post', '', 0),
