(616, 3, '2009-10-14 19:28:47', '2009-10-14 19:28:47', 'Indiana Office of Community and Rural Affairs (OCRA) is proposing grant funding for numerous types of projects in counties declared eligible for Federal Disaster Funding.\r\n\r\nEighty two of Indiana''s 92 counties were federally declared disaster areas in 2008 due to severe flooding in northern Indiana (DR-1740) early in the year, tornados and severe flooding in late May and early June (DR-1766), and severe flooding in northern Indiana from the remnants of Hurricane Ike in early September (DR-1975).  The state experienced an estimated $1.9 billion in damage to public infrastructure, housing and farmland.  Damage to Indiana''s infrastructure alone is estimated at $325 million.\r\n\r\nThe State of Indiana recently released a "substantial amendment" to its Action Plan for Disaster Recovery.  The amendment will guide the distribution of an additional $253,340,079 of Community Development Block Grant Disaster Recovery Funding to meet housing, infrastructure, business, public service, public facility and other needs in the 82 affected counties.\r\n\r\nIndiana Office of Community and Rural Affairs is proposing grant funding for numerous types of projects in 2010 to counties declared eligible for Federal Disaster Funding.\r\n\r\nWhile many of the details are still unknown, the categories most interesting to units of local government are an additional:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Nearly $25 million for stormwater drainage projects ($1 million maximum grant)</li>\r\n	<li>$50 million for water and wastewater projects (SRF/USDA-RD approved  projects)</li>\r\n	<li>$30 million for water and wastewater small projects ($1 million maximum grant)</li>\r\n	<li>$25 million for dam/levee improvements (Distributed at OCRA''s discretion)</li>\r\n	<li>$15 million for waterway debris removal</li>\r\n	<li>$20 million for community economic development (case-by-case determination)</li>\r\n	<li>$6 million for clearance/demolition ($500,000 maximum grant)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnother $13 million is available for floodplain/green space acquisition, $5 million for community revitalization, $23 million for owner-occupied rehabilitation and $28 million for multi-family rental housing.\r\n\r\nIf your area is still struggling to recover from 2008 weather events, this is your opportunity to request grant funding.  Eligible projects will either have sustained damage or be vital to the economic recovery of the area.\r\n\r\nEach project category area has its own priorities and award limits.  In many cases grant applications will be accepted and awards made until funding is no longer available ("non-competitive").  Other categories will award grants in competitive funding rounds.\r\n\r\nMore information from OCRA is available at www.ocra.IN.gov or 800-824-2476.\r\n\r\nIf you have projects and need assistance, please contact us.', 'Additional Disaster Recovery Funding Announced for Areas Affected by 2008 Flooding', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'additional-disaster-recovery-funding-announced-for-areas-affected-by-2008-flooding', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:50:32', '2011-01-25 18:50:32', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=616', 0, 'post', '', 0),
