(618, 3, '2009-09-30 19:42:50', '2009-09-30 19:42:50', '<div>\r\n<p id="internal-source-marker_0.7233244639355689"><em>Part 7 in a series</em></p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nAll organizations achieve excellence by satisfying three core expectations: meeting customer needs, providing quality products and services, and employing efficient operations.  The best tools to meet such expectations are strategic planning, performance measurement and process improvement.\r\n\r\nA process is how work gets accomplished.  As service demands change, the processes that produce those services must also evolve.  Without constant re-evaluation, processes stagnate â€“ resulting in increased costs, poor quality, inefficient service delivery and constituent dissatisfaction.\r\n\r\nSeveral widely used methods can improve your processes, including: Business Process Reengineering, Six Sigma, Lean, and Total Quality Management. But don''t let the buzz-word terminology turn you off, because all these programs have common steps that can be used by your governmental unit in any process-improvement effort.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Plan and organize</strong> â€“ Identify a leader to support and guide the effort, charter a team to perform the evaluation and make recommendations, set a mission, define the project scope, and analyze customer needs and concerns.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Map</strong> â€“ Plot out detailed flow charts of all current process steps and requirements.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Identify and Analyze</strong> â€“ Look at time constraints and quality problems, evaluate structural process issues, and analyze individual process steps.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Recommend</strong> â€“ Outline all potential opportunities for improvement.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Implement</strong> â€“ Meet with stakeholders to review draft recommendations, assign responsibility for specific actions, implement improvements, and ensure results by gathering data and feedback and checking progress.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nGiven the number of hours and resources allocated to producing services, organizations typically put little thought into the underlying process, but the efficiency of the process determines the success of meeting constituents'' needs and expectations.  Simply put, process improvement is an excellent tool for optimizing your efficiency.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance with process improvement or strategic planning, Umbaugh partners with Sikich, a leading provider of professional services in the Midwest serving government, business and not-for-profit organizations. Please contact us.<em></em></em>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: The Process-Oriented Organization', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'strategies-for-government-efficiency-the-process-oriented-organization', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:55:44', '2011-01-25 18:55:44', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=618', 0, 'post', '', 0),
