(622, 3, '2011-01-19 19:45:27', '2011-01-19 19:45:27', '<p>New economic data suggests that the nearly two-year recession the country has been weathering is now over according to the Federal government.  This is good news, but most experts acknowledge that times will continue to be financially challenging for the foreseeable future.  In fact, it is likely that we will continue to see companies consolidating or closing facilities -- or declaring bankruptcy in some instances.</p>\n<p>In many communities across the state, municipal utilities provide service to large customers that generate a significant amount of the utility''s annual revenues.  Keep in mind that "large" and "significant" are relative terms.  A $20,000-per-year customer means more to a utility with annual revenues of $100,000 than it does to a utility with annual revenues of $10 million.  Situations where the loss of a large customer would seriously impact the ongoing ability of the utility to meet its financial requirements need to be monitored closely and proactively managed.  Talk to company representatives often so you are not surprised by a sudden reduction or departure.  In some cases, the utility may be able to employ strategies to assist the large customer.  If your customer has already made the difficult decision to leave, it''s too late to analyze potential options, so keep your lines of communication open and active.</p>\n<p>If you need assistance with analyzing options to help retain a large customer or if you are dealing with the impact of a recent departure of a major industry, please contact us.</p>', 'Monitor the Economic Health of Your Large Utility Customers', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '621-revision', '', '', '2011-01-19 19:45:27', '2011-01-19 19:45:27', '', 621, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/621-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(623, 3, '2009-09-16 20:02:53', '2009-09-16 20:02:53', 'Just like a child waiting for a promised gift to arrive in the mail, school districts and local governments in parts of Indiana are still anxiously awaiting semiannual property tax receipts that traditionally arrive in June and December.  Even worse, entities in some parts of the state know the distributions are still far away because tax bills haven''t been sent to taxpayers yet.  Meanwhile, payrolls and utilities must still be paid and services must still be provided.\r\n\r\nUnless you can draw on cash reserves indefinitely, you will have to borrow to meet cash flow needs using temporary loan warrants.  Borrowing doesn''t reflect badly on your financial management.  It is a nearly universal necessity in parts of the state where tax collections have been delayed.\r\n\r\nA warrant is specific to a particular fund.  Schools normally borrow against the collections for the General Fund, the Transportation Fund, the Capital Projects Fund, the Debt Service and Pension Debt Service Fund.  The principal of the warrant is payable from the designated fund, but schools have the option to pay the interest from the Debt Service Fund.  The option of paying interest from a Debt Service fund is not available to other governmental entities.  However, libraries, fire departments, cities and other local governmental units are experiencing the same need for tax anticipation warrants.\r\n\r\nState law limits the principal of a warrant to 80 percent of the semiannual property tax distribution that is dedicated to paying the warrant.  As long as 80 percent of property taxes are collected, the warrant holder will be repaid.  Although achieving 80 percent of collections is somewhat of a concern in these challenging times, historically it is very rare for collections to be less than 90 percent.  Additional federal guidelines apply to the warrant amounts, and you will need to apply both federal and state tests before establishing the amount for your warrant.\r\n\r\nThe credit analysis for a tax anticipation warrant will include current financial information, the assessed valuation in your taxing district, the percentage of property tax collections in recent years, and a list of the largest current taxpayers in the taxing district.  Growth projections and fund balances are not relevant since the warrant is a first lien on the distribution of property taxes or state aid distributions.\r\n\r\nSince state law has removed school districts'' General Funds from the local property tax levy, current warrants for school General Funds are issued against state tuition support distributions and are subject to the same 80 percent limitation.\r\n\r\nA warrant must mature in the same year it was issued. If property tax collections will be later than December 31, it will be necessary to issue warrants initially with a December 31 maturity, and refund them later with a new maturity date.\r\n\r\nIf your unit of government needs tax anticipation warrants to fulfill financial obligations before tax collections come in, Umbaugh can help with:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Preparing cash flow projections</li>\r\n	<li>Preparing a term sheet to explain all loan terms in easily understood language</li>\r\n	<li>Preparing a bid form</li>\r\n	<li>Sending the documents above to potential purchasers, along with legal documents prepared by bond counsel</li>\r\n	<li>Coordinating and hosting a competitive sale</li>\r\n	<li>Summarizing the bid results and determining the lowest bidder</li>\r\n	<li>Distributing the after-sale letter with wire transfer and closing instructions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<em>If you need help with a tax anticipation warrant, please contact us.</em>', 'Tax Anticipation Warrants Nearly A Necessity With Late Property Tax Distributions', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'tax-anticipation-warrants-nearly-a-necessity-with-late-property-tax-distributions', '', '', '2011-01-25 19:09:15', '2011-01-25 19:09:15', '', 0, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/?p=623', 0, 'post', '', 0),
