(828, 5, '2011-01-19 20:07:20', '2011-01-19 20:07:20', '<p>"History is a vast early warning system."  Unfortunately, we have not heeded Norman Cousins'' advice when it comes to the economy, failing to learn from the "Internet bubble burst" to prevent the current recession.  Our current situation was caused in part by unsustainable levels of growth, fueled by unrealistic speculation. Housing soared and the market roaredâ€”causing some to become accustomed to large tax collections or reliant on one-time revenue sources.</p>\r\n<p>It is now clear that much of the growth was too good to be true.  Now that growth has slowed, focusing solely on immediate cost-cutting measures or strategies is short sighted.  Today''s trials can become a positive learning experience if they lead you to ask truly critical questions such as, "What do we want this organization to look like in the future?" This is an opportune time to initiate strategic planning and evaluate processes.  Strategic planning focuses the organization on its destination, while process improvement helps determine the most efficient route.</p>\r\n<p>Tough decisions can and will be made, but the approach to the decision-making process is as important as the results.  When you implement strategic planning, you look back and forward to achieve meaningful organizational change.  Strategic planning helps focus a government on its most productive activities by determining actions that will best address challenges or policy issues.  Only by engaging in a rational planning-based process will you know what to keep, what to reduce, what to outsource, or what to eliminate while maintaining the critical services and community values of your stakeholders.  </p>\r\n<p>Most importantly, craft a vision of your ideal organization by assembling a group of participants who both provide the diverse opinions to understand the issues confronting the organization as well as have the authority and support to effectively apply the necessary resources to implement the initiatives they define.  These stakeholders should then explore history, observe current trends and issues, and brainstorm about the future.   Once a word picture of that "ideal" has been captured, the task is to answer: "What elements of the organization are permanent and which are flexible?"    </p>\r\n<p>Despite the current crisis environment, we encourage you to attempt to do more than survive the next budget cycle.  Be cognizant of the past, but even more so, look forward for your vision and around you at your resources and options to ensure government''s success today and in the future.</p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance with strategic planning, Umbaugh partners with Sikich, a leading provider of professional services in the Midwest serving government, business and not-for-profit organizations. Please contact us.</em></p>', 'Strategic Strategies for Government Efficiency: Strategic Planning', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '625-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 20:07:20', '2011-01-19 20:07:20', '', 625, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/625-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
