(663, 3, '2011-01-11 20:44:08', '2011-01-11 20:44:08', '<h2>Our Services for Local Government</h2>\r\n                    <p><strong>Financial Management</strong> - No one who works in local government would say that financial management is "simple."   Your constituents never think about how time consuming your day-to-day tasks are.  Umbaugh can help you with:</p>\r\n                        <ul class="left">\r\n                            <li>Audit Preparation</li>\r\n                            <li>CAFR Preparation</li>\r\n                            <li>Financial Reporting</li>\r\n                            <li>Tax Revenue Analysis and Management</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        \r\n                        <ul class="right">\r\n                            <li>Budget Preparation Assistance</li>\r\n                            <li>Comprehensive Financial Planning</li>\r\n                            <li>GASB 34 Compliance</li>\r\n                            <li>User Fee Development</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n\r\n	                    <p>As you look for every <strong>cost savings and efficiency</strong>, we can also provide:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>Consolidation Planning and Implementation</li>\r\n                                <li>Negotiating Inter-Governmental Agreements</li>\r\n                                <li>Performance Management Studies</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n\r\n	                    <p>If you are considering a new accounting system, let us relieve your nightmares and worry of system selection (What if it doesn''t work?  What if we lose our data?) with:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>Accounting Systems Consulting</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                    \r\n	                    <p><strong>Capital Planning</strong> - Every unit of government has projects that need to be done â€“ and equipment that needs to be upgraded or replaced.  It''s tempting to defer projects and delay expenses, but that could catch up to you someday with a big bill â€“ or a service failure.  We all know it''s better to plan ahead.  Umbaugh can help you with:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>Debt Management Studies</li>\r\n                                <li>Project Planning and Financial Development</li>\r\n                                <li>Refinancing of Existing Debt</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            \r\n                            <ul class="right">\r\n                                <li>Long-Range Capital Planning and Implementation</li>\r\n                                <li>Developing and Evaluating Funding Alternatives</li>\r\n                                <li>Financial Presentations to Elected Officials and the Public</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                    \r\n	                    <p><strong>Bond Issuance</strong> - Bond issues are not something you do every day, and you''ve got to get it right. The stakes are literally too high to risk a mistake or miss an opportunity to save. Since Umbaugh is an independent advisor, our only priority is doing what''s best for the local governments we represent. We can provide:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>Official Statements and Bond Sale Preparations</li>\r\n                                <li>Presentations to Bond Ratings Agencies</li>\r\n                                <li>Evaluation of Bond Insurance Proposals</li>\r\n                                <li>Competitive Bond Sales and Electronic Bidding Services</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            \r\n                            <ul class="right">\r\n                                <li>Negotiated Bond Sales and Private Placements</li>\r\n                                <li>Coordination of Bond Closings</li>\r\n                                <li>Assistance to the Trustee Bank</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                    \r\n	                    <p><strong>Post Issuance</strong> - Unfortunately, the paperwork does not go away after the bonds are sold.  You as the bond issuer have a great deal of responsibility for reporting and compliance, at a time when you''d much rather be paying attention to your bond-funded project.  Umbaugh can take those worries off your plate as well with:</p>\r\n                            <ul class="left">\r\n                                <li>In-Progress Construction Reports</li>\r\n                                <li>Arbitrage Rebate Calculations</li>\r\n                                <li>Continuing Disclosure Filings</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            \r\n                            <ul class="right">\r\n                                <li>Post Issuance Compliance</li>\r\n                                <li>Escrow Verifications</li>\r\n                                <li>Parity Reports</li>\r\n                            </ul>', 'Local Governments', 'Operating a local governmental unit always has challenges and opportunities. You may be looking for new efficiencies, projecting changes in tax revenue, finding new revenue sources, working on long-range planning, funding buildings and improvements, or structuring the most advantageous economic development package. Our years of experience in helping others in similar situations make us uniquely qualified to help you today -- and with tomorrow''s challenges.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '206-revision-15', '', '', '2011-01-11 20:44:08', '2011-01-11 20:44:08', '', 206, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/206-revision-15', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(671, 1, '2011-01-21 10:43:30', '2011-01-21 10:43:30', '<p>Wind farms are a relatively new form of economic development with unique financial considerations for both private and public entities. For private land owners, lease terms and liability protection are important factors to consider. For public entities, other aspects rise to the top of the priority list.</p>\r\n<p>Every project is unique. When deciding whether to pursue wind farms in your community, your top priorities should be protecting the infrastructure (both now and in the future), creating economic development agreements to create "win-win" scenarios, and ensuring open communication -- both internally as well as to the public.</p>\r\n<p>If you are considering wind turbines for your area, the tax abatement, tax base and tax rate implications will be essential elements. There are significant tax breaks associated with wind farms in Michigan. These projects are subject to Industrial Facility Tax, but may be partially exempt from some taxing authorities such as school districts. Investment in wind farm technology is primarily considered to be personal property. It is therefore necessary to work closely with company representatives and Michigan Economic Development Corporation for appropriate treatment.</p>\r\n<p>Because the construction of wind turbines requires extensive use of road and bridges, infrastructure protection is an important consideration.  A road use agreement is critical to protect the municipality''s infrastructure and define liability and traffic flow during construction. Key components of a road use agreement include a detailed map of roads, bridges and intersections to be used for construction and a process to determine existing conditions and identify county-regulated drains that may be affected.</p>\r\n<p>The municipality will need to reach an economic development agreement with the wind farm developer. Wind farms may take significant acreage and therefore reduce or eliminate opportunities for other economic development to occur within the project area. You will want to be compensated for this to generate funds to promote, encourage and create other types of economic development in other areas of the county.  The amount and timing of these payments need to be negotiated and defined.  Payments should not be considered payments in lieu of taxes or any type of "property tax;" they should be treated as miscellaneous revenue or for a specific use.  Your agreement may allocate these payments to schools, libraries, towns, fire departments or other units.</p>\r\n<p>You will also need to have a decommissioning plan in place prior to construction to protect the county and its constituents. The plan should include provisions and details for removal of towers, footings and access roads and returning the area to as near the same condition as possible if the wind generation project is terminated. Financial assurances need to be covered, and you should establish a schedule to review the decommissioning plan periodically.</p>\r\n<p>While alternative energy, and specifically wind farm development, seems to be gaining momentum; there are certainly very important financial aspects to consider for your community.  If Umbaugh''s experience in working through these issues would be helpful in your community, or if you have questions, please contact us.</p>', 'Alternative Energy Sources as Economic Development', 'Wind farms are a relatively new form of economic development with unique financial considerations for both private and public entities. For private land owners, lease terms and liability protection are important factors to consider. For public entities, other aspects rise to the top of the priority list.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '638-revision-5', '', '', '2011-01-21 10:43:30', '2011-01-21 10:43:30', '', 638, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/638-revision-5', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(672, 1, '2011-01-19 20:13:44', '2011-01-19 20:13:44', '<p><strong>Part 2 in a series</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The huge Economic Recovery Package working its way through Congress may provide sorely needed funding to upgrade your local water and wastewater systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As proposed, approximately $11.8 billion or nearly 20% of the infrastructure investment portion of the Economic Recovery Package is targeted for community water and wastewater infrastructure. Of that amount:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>$6 billion is slated for wastewater projects funded through the Clean Water State Revolving Fund (CWSRF)</li>\r\n	<li>$2 billion is allotted for drinking water projects funded through the Drinking Water State Revolving Fund, and </li>\r\n	<li>$3.8 billion is budgeted for rural water and wastewater systems. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Half of the $6 billion for wastewater projects would be disbursed by the states as loans. States would be required to use the other half to provide assistance "in the form of additional subsidization, including forgiveness of principal, negative interest loans, and grants, to municipalities (as defined in section 502 of such Act) for projects that are included on the State''s priority list established under section 603(g)."  The majority of the grant money would be for projects "to benefit municipalities that meet affordability criteria as determined by the Governor of the State," so we don''t know yet how that would be defined in Indiana.  The remainder of the grant money would be available for projects to mitigate storm water runoff or to achieve water efficiency, energy efficiency or environmentally sensitive project planning.</p>\r\n \r\n<p>The overall goals of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 are immediate and continuing job creation.  At $825 billion ($550 billion in federal spending and $275 billion in tax cuts over the next two years), the legislation would be one of the largest bills ever to move through Congress.  House and Senate leaders have pledged to have it ready for President Obama''s signature by mid-February.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course, provisions of the Economic Recovery Package are changing from day to day as the House of Representatives and Senate work to find common ground.  We will keep you updated in Footnotes as the bill progresses.  In our next issue, we''ll explain how the stimulus package may affect the municipal bond market.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Umbaugh will be happy to work with you to structure potential projects that may qualify for stimulus package funding.</p>', 'What The Stimulus Package Could Mean For Local Water And Wastewater Projects', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '629-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 20:13:44', '2011-01-19 20:13:44', '', 629, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/629-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(673, 1, '2011-01-19 20:09:16', '2011-01-19 20:09:16', '<p>The first four parts of this series have covered how to structure sufficient revenue from your existing tax base to continue to provide the services your constituents expect.  This article goes beyond that to examine increasing your tax base.  </p>\r\n<p>Growth in assessed value minimizes total property tax rates and the revenue losses from associated with the new tax caps.  Growth in your employment base helps offset the natural swings in local income tax revenues that result from shifts in the economy.  Growth of investment and employment are both necessary to provide a stable source of tax revenue, and economic development can accomplish both.</p>\r\n<p>No one should ever "give away the farm" in attracting economic development.  Most localities have been smart about matching their incentives to the potential benefits that the economic development can deliver.  But in the current economic environment, the incentives must be strategic and precise to produce the economic benefit you''re hoping for.</p>\r\n<p>There is no "one size fits all" formula to follow.  Instead, you should develop flexible incentive guidelines that consider:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>the level of investment,</li>\r\n	<li>the probable term of investment,</li>\r\n	<li>the number of jobs created and</li>\r\n	<li>the value of the payrolls created or retained.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Use a tiered approach to tax abatements so you offer longer abatement periods only to those projects with largest investments, more jobs and higher payrolls.   Use that same tiered approach to determine the amount of the investment that will qualify for abatement.</p>\r\n<p>You can apply a tiered approach to the use of tax increment financing (TIF) as well:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Limit TIF use to those projects with larger investments, more jobs and higher payrolls. </li>\r\n	<li>Limit the amount of investment captured by the TIF allocation area.</li>\r\n	<li>Consider using TIF for only those projects that develop infrastructure capacity that can attract additional future investment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The benefits of economic development don''t happen overnight.  It takes time to produce the desired results, but the long-term benefits of increased revenue from income and property taxes are clear.  With the new restrictions on tax increment allocation areas brought by HEA 1001 in 2008 and challenging economic conditions, the old ways of approaching economic development no longer apply.  But if you are smart and strategic, the economic benefits of minimizing the impact of property tax caps, keeping local services funded and keeping property taxes low are worth the effort.</p>\r\n<p>Remember that one of the most important factors in business location decisions is quality of life.  If reductions in your traditional revenue sources are causing you to consider cutting back services, remember that if cuts adversely affect the quality of life too severely, you will hurt your competitive position in economic development opportunities.   </p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance with structuring economic development incentives, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: Grow Your Tax Base', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '627-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 20:09:16', '2011-01-19 20:09:16', '', 627, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/627-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
