(682, 5, '2011-01-25 18:19:15', '2011-01-25 18:19:15', 'In a previous issue of Footnotes, we discussed factors to consider as you determine whether to implement alternative work schedules for your unit of local government.  Today''s article reviews additional factors to think about once you''ve decided to implement an alternative work schedule.\r\n\r\nThe first step in deciding which schedule best fits your taxing unit is to clearly identify your needs and the goals you wish to attain from the change.  Identify the essential services and hours of operation, performance standards, financial impact for your governmental unit and employees, and the impact on customer/constituent service.\r\n\r\nAs you determine the financial impact of the alternative work schedule, consider the following considerations:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Have a clear understanding of your cost structure.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Are the majority of your costs fixed or variable?</li>\r\n	<li>Will an alternative schedule create an opportunity for utility savings?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Determine how costs will vary for compressed schedules and traditional schedules.</li>\r\n	<li>Decide if potential savings may be mitigated if your taxing unit has already implemented a plan for energy savings.</li>\r\n	<li>Determine if the new schedule will affect cash flow and potentially reduce interest income.</li>\r\n	<li>Assess the financial landscape under HEA 1001 and potential circuit breaker credits.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIt is vital to involve both management and employees in the planning and decision making.  Solicit new ideas and feedback in a variety of ways, including surveys.  Surveys can help you determine if employees will save money from a reduced commute or if the alternate work schedule will create child-care or dependent-care issues.\r\n\r\nThe new hours should be perceived as an enhancement and allow for increased access to services for customers and constituents.  Develop a plan to communicate the new schedules to let constituents and customers take advantage of the added convenience.\r\n\r\nWhen developing your alternative work schedule, you''ll want a consistent structure.  Consider the following questions:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Does the new schedule meet applicable wage and hour laws?</li>\r\n	<li>Are there any conflicts with bargaining unit agreements?</li>\r\n	<li>Will the schedule be optional or mandatory?</li>\r\n	<li>How will the schedule impact paid holidays and paid leave?</li>\r\n	<li>How will you provide equity for employees on the alternative and traditional schedules?</li>\r\n	<li>Who will be eligible for the alternative work schedule and who makes that determination?</li>\r\n	<li>What kind of training will be needed for supervisors and employees?</li>\r\n	<li>Will we need different record keeping requirements and evaluation methods?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nContinuous monitoring is critical to the success of the new schedule and will help ensure programs are aligned with your goals and expectations.\r\n\r\nWe are all waiting to see what the future will bring.  Additional economic and legislative changes could increase the need to adapt you service delivery model.  Additional economic challenges could reduce property and income tax revenues.  Services and structure of county government could change dramatically as ideas from the Kernan/Shepard report are implemented.  All of these changes may make alternative work schedules a desirable strategy to adjust to new ways of doing business.', 'Ways to Develop and Monitor an Alternative Work Schedule', '<p>In a previous issue of Footnotes, we discussed factors to consider as you determine whether to implement alternative work schedules for your unit of local government.  Today''s article reviews additional factors to think about once you''ve decided to implement an alternative work schedule.</p>\r\n<p>The first step in deciding which schedule best fits your taxing unit is to clearly identify your needs and the goals you wish to attain from the change.  Identify the essential services and hours of operation, performance standards, financial impact for your governmental unit and employees, and the impact on customer/constituent service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As you determine the financial impact of the alternative work schedule, consider the following considerations:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Have a clear understanding of your cost structure.\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>Are the majority of your costs fixed or variable?</li>\r\n			<li>Will an alternative schedule create an opportunity for utility savings?</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n	<li>Determine how costs will vary for compressed schedules and traditional schedules.</li>\r\n	<li>Decide if potential savings may be mitigated if your taxing unit has already implemented a plan for energy savings.</li>\r\n	<li>Determine if the new schedule will affect cash flow and potentially reduce interest income.</li>\r\n	<li>Assess the financial landscape under HEA 1001 and potential circuit breaker credits.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>It is vital to involve both management and employees in the planning and decision making.  Solicit new ideas and feedback in a variety of ways, including surveys.  Surveys can help you determine if employees will save money from a reduced commute or if the alternate work schedule will create child-care or dependent-care issues.</p>\r\n<p>The new hours should be perceived as an enhancement and allow for increased access to services for customers and constituents.  Develop a plan to communicate the new schedules to let constituents and customers take advantage of the added convenience.</p>\r\n<p>When developing your alternative work schedule, you''ll want a consistent structure.  Consider the following questions:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Does the new schedule meet applicable wage and hour laws?</li>\r\n    <li>Are there any conflicts with bargaining unit agreements?</li>\r\n    <li>Will the schedule be optional or mandatory?</li>\r\n    <li>How will the schedule impact paid holidays and paid leave?  </li>\r\n    <li>How will you provide equity for employees on the alternative and traditional schedules?</li>\r\n    <li>Who will be eligible for the alternative work schedule and who makes that determination?</li>\r\n    <li>What kind of training will be needed for supervisors and employees?</li>\r\n    <li>Will we need different record keeping requirements and evaluation methods?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Continuous monitoring is critical to the success of the new schedule and will help ensure programs are aligned with your goals and expectations.</p>\r\n<p>We are all waiting to see what the future will bring.  Additional economic and legislative changes could increase the need to adapt you service delivery model.  Additional economic challenges could reduce property and income tax revenues.  Services and structure of county government could change dramatically as ideas from the Kernan/Shepard report are implemented.  All of these changes may make alternative work schedules a desirable strategy to adjust to new ways of doing business.</p>', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '579-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:19:15', '2011-01-25 18:19:15', '', 579, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/579-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
