(698, 3, '2011-01-17 19:55:59', '2011-01-17 19:55:59', 'Numerous factors caused the financial markets to nearly come to a complete halt in October, 2008.  Many believe the meltdown of residential mortgages was the key to the market collapse and subsequent credit freeze.  Packaged mortgage debt, or Collateralized Debt Obligations, had become a significant portion of many institutional investorsâ€™ investment portfolios, including insurance giants like AIG and financial-services firms such as Lehman Brothers.\n\nBecause of the sudden disintegration of their assets last fall, major institutions were no longer purchasing municipal bonds.  Investors with solid balance sheets flew to safety and began investing almost exclusively in US Treasury instruments.  As investors sought to protect their principal without regard to interest earnings, Treasury yields fell to historic lows. During December of 2008 the three-month Treasury yield fell to 0% on three separate occasions.\n\nAs the dust settled on the collapse and investors who remained solvent realized that the likelihood of default on municipal bonds is extremely low, we the bond market began to ease.  However, the market had changed.  There were far fewer institutional investors with funds available to purchase municipal bonds, and retail investors (individuals) began to play a larger role.  Because many banks were not making a profit, the demand for tax-exempt bond purchases was reduced.\n\nAlong with AIG and Lehman Brothers, municipal bond insurance providers experienced massive losses in assets due to the meltdown of residential mortgages.  All but two of the major municipal bond insurers have lost their AAA rating from Standard & Poorâ€™s, and all of them have lost their Aaa rating from Moodyâ€™s.  In 2007, roughly half of all municipal bond sales were insured.  Through July of 2009, only 11% of sales have been insured.  The absence of insurers with highest quality ratings has left issuers without this option for enhancing the credit on their bonds.\n\nSmaller bond issues are commonly sold without a bond rating, but larger issues can benefit from an investment grade rating of A or higher.  The cost of the rating will be offset by lower interest costs.  For example, an issuer of a 20-year $5 million bond with a â€œAAâ€ rating would save nearly $1 million in interest compared to the same bond with a â€œBBBâ€ rating.  With the various market changes, the differential in interest rates has widened from those credits receiving a â€œAAâ€ rating or better compared to â€œAâ€ or lower.  This is demonstrated in the following table:', 'A Year of Change for the Municipal Bond Market', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '482-revision', '', '', '2011-01-17 19:55:59', '2011-01-17 19:55:59', '', 482, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/482-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(699, 3, '2011-01-07 20:24:34', '2011-01-07 20:24:34', '                <p>"Business as it used to run in the counties can no longer happen," says Ken Paust, county commissioner in Wayne County, Indiana.</p>\r\n                <p>He''s speaking of how local governments in Indiana were affected when property tax caps began taking effect just as a general economic downturn reduced other revenue sources.  </p>\r\n                <p>"We had an idea of the effect of property tax caps on our county and had done some budget reductions in anticipation," said Paust.  </p>\r\n                <p>Then a startling development occurred:  "Our auditor and treasurer came to us in early 2010 and said our cash flow was so diminished, we had only enough cash to operate for another month or two.  We decided the best firm to give us an impartial look at our entire county finances would be Umbaugh. </p>\r\n                <p>"We asked Umbaugh to look at total financial management, the effect of property tax caps, our cash flow, projections for the end of 2010, and what changes we needed to make to have a positive cash flow."  </p>\r\n                <p>The resulting plan is providing a financial road map to accomplish Wayne County''s priorities over the next several years.  It defines the county''s financial position, forecasts receipts and disbursements, identifies potential funding gaps and recommends funding solutions.  </p>\r\n                <p>"Wayne County was fortunate to be in a financial position that we had a solution available.  We loaned ourselves $4 million from our capital reserve accounts," said Paust.  "We asked Umbaugh to structure our financial plan so we''d have adequate funds to repay the loan and also start the following year with an additional $4 to 4.5 million." </p>\r\n                <p>"Full implementation of new property tax policies, coupled with current economic conditions, is requiring all local governments to look at their financial situation over a much longer period of time," said Gary Malone of Umbaugh, who worked with Wayne County on its financial study.  "It''s no longer adequate to prepare a budget for the next year; you need to look ahead three to five years."  </p>\r\n                <p>Although Wayne County''s controlled funds had maintained an average cash reserve of 41% in the past three years, the Umbaugh study showed that those controlled funds cash reserves would fall from the $14.8 million they had been in 2007 to just $3.2 million by 2012 unless the County made sufficient budget adjustments.  Cash reserves are considered an indicator of strong financial stability and they fund essential operations and cover temporary cash flow deficits.</p>\r\n                <p>Similar analyses were performed for all County funds â€“ from highway and local road and street funds to courthouse, debt service and capital projects funds.</p>\r\n                <p>Paust adds: "Without Umbaugh''s assistance, we wouldn''t have known exactly how much to cut out of our budget this year.  Having that number is worth its weight in gold.  You need to know for sure what the number''s going to be.  </p>\r\n                <p>"Wayne County has always managed its money very well, but we have to be even better managers of taxpayers'' dollars now because there are fewer dollars to work with.  Counties need to stay ahead of this, and Umbaugh can give you financial information to do that."</p>', 'A Financial Road Map for Wayne County', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '280-revision-11', '', '', '2011-01-07 20:24:34', '2011-01-07 20:24:34', '', 280, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/280-revision-11', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(700, 3, '2011-01-19 20:02:53', '2011-01-19 20:02:53', '<p>Just like a child waiting for a promised gift to arrive in the mail, school districts and local governments in parts of Indiana are still anxiously awaiting semiannual property tax receipts that traditionally arrive in June and December.  Even worse, entities in some parts of the state know the distributions are still far away because tax bills haven''t been sent to taxpayers yet.  Meanwhile, payrolls and utilities must still be paid and services must still be provided.</p>\r\n<p>Unless you can draw on cash reserves indefinitely, you will have to borrow to meet cash flow needs using temporary loan warrants.  Borrowing doesn''t reflect badly on your financial management.  It is a nearly universal necessity in parts of the state where tax collections have been delayed.</p>\r\n<p>A warrant is specific to a particular fund.  Schools normally borrow against the collections for the General Fund, the Transportation Fund, the Capital Projects Fund, the Debt Service and Pension Debt Service Fund.  The principal of the warrant is payable from the designated fund, but schools have the option to pay the interest from the Debt Service Fund.  The option of paying interest from a Debt Service fund is not available to other governmental entities.  However, libraries, fire departments, cities and other local governmental units are experiencing the same need for tax anticipation warrants. </p>\r\n<p>State law limits the principal of a warrant to 80 percent of the semiannual property tax distribution that is dedicated to paying the warrant.  As long as 80 percent of property taxes are collected, the warrant holder will be repaid.  Although achieving 80 percent of collections is somewhat of a concern in these challenging times, historically it is very rare for collections to be less than 90 percent.  Additional federal guidelines apply to the warrant amounts, and you will need to apply both federal and state tests before establishing the amount for your warrant.</p>\r\n<p>The credit analysis for a tax anticipation warrant will include current financial information, the assessed valuation in your taxing district, the percentage of property tax collections in recent years, and a list of the largest current taxpayers in the taxing district.  Growth projections and fund balances are not relevant since the warrant is a first lien on the distribution of property taxes or state aid distributions.  </p>\r\n<p>Since state law has removed school districts'' General Funds from the local property tax levy, current warrants for school General Funds are issued against state tuition support distributions and are subject to the same 80 percent limitation.</p>\r\n<p>A warrant must mature in the same year it was issued. If property tax collections will be later than December 31, it will be necessary to issue warrants initially with a December 31 maturity, and refund them later with a new maturity date.</p>\r\n<p>If your unit of government needs tax anticipation warrants to fulfill financial obligations before tax collections come in, Umbaugh can help with:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Preparing cash flow projections</li>\r\n    <li>Preparing a term sheet to explain all loan terms in easily understood language</li>\r\n    <li>Preparing a bid form</li>\r\n    <li>Sending the documents above to potential purchasers, along with legal documents prepared by bond counsel</li>\r\n    <li>Coordinating and hosting a competitive sale</li>\r\n    <li>Summarizing the bid results and determining the lowest bidder</li>\r\n    <li>Distributing the after-sale letter with wire transfer and closing instructions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>If you need help with a tax anticipation warrant, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Tax Anticipation Warrants Nearly A Necessity With Late Property Tax Distributions', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '623-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 20:02:53', '2011-01-19 20:02:53', '', 623, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/623-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(701, 3, '2011-01-20 19:11:38', '2011-01-20 19:11:38', 'We love to share our expertise!  Umbaugh representatives frequently  speak before seminars, conferences and government hearings to help even  the experts stay current during these changing times for local  governments and finances.  You''ll find here presentations, timely  articles from past issues of Footnotes and even a white paper or two.   (Don''t let the term ''white paper'' scare you; it''s technical, but  understandable, information.)\r\n\r\nCheck this section often â€“ we''ll update it constantly.\r\n\r\nIf you''d like to schedule a presentation tailored to  your group â€“ or if you don''t find the topic you''re looking for, please  call us at (1-888-516-9594) and we''ll find the person or information you''re  looking for.', 'Our Library', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '85-revision-8', '', '', '2011-01-20 19:11:38', '2011-01-20 19:11:38', '', 85, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/85-revision-8', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
