(706, 1, '2011-01-21 12:54:44', '2011-01-21 12:54:44', '<strong>Part 2 in a series</strong>\r\n\r\nThe huge Economic Recovery Package working its way through Congress may provide sorely needed funding to upgrade your local water and wastewater systems.\r\n\r\nAs proposed, approximately $11.8 billion or nearly 20% of the infrastructure investment portion of the Economic Recovery Package is targeted for community water and wastewater infrastructure. Of that amount:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>$6 billion is slated for wastewater projects funded through the Clean Water State Revolving Fund (CWSRF)</li>\r\n	<li>$2 billion is allotted for drinking water projects funded through the Drinking Water State Revolving Fund, and</li>\r\n	<li>$3.8 billion is budgeted for rural water and wastewater systems.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHalf of the $6 billion for wastewater projects would be disbursed by the states as loans. States would be required to use the other half to provide assistance "in the form of additional subsidization, including forgiveness of principal, negative interest loans, and grants, to municipalities (as defined in section 502 of such Act) for projects that are included on the State''s priority list established under section 603(g)."  The majority of the grant money would be for projects "to benefit municipalities that meet affordability criteria as determined by the Governor of the State," so we don''t know yet how that would be defined in Indiana.  The remainder of the grant money would be available for projects to mitigate storm water runoff or to achieve water efficiency, energy efficiency or environmentally sensitive project planning.\r\n\r\nThe overall goals of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 are immediate and continuing job creation.  At $825 billion ($550 billion in federal spending and $275 billion in tax cuts over the next two years), the legislation would be one of the largest bills ever to move through Congress.  House and Senate leaders have pledged to have it ready for President Obama''s signature by mid-February.\r\n\r\nOf course, provisions of the Economic Recovery Package are changing from day to day as the House of Representatives and Senate work to find common ground.  We will keep you updated in Footnotes as the bill progresses.  In our next issue, we''ll explain how the stimulus package may affect the municipal bond market.\r\n\r\nUmbaugh will be happy to work with you to structure potential projects that may qualify for stimulus package funding.', 'What The Stimulus Package Could Mean For Local Water And Wastewater Projects', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '629-revision-4', '', '', '2011-01-21 12:54:44', '2011-01-21 12:54:44', '', 629, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/629-revision-4', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(709, 5, '2011-01-25 20:32:36', '2011-01-25 20:32:36', 'Wind farms are a relatively new form of economic development with unique financial considerations for both private and public entities. For private land owners, lease terms and liability protection are important factors to consider. For public entities, other aspects rise to the top of the priority list.\n\nEvery project is unique. When deciding whether to pursue wind farms in your community, your top priorities should be protecting the infrastructure (both now and in the future), creating economic development agreements to create "win-win" scenarios, and ensuring open communication -- both internally as well as to the public.\n\nIf you are considering wind turbines for your area, the tax abatement, tax base and tax rate implications will be essential elements. There are significant tax breaks associated with wind farms in Michigan. These projects are subject to Industrial Facility Tax, but may be partially exempt from some taxing authorities such as school districts. Investment in wind farm technology is primarily considered to be personal property. It is therefore necessary to work closely with company representatives and Michigan Economic Development Corporation for appropriate treatment.\n\nBecause the construction of wind turbines requires extensive use of road and bridges, infrastructure protection is an important consideration.  A road use agreement is critical to protect the municipality''s infrastructure and define liability and traffic flow during construction. Key components of a road use agreement include a detailed map of roads, bridges and intersections to be used for construction and a process to determine existing conditions and identify county-regulated drains that may be affected.\n\nThe municipality will need to reach an economic development agreement with the wind farm developer. Wind farms may take significant acreage and therefore reduce or eliminate opportunities for other economic development to occur within the project area. You will want to be compensated for this to generate funds to promote, encourage and create other types of economic development in other areas of the county.  The amount and timing of these payments need to be negotiated and defined.  Payments should not be considered payments in lieu of taxes or any type of "property tax;" they should be treated as miscellaneous revenue or for a specific use.  Your agreement may allocate these payments to schools, libraries, towns, fire departments or other units.\n\nYou will also need to have a decommissioning plan in place prior to construction to protect the county and its constituents. The plan should include provisions and details for removal of towers, footings and access roads and returning the area to as near the same condition as possible if the wind generation project is terminated. Financial assurances need to be covered, and you should establish a schedule to review the decommissioning plan periodically.\n\nWhile alternative energy, and specifically wind farm development, seems to be gaining momentum; there are certainly very important financial aspects to consider for your community.  If Umbaugh''s experience in working through these issues would be helpful in your community, or if you have questions, please contact us.', 'Alternative Energy Sources as Economic Development', 'Wind farms are a relatively new form of economic development with unique financial considerations for both private and public entities. For private land owners, lease terms and liability protection are important factors to consider. For public entities, other aspects rise to the top of the priority list.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '638-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-25 20:32:36', '2011-01-25 20:32:36', '', 638, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/638-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
