(725, 3, '2011-01-18 21:56:57', '2011-01-18 21:56:57', '<p>Municipalities may consider annexation for a variety of reasons including: a desire for orderly and planned growth, achieving economic development goals or a need to extend services to individuals or businesses currently outside the municipal boundaries. Although annexation also may be considered as a way to increase revenue, the amount of new revenue your municipality may expect to generate varies depending on assessed value, population and road mileage.  </p>\r\n<p>State revenue distributions such as gasoline and cigarette taxes are wholly or partly based on <strong>population</strong> as determined by the most recent certified census. Some distributions of gasoline taxes are also based on <strong>changes in road mileage</strong> as well as population.  Revenues generated by local option income tax (CAGIT, COIT, LOIT, and EDIT) are based on the taxing unit''s <strong>levy as a percent of total county levies</strong>; therefore, local income tax revenue will increase if the municipality''s levy increases and if there are no other offsetting levy increases by other taxing units in the county. </p>\r\n<p>Annexation''s effect on property tax revenues is often misunderstood.  An increase in assessed value or population does not always translate to additional property tax revenue.  Each municipality has a limit for the amount of property tax it may levy for controlled funds.  Over the last few years, the maximum levy growth limit has been 3.7% to 4%. Generally, a municipally cannot raise taxes above the cap without obtaining authorization to levy taxes for a non-controlled fund or filing for an appeal with the DLGF to increase the maximum levy due to a qualifying reason, such as an annexation levy appeal.  A municipality may qualify for an automatic levy adjustment of up to 15% for the ensuing budget year if it annexed land on or before March 1. The percentage of increase is based on the annexed area''s <strong>assessed value</strong> rather than its population or the cost of providing services to the annexed area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Umbaugh can help your municipality estimate the additional revenue potential for an annexation as well as the cost of providing services. If you have questions or need assistance, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Municipal Annexation: Will It Generate the Revenue You Expect?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '572-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 21:56:57', '2011-01-18 21:56:57', '', 572, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/572-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(726, 3, '2011-01-18 21:55:00', '2011-01-18 21:55:00', '<p>The recent changes in our economy have led to lower property values and higher unemployment.  Coupled with Indiana''s new property tax caps, it is fair to say that all taxing units are facing declining revenues -- or soon will be.  For some, these shortfalls will be greater than you expect. So what''s next?  Do we deplete our fund balances?  Do we reduce spending, and, if so how?  Are new user fees a solution?  And what about changes to our local option income taxes.  Should new ones be adopted?</p>\r\n<p>We all have many questions.  Unfortunately, there are no easy answers.  Over the coming months, our firm''s partners will provide their thoughts and suggestions for navigating these turbulent waters.  We will discuss the appropriate use of fund balances; how much should we reserve and when is it appropriate to draw down excess funds.  We will take an in-depth look at budget cuts, and how we can tackle this process and still provide the essential services demanded by taxpayers.  We will explore using fees to replace lost income.  What fees make sense and how can we be sure that they are fair?  We will also examine the available variety of local option income taxes.  How can we create local policy to use these taxes for additional revenue and reduce the amount of property taxes lost to the new tax caps?</p>\r\n<p>We welcome your suggestions.  Let us know if there are additional topics  you would like to see discussed or if you have successes to share with others.  We are committed to helping you better serve your communities.</p>', 'Declining tax revenues? What next?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '569-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-18 21:55:00', '2011-01-18 21:55:00', '', 569, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/569-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(727, 3, '2011-01-18 21:23:29', '2011-01-18 21:23:29', '<p>The time frame for adopting any of the Local Option Income Taxes is April 1 to July 31.  This window of opportunity applies to CAGIT, COIT, CEDIT or any of the three LOITs.  If you have already adopted local income taxes and want to make adjustments, that also must be done during this same time period.  Any rate adopted or adjusted from April through July will take effect October 1.</p>\r\n<p>You may find that you need to adopt a new tax or adjust current income taxes to make up for reduced property tax revenues due to Circuit Breaker caps and recessionary times.  Also, if you anticipate reduced revenue from local income taxes, you may need to analyze what is realistic in recessionary times. Please contact us at umbaugh@footnotes.com if you have any questions, need additional information, or if we can be of assistance.</p>', 'Local Option Income-taxes - If You Want To Adopt One Nowâ€™s The Time', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '560-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 21:23:29', '2011-01-18 21:23:29', '', 560, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/560-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(728, 3, '2011-01-24 20:33:09', '2011-01-24 20:33:09', '<p>Laws governing referendum, petition and remonstrance procedures for controlled projects changed again in the 2009 session of the Indiana General Assembly.  Most of the changes merely fine tuned and clarified the process, but some provisions will make getting approval for building projects different going forward.</p>\r\n<p>The main changes are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>We will no longer see special elections spread throughout the year as we experienced in 2009.</strong>  Referenda will be considered at the next primary, general or municipal election.  If there is no primary, general or municipal election in the year after a public question becomes eligible to be on the ballot, the political subdivision may request a special election on the first Tuesday after the first Monday in May or November. The fiscal body of a political subdivision requesting a special election must pay the costs of holding a special election.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>The wording of the ballot question has been spelled out more clearly, and it must include the project cost and tax increase amount.</strong>  The amendment for ballot question reads:</li>\r\n	"Shall __________ (insert name of the political subdivision) issue bonds or enter into a least to finance ___________ (insert a brief description of the controlled project), which is estimated to cost not more than _________ (insert the total cost of the project) and is estimated to increase the property tax rate for debt service by _________ (insert increase in tax rate as determined by the department of local government finance)?"\r\n	<p>The exact wording of the question must be approved by the County Election Board(s) for that jurisdiction.</p>\r\n	<li><strong>A political subdivision may withdraw a public question from the ballot.</strong></li>\r\n	<li>The law allows the county election board to defer action on a petition submitted shortly before a regularly scheduled election until after the election.  Under this revision, <strong>the time period before an election when action can be deferred has been lengthened from 35 days to 45 days.</strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>The definitions of registered voter and eligible voter were clarified.</strong>  Formerly, an individual was eligible to vote on the public question if he was registered to vote in the political subdivision 30 days before the date of the election.\r\n		<br /><br />The law now says that an eligible voter is one who is eligible to vote in the political subdivision in which the public question will be held, pursuant to State Statute.  Further, to be eligible to vote, the individual must reside within the boundaries of the political subdivision for which the public question is being considered.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>The revisions spell out what information a political subdivision must make available to the public at the preliminary determination hearing.</strong>  This includes not only the maximum term, annual lease rental, principal amount and purpose of the proposed project, but also includes the indebtedness of "overlapping" taxing units.</li>\r\n	<li>The political subdivision must submit certain information regarding the referendum project to the Department of Local Government Finance at least 30 days before the election for posting on the DLGF Web site.  This information includes:\r\n    	<ul>\r\n            <li>The cost per square foot of any buildings being constructed as part of the controlled project.</li>\r\n            <li>The effect that approval of the controlled project would have on the political subdivision''s property tax rate.</li>\r\n            <li>The maximum term of the bonds or lease.</li>\r\n            <li>The estimated interest rates that will be paid and the total interest costs associated with the bonds or lease.</li>\r\n            <li>The purpose of the bonds or lease.</li>\r\n            <li>In the case of a controlled project proposed by a school corporation:\r\n            	<ul>\r\n                    <li>The current and proposed square footage of school building space per student;</li>\r\n                    <li>Enrollment patterns within the school corporation; and</li>\r\n                    <li>The age and condition of the current school facilities.</li>\r\n				</ul>\r\n             </li>\r\n			<li><strong>A political subdivision itself may introduce a public question on the ballot without a taxpayer petition under certain circumstances.</strong></li>\r\n			<li><strong>An elected or appointed official of a political subdivision may personally advocate for or against a position on the petition or remonstrance or a local public question as long as it is not done using public funds.</strong></li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>A student may use school equipment or facilities to report or editorialize about a local public question as part of news coverage of the referendum by student newspaper or broadcast.</p>\r\n<p>The above information is in part based upon a memo of the DLGF Commissioner dated August 7, 2009.</p>\r\n<p>Umbaugh is currently working with four school districts that have referenda on the November 3 ballot: Batesville Community School Corporation, Southwest Dubois County School Corporation, Tell City-Troy Township School Corporation and the MSD of Perry Township.</p>\r\n<p>If you have questions or need assistance with financing a controlled project, please contact us.</p>', 'Changes To Indiana Law Affect Approval Process for Shool and Local Government Building Projects', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '610-revision-5', '', '', '2011-01-24 20:33:09', '2011-01-24 20:33:09', '', 610, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/610-revision-5', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(729, 3, '2011-01-24 21:05:06', '2011-01-24 21:05:06', '<p>In 2009 and 2010, the State of Indiana will provide replacement grants to school corporations throughout Indiana that will experience the greatest losses due to the circuit breaker.  A school corporation with a circuit breaker loss more than 2% of its levy is eligible for the state levy replacement grant. Originally, these grants were set to be statewide distributions of $50 million in 2009 and $70 million in 2010.  However, the most recent legislative session made some modifications, and current projections show up to $40 million to be distributed in 2009 and up to $60 million distributed in 2010.  However, to date only $90 million has been appropriated by the State of Indiana for such grants.</p>\r\n<p>In 2009 we anticipate the grants to be allocated based upon the individual school corporation''s loss as a portion of total losses of eligible schools.  This same process will be applied in 2010, but each school corporation must first absorb the 2% levy loss, leaving the remainder eligible for the credits.  The State is expected to distribute these grants one time in the second half of the calendar year.  We do not know if these grants will be available beyond 2010.</p>\r\n<p>Based on the latest data prepared by the Legislative Services Agency, the following schools will be eligible for the state levy replacement grants:</p><br />\r\n<table width="100%" border="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Alexandria Community School Corporation</td>\r\n    <td>Mississinewa Community School Corp.</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Anderson Community School Corporation</td>\r\n    <td>Mitchell Community School Corp.</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Attica Consolidated School Corporation</td>\r\n    <td>Monroe Central School Corporation</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Avon Community School Corporation</td>\r\n    <td>Mt. Pleasant Township Comm. School Corp.</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Beech Grove City School Co