(732, 3, '2011-01-24 21:10:07', '2011-01-24 21:10:07', '<p>The recent changes in our economy have led to lower property values and higher unemployment.  Coupled with Indiana''s new property tax caps, it is fair to say that all taxing units are facing declining revenues -- or soon will be.  For some, these shortfalls will be greater than you expect. So what''s next?  Do we deplete our fund balances?  Do we reduce spending, and, if so how?  Are new user fees a solution?  And what about changes to our local option income taxes.  Should new ones be adopted?</p>\r\n<p>We all have many questions.  Unfortunately, there are no easy answers.  Over the coming months, our firm''s partners will provide their thoughts and suggestions for navigating these turbulent waters.  We will discuss the appropriate use of fund balances; how much should we reserve and when is it appropriate to draw down excess funds.  We will take an in-depth look at budget cuts, and how we can tackle this process and still provide the essential services demanded by taxpayers.  We will explore using fees to replace lost income.  What fees make sense and how can we be sure that they are fair?  We will also examine the available variety of local option income taxes.  How can we create local policy to use these taxes for additional revenue and reduce the amount of property taxes lost to the new tax caps?</p>\r\n<p>We welcome your suggestions.  Let us know if there are additional topics  you would like to see discussed or if you have successes to share with others.  We are committed to helping you better serve your communities.</p>', 'Declining tax revenues? What next?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '569-revision-4', '', '', '2011-01-24 21:10:07', '2011-01-24 21:10:07', '', 569, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/569-revision-4', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(733, 3, '2011-01-24 21:11:05', '2011-01-24 21:11:05', '<p>The time frame for adopting any of the Local Option Income Taxes is April 1 to July 31.  This window of opportunity applies to CAGIT, COIT, CEDIT or any of the three LOITs.  If you have already adopted local income taxes and want to make adjustments, that also must be done during this same time period.  Any rate adopted or adjusted from April through July will take effect October 1.</p>\r\n<p>You may find that you need to adopt a new tax or adjust current income taxes to make up for reduced property tax revenues due to Circuit Breaker caps and recessionary times.  Also, if you anticipate reduced revenue from local income taxes, you may need to analyze what is realistic in recessionary times. Please contact us at umbaugh@footnotes.com if you have any questions, need additional information, or if we can be of assistance.</p>', 'Local Option Income-taxes - If You Want To Adopt One Nowâ€™s The Time', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '560-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-24 21:11:05', '2011-01-24 21:11:05', '', 560, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/560-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(734, 3, '2011-01-18 21:19:28', '2011-01-18 21:19:28', '<p>The date for enforcing the Red Flag Regulations, which are part of the Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act of 2003, is almost here.  In the October 29, 2008 edition of Footnotes, we reported that the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) postponed enforcement of the regulations from November 1, 2008 until May 1, 2009.  If you haven''t done so already, now is the time to develop and adopt your red flag policies to detect, prevent and mitigate potential identity theft risks in connection with customer accounts. </p>\r\n<p>The Red Flag Regulations affect creditors with covered accounts.  A creditor is defined as any person or entity that regularly arranges for the extension, renewal or continuation of credit or defers payments for goods or services â€“ and utilities are specifically included.  A covered account is an account offered or maintained primarily for personal, family or household purposes, which involves or is designed to permit multiple payments or transactions. Clearly, a utility account fits this definition. </p>\r\n<p>Please keep in mind that the rules allow your identity theft program to be "appropriate for the size and complexity of the municipality."  Preparing your policy and reviewing and updating it on a regular basis do require an investment of time, but it is important to be in compliance.  If you chose to ignore the Red Flag Regulations, you are putting yourself at risk for a fine or other enforcement actions from the FTC.  Compliance also protects your customers.  </p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions about Red Flag Regulations or would like additional information, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Red Flag Regulations Enforcement Date Is Almost Here', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '558-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 21:19:28', '2011-01-18 21:19:28', '', 558, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/558-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(735, 3, '2011-01-18 20:30:09', '2011-01-18 20:30:09', '<p>Just as it does for individuals and businesses, having money in reserve gives taxing units a sense of comfort. A fund balance is the result of receipts minus disbursements.  You have a positive fund balance when actual receipts are higher than budgeted, actual disbursements are lower than budgeted, or a combination of both. </p>\r\n<p>There are a number of reasons why taxing units should maintain adequate fund balances:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Some revenues are not available when needed.  For example, it is not uncommon to experience negative cash flow when property tax disbursements are delayed. It is not possible to delay operating expenses such as payroll until you receive the property tax distribution, so more money is being paid out than is coming in. Fund balances allow you to manage cash flow shortages without depleting cash. Further, using fund balances in this way will avoid the need for short-term borrowing and the associated interest costs.</li>\r\n	<li>Fund balances can be used to respond to unforeseen events or emergencies.  Buildings or equipment may be damaged by a natural disaster or other unexpected event.  An emergency may require more employee overtime expenses than budgeted.  On the positive side, having a fund balance may allow you to take advantage of an unanticipated opportunity, such as purchasing land that becomes available.</li>\r\n	<li>Fund balances enhance your credit worthiness.  Maintaining adequate fund balances is a major factor bond rating agencies consider when they evaluate credit worthiness. Bond rating agencies generally require cash reserves equal to 15 to 20 percent of the general operating budget.  Adequate cash reserves demonstrate financial stability, enhancing the bond rating â€“ and possibly reducing the cost of issuing debt.</li>\r\n	<li>Fund balances may be used to finance capital expenditures.  Building up a fund balance over time may eliminate the need to borrow for capital expenses -- or at least reduce the amount to be borrowed, which reduces interest costs.  </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>What is an "adequate" fund balance?  It is not easy to tie it to a particular amount or percentage.  Although 15 to 20 percent is a good rule of thumb, cash needs can vary among taxing units.  An adequate fund balance for your situation is one that provides optimal cash flow for operations.</p>', 'The Importance of Adequate Fund Balances', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '552-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 20:30:09', '2011-01-18 20:30:09', '', 552, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/552-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
