(766, 5, '2011-01-18 19:38:16', '2011-01-18 19:38:16', '<p>School districts throughout Indiana may qualify for three financing tools â€“ including two that are interest free â€“ because of the federal stimulus legislation.  The  programs can mean a substantial savings and there are time and/or funding limits for the programs, so school districts need to act quickly.  The three programs are Qualified School Construction Bonds, Qualified Zone Academy Bonds and Build America Bonds.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Qualified School Construction Bonds</strong> -- Indiana has received an allotment of $177,861,000 for this zero-interest funding program.  The Indiana Department of Education will make $77,861,000 available to school districts for bond issues of up to $2 million each.  The remaining $100 million will be allocated for bonds between $2 million and $10 million.  IPS qualifies for a separate allocation of $31,181,000 under this program because it is one of 100 largest school corporations in the country. </p>\r\n<p>All school corporations with school renovation, repair or modernization plans may apply to the Indiana Department of Education for these funds, but if the project is subject to a referendum or petition process, it must have petition or referendum approval before the application is submitted.  The first round of applications must be received by August 3; a second round of applications is due November 13.</p>\r\n<p>New construction, space additions and projects receiving a Qualified Zone Academy Bond allocation (see below) will be considered for the remaining Qualified School Construction Bonds allocation after all other qualified requests have been filled. </p>\r\n<p>The Qualified School Construction Bonds are supported through federal tax credits to the bond purchaser. The maximum length of the bonds can be 14 to 15 years.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Qualified Zone Academy Bonds</strong> of up to $2 million are available to Indiana schools in economically distressed areas and with curriculum designed through a school/business partnership.  To qualify for a Qualified Zone Academy Bond, at least 35 percent of students must be eligible for free or reduced lunch and the project must have a business "matching" component.  The match consists of written commitments from private entities for contributions equaling at least 10 percent of the bond proceeds; in-kind and volunteer contributions may qualify for the match. Proceeds of the bonds may be used to remodel and repair school facilities, purchase equipment, develop course materials or conduct professional development.</p>\r\n<p>Qualified Zone Academy Bonds are interest free and the bondholder receives a tax credit. This allocation is an ongoing application process with the Indiana Department of Education. </p>\r\n<p>Projects funded by either Qualified School Construction Bonds or Qualified Zone Academy Bonds are required to abide by the Davis-Bacon Act requiring prevailing wages (i.e. union scale) for construction bidding.</p>\r\n<p>Build America Bonds -  Unlike the other two funding mechanisms, Build America Bonds are subject to interest, and in fact, it is taxable interest rather than tax exempt.  The bonds may be sold with either the bondholder receiving the tax credit or the tax credit received as a direct payment to the school corporation. The direct payment option is more advantageous for the school corporation.  After the Build America Bonds are sold at taxable rates, on each interest payment date the school corporation (or trustee bank) receives payment from the US Treasury for 35 percent of the interest due on that date. This is the economic benefit of selling "taxable" bonds with a tax-credit feature.  In general, these bonds may be used for projects that could otherwise be financed with tax-exempt bonds, including construction, renovation, equipment purchases and real estate acquisition.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Build America Bonds</strong> are expected to be available through the end of 2010. The maturity schedule on these bonds would be the 20-year normal limit prescribed by Indiana statutes. </p>\r\n<p>Umbaugh is assisting several clients with applications for the Qualified School Construction Bonds and structuring financings for all three of these stimulus financing tools.</p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions about whether one or more of these financing tools is applicable for your school renovation or construction project, please contact us.</em></p>', 'School Facility Projects Qualify for Special Funding Options Through Federal Stimulus Package', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '538-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-18 19:38:16', '2011-01-18 19:38:16', '', 538, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/538-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(769, 5, '2011-01-21 19:21:58', '2011-01-21 19:21:58', 'Numerous factors caused the financial markets to nearly come to a complete halt in October, 2008.  Many believe the meltdown of residential mortgages was the key to the market collapse and subsequent credit freeze.  Packaged mortgage debt, or Collateralized Debt Obligations, had become a significant portion of many institutional investorsâ€™ investment portfolios, including insurance giants like AIG and financial-services firms such as Lehman Brothers.\r\n\r\nBecause of the sudden disintegration of their assets last fall, major institutions were no longer purchasing municipal bonds.  Investors with solid balance sheets flew to safety and began investing almost exclusively in US Treasury instruments.  As investors sought to protect their principal without regard to interest earnings, Treasury yields fell to historic lows. During December of 2008 the three-month Treasury yield fell to 0% on three separate occasions.\r\n\r\nAs the dust settled on the collapse and investors who remained solvent realized that the likelihood of default on municipal bonds is extremely low, we the bond market began to ease.  However, the market had changed.  There were far fewer institutional investors with funds available to purchase municipal bonds, and retail investors (individuals) began to play a larger role.  Because many banks were not making a profit, the demand for tax-exempt bond purchases was reduced.\r\n\r\nAlong with AIG and Lehman Brothers, municipal bond insurance providers experienced massive losses in assets due to the meltdown of residential mortgages.  All but two of the major municipal bond insurers have lost their AAA rating from Standard & Poorâ€™s, and all of them have lost their Aaa rating from Moodyâ€™s.  In 2007, roughly half of all municipal bond sales were insured.  Through July of 2009, only 11% of sales have been insured.  The absence of insurers with highest quality ratings has left issuers without this option for enhancing the credit on their bonds.\r\n\r\nSmaller bond issues are commonly sold without a bond rating, but larger issues can benefit from an investment grade rating of A or higher.  The cost of the rating will be offset by lower interest costs.  For example, an issuer of a 20-year $5 million bond with a â€œAAâ€ rating would save nearly $1 million in interest compared to the same bond with a â€œBBBâ€ rating.  With the various market changes, the differential in interest rates has widened from those credits receiving a â€œAAâ€ rating or better compared to â€œAâ€ or lower.  This is demonstrated in the following table:', 'A Year of Change for the Municipal Bond Market', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '482-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-21 19:21:58', '2011-01-21 19:21:58', '', 482, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/482-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(770, 5, '2011-01-18 18:07:29', '2011-01-18 18:07:29', '<p>Does the term "non-binding review and recommendation" sound pretty futile? It doesn''t have to be.</p>\r\n<p>When the Indiana General Assembly changed the property tax system over the last few sessions and enacted Circuit Breaker property tax caps, budgets for units of local government became more interdependent.  At the same time, the changes increased the role of County Councils in the process of budget approvals and setting tax rates.</p>\r\n<p>All civil taxing units â€“ and that can be a large number depending on the county â€“ must file their proposed tax rate, levy and budget with the County Council for review and a non-binding recommendation.</p>\r\n<p>The county fiscal body then has 15 days to:</p>\r\n	<ul>\r\n    	<li>review the proposed budget, estimated tax rate and levy</li>\r\n		<li>issue a non-binding recommendation to each civil taxing unit that includes:\r\n			<ul>\r\n				<li>comparison of any increase in the unit''s budget or tax levy to the average increase in state and county nonfarm personal income for the preceding six calendar years</li>\r\n				<li>increases in the budgets and tax levies of other civil taxing units in the county.</li>\r\n        	</ul>\r\n    	</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n    \r\n<p>The Department of Local Government Finance (DLGF) has developed forms that counties may use on a voluntary basis to make these comparisons.</p>\r\n<p>The review for each civil taxing unit could be very perfunctory -- or County Councils may elect to use this process as an opportunity to facilitate meaningful collaboration on a budget.</p>\r\n<p>These recommended steps will help County Councils make this process meaningful:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Contact each unit to discuss and ask questions about their budgets.</strong> You''re not doing this to be intrusive or question the validity of their budget.  You''re trying to share meaningful information about changes in debt structure, anticipated debt issuance and expected material changes in local assessed valuation.  You''re also gathering information to develop a model to estimate what the Circuit Breaker impacts will be for each unit.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Develop a county-wide model showing the impact of Circuit Breaker credits.</strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Convene a meeting to share the results with all civil taxing units</strong> BEFORE the budgets are finalized, giving everyone a chance to regroup with the benefit of complete information.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Reach out to school districts</strong>.  Although they are not civil taxing units and are not required to submit their budgets, school districts are impacted by the Circuit Breaker and other units'' tax rates.  When you include school districts in the process, it fosters cooperation among the interdependent taxing units.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Identify controlled funds</strong> and determine, based on the levy growth quotient, what the reduction in each levy or budget is likely to be along with the resulting reduction to the tax rate.  Another less-time-consuming alternative is to look for increases in non-controlled levies (i.e. debt service) because they cannot be cut.</li>\r\n	<li>Use the non-binding recommendation to <strong>point out to each taxing unit where they exceed the growth quotient</strong>, and how they compare to other budget/levy changes, and how they compare with nonfarm income changes.  If necessary, include a general statement that their budget is like to be cut and by how much.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Remind those submitting from appointed boards</strong> (usually libraries) where the levies exceed the average growth quotient that their budget is not subject to the non-binding review, but must be adopted by the appropriate fiscal body (city/town or county).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In the end, each County Council''s decision on how proactive to be in the non-binding review and recommendation process largely will depend on how much time they are willing to devote to the process.  It could very well be time well spent in terms of their county''s economic health.</p>\r\n<p>If your county needs assistance in the budget review and recommendation process, please contact.</p>', 'County budget review: futile or meaningful?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '487-revision-4', '', '', '2011-01-18 18:07:29', '2011-01-18 18:07:29', '', 487, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/487-revision-4', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
