ll spent in terms of their county''s economic health.\r\n\r\nIf your county needs assistance in the budget review and recommendation process, please contact.', 'County budget review: futile or meaningful?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '487-revision-5', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:07:22', '2011-01-25 16:07:22', '', 487, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/487-revision-5', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(773, 3, '2011-01-25 15:03:17', '2011-01-25 15:03:17', 'Decatur County, Indiana, had the opportunity of a lifetime in 2006.  All they had to do was present the winning case for why their area was the most advantageous location for a new Honda Motors automobile assembly plant.  And like most economic development projects, responding quickly was essential to stay in the running.\r\n\r\n"For me, this project was very challenging," said Jerome Buening, a Decatur County commissioner.  "Decatur County had never been through anything of this magnitude.  We enlisted professionals to help us, and the State was very important to the effort in funding for infrastructure."\r\n\r\nIndiana was one of five states being considered for what became a $550 million investment and a potential of up to 2,000 jobs.  All the "short list" locations were close to interstate highway and rail transportation and within supplying distance of Honda''s Marysville, Ohio, location.\r\n\r\n"Honda''s main issue was trying to assemble enough pieces of property.  They had looked at one site in Decatur County that wouldn''t work, but we found a better area they hadn''t looked at," said Buening.\r\n\r\nUmbaugh was a member of the professional services team helping evaluate proposed options and create just the right package to attract Honda.  The eventual agreement was creative and beneficial to everyone.\r\n\r\n"Umbaugh put the numbers together.  They let us know what was and wasn''t going to work, what pieces were missing, what we needed and when we needed it," said Buening.\r\n\r\nWhen Decatur County was named the winning location June 28, 2006, an Indianapolis Star reporter remarked on just how competitive the field had been: "Indiana not only prevailed over Ohio, but also Illinois, Wisconsin and Michigan â€“ fellow rustbelt holdovers desperate to prod their economies."\r\n\r\nBuening says:  "Our TIF (tax increment financing) was somewhat complicated.  It''s a county TIF because of the Honda location, but the City of Greensburg needed improvements in its water and wastewater systems to serve the new facility.  We needed a creative TIF structure that would allow that to happen.  In addition, we structured excess TIF revenue up front to help the City make those improvements.\r\n\r\n"The people I dealt with at Umbaugh are outstanding individuals. They didn''t talk over our heads.  This was a complicated project to understand, and they explained things well.  They are very down to earth and good people to work with.  I''m very pleased that we worked with Umbaugh."\r\n\r\nHonda, of course, brought jobs to the area along with new tax revenue, but Buening notes that Honda has become an "anchoring company" attracting other new businesses and keeping companies in Decatur County: "At least one company that was in danger of leaving to consolidate with their other location elsewhere not only stayed in Decatur County, they brought their other operations here rather than other way around."\r\n\r\nThe Honda plant opened in 2008, just before the automotive industry and the economy in general began serious financial struggles.  Nonetheless, the economic development deal is still a great boost for Decatur County.\r\n\r\n"Honda has not been able to advance to a second shift as they thought they might, but the fact that they were able to hold the number of employees and the amount of time working steady in the current economic conditions is outstanding. The potential here is amazing for Decatur County," Buening adds.', 'Winning a Honda Plant for Decatur County', 'Decatur County, Indiana, had the opportunity of a lifetime in 2006. All they had to do was present the winning case for why their area was the most advantageous location for a new Honda Motors automobile assembly plant. And like most economic development projects, responding quickly was essential to stay in the running.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '353-revision-7', '', '', '2011-01-25 15:03:17', '2011-01-25 15:03:17', '', 353, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/353-revision-7', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(774, 5, '2011-01-18 18:07:35', '2011-01-18 18:07:35', '<p>As we look at ways local governments can provide local services using less revenue, managing your capital needs is an essential tool for government efficiency because capital projects can be such a large expenditure.</p>\r\n<p>Start by looking at the big picture.  Develop a capital plan that includes all major improvements and related costs expected over the next five to ten years.  Although you may not be able to accomplish all projects on the optimal schedule â€“ and there may be additional unexpected projects crop up â€“ having all of the potential projects on your capital plan gives you a road map to guide the planning process.</p>\r\n<p>Include a review of your current debt repayment obligations in that capital plan.  These payments must be made, so they will figure into the amount of resources you have for new projects. As you review current debts, consider whether you should take this opportunity to refinance or restructure existing bonds to save money.  Plot a timetable showing when existing bonds will be retired.  If you can schedule payments for new projects to begin as other bonds are paid off, that provides an opportunity to fund projects without using more of your current revenue.</p>\r\n<p>Many long-lived assets can be financed through issuing debt rather than by paying for them out of current income.  Local governmental units often prefer to avoid borrowing because they don''t like to incur interest expense.  Rather than applying this "pay as you go" philosophy, financing on a "pay as you use" basis pays for the asset as taxpayers use it over the next 20 years or so.  It is a fair way to match the benefit of the asset with the taxpayers who will actually use it.   Financing these assets with debt reduces the amount of current taxes needed to pay for public infrastructure.  Bond financing approved by a referendum may give you the additional advantage of having those bond repayments outside of property tax caps.</p>\r\n<p>Once you have your capital plan, review and update it annually to adjust for changing needs and circumstances.</p>\r\n<p>Our next article in the strategies for government efficiency series will cover how to grow your tax base to bring in more revenue.  </p>\r\n<p>If you have questions or need assistance with managing your capital needs, please contact us.</p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency Part 4: Managing Your Capital Needs', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '485-revision-5', '', '', '2011-01-18 18:07:35', '2011-01-18 18:07:35', '', 485, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/485-revision-5', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(777, 5, '2011-01-18 18:29:38', '2011-01-18 18:29:38', '<p>As officials look for ways to streamline local government, many will consider consolidation.  Saving money, however, is not the only potential advantage of consolidation.</p>\r\n<p>Consolidation may also allow you to better manage and control growth and development through unified planning and zoning, and it can identify your borders by thwarting the possible encroachment on unincorporated areas by other taxing units.  It also promotes better coordination with schools and county government and eliminates the complexity of multiple taxing units.  Consolidation is also intended to create greater transparency in government.</p>\r\n<p>In the cost efficiency category, consolidation can provide a broader tax base for funding and may allow areas to share resources to enhance the ability to provide services.  The cost-efficiency benefits were among the reasons the Government Modernization Act was passed in 2006 to allow voluntary consolidation of local governments.  Initiatives from the Kernan-Shepard report also encourage consolidation.</p>\r\n<p>As you might expect, some issues may arise when you consider consolidation:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>It may cause changes in Council districts.</li>\r\n	<li>Representatives from all entities being consolidated may have different goals and agendas.</li>\r\n	<li>The consolidation may result in "stranded" debt; each issuing body will be responsible for its pre-existing debt and will need a mechanism to fund payments.</li>\r\n	<li>You will need to determine where services will be allocated.</li>\r\n	<li>You will need to address whether municipal ordinances are applicable to "rural" areas.</li>\r\n	<li>Finally, it may be possible that despite increased operational efficiencies the consolidation does not translate into cost savings.  If they do not, the consolidation is less appealing to taxpayers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Under the Indiana Government Modernization Act, reorganization may be initiated by adoption of a resolution by the legislative body of a political subdivision or a written petition signed by at least five percent of voters filed with the clerk of the political subdivision.  The law further requires:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Legislative bodies to conduct hearings and adopt resolutions to participate in the reorganization.</li>\r\n	<li>Preparation of a comprehensive reorganization plan.</li>\r\n	<li>Consideration of the plan by the legislative bodies of the participating units,</li>\r\n	<li>Filing the plan with the county recorder, the DLGF, the Department of Education (if applicable), and the clerk of circuit court (if applicable).</li>\r\n	<li>Placing a public question on the ballot by the county election board for consideration by voters.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Under the Indiana Government Modernization Act, reorganization may be initiated by adoption of a resolution by the legislative body of a political subdivision or a written petition signed by at least five percent of voters filed with the clerk of the political subdivision.  The law further requires:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Legislative bodies to conduct hearings and adopt resolutions to participate in the reorganization.</li>\r\n    <li>The appointment of a reorganization committee either in accordance with an agreement adopted by the participating units or a committee made up of three members appointed by the executive of each participating unit (with no more than two of their three appointments from the same political party).</li>\r\n    <li>Preparation of a comprehensive reorganization plan.</li>\r\n    <li>Consideration of the plan by the legislative bodies of the participating units,</li>\r\n    <li>Filing the plan with the county recorder, the DLGF, the Department of Education (if applicable), and the clerk of circuit court (if applicable).</li>\r\n    <li>Placing a public question on the ballot by the county election board for consideration by voters.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The new entity would also likely need to appeal to the DLGF for revisions to its levy.</p>\r\n<p>The possibility of creating a reorganized political subdivision can be a daunting task with complex financial implications.   If you have questions or need assistance with considering consolidation, please contact us.</p>', 'Consolidation â€“ A Viable Option?', '<p>As officials look for ways to streamline local government, many will consider consolidation.  Saving money, however, is not the only potential advantage of consolidation.</p>\r\n<p>Consolidation may also allow you to better manage and control growth and development through unified planning and zoning, and it can identify your borders by thwarting the possible encroachment on unincorporated areas by other taxing units.  It also promotes better coordination with schools and county government and eliminates the complexity of multiple taxing units.  Consolidation is also intended to create greater transparency in government.</p>', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '523-revision-5', '', '', '2011-01-18 18:29:38', '2011-01-18 18:29:38', '', 523, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/523-revision-5', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(776, 5, '2011-01-25 16:18:35', '2011-01-25 16:18:35', '<div>\r\n<p id="internal-source-marker_0.8404643973335624">Part 3 in a series</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nIn the first article of this series on Strategies for Government Efficiency, we listed five strategies that must be included:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>managing revenues efficiently,</li>\r\n	<li>finding opportunities for cost efficiencies,</li>\r\n	<li>providing services efficiently through consolidation,</li>\r\n	<li>managing capital expenditures and</li>\r\n	<li>growing your tax base.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThis article covers finding opportunities for cost efficiencies.\r\n\r\nIf dealing with reduced revenue means you must reduce the cost of providing services, you can do that by:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>improving efficiencies,</li>\r\n	<li>reducing the quality of services and/or</li>\r\n	<li>cutting public services.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNormally we dislike the second and third alternatives above, because constituents have become accustomed to a certain level of service.  But don''t totally discount reducing or cutting services.  This is a good time for all stakeholders to evaluate such questions as what crime rate is acceptable, how quickly do we really need to fill potholes, and can we tolerate a longer fire response time?  The answers will vary from community to community.  Answering these and other questions about local services will give you a strategic planning framework for making difficult decisions to reduce the quality of services, reduce the level of public services or to increase taxes.  (We''ll have more on strategic planning in future issues.)\r\n\r\nOther counties have found creative approaches that may work in your area.  Their cost efficiency solutions include four-day work weeks and/or special summer shifts, self-insurance programs, wellness programs, coordinating city police and county sheriff responsibilities, centralized purchasing, energy audits, in-house construction inspection and working with judges to manage jail capacity.\r\n\r\nAs you look for ways to reduce costs, reducing the number of employees is always something to consider.  In a previous issue of Footnotes, we reviewed the costs of downsizing.  Please refer to the June 10 issue on our Web site if staff reductions are being considered in your cost efficiency plan.\r\n\r\nAs you look for cost efficiencies, resist the immediate temptation to simply slash services without adequate thought to the consequences.  If reducing services destroys the quality of life that attracts people to your area, people move away and you don''t attract new employers.  You will have to strike the right balance for your community, and that''s why strategically planning these efficiencies is so important.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance dealing with reduced funding, please contact us.</em>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: Finding Opportunities for Cost Efficiencies', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '489-revision-8', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:18:35', '2011-01-25 16:18:35', '', 489, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/489-revision-8', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(780, 5, '2011-01-25 16:28:15', '2011-01-25 16:28:15', '<div>\r\n<p id="internal-source-marker_0.5006012336816639">Part 1 in a series</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nCan local governments continue to provide the same level of service with a <strong>half billion dollar reduction</strong> in income?  That is the question local entities should ask as they plan services and budgets for the future.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately the $500 million reduction in statewide property tax collections projected by the Legislative Services Agency is just the reduction from the full implementation of property tax caps.  Actual revenue losses for local governments will be greater for a number of reasons, including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Expansion of the homestead exemption -- The new state 35 percent homestead exemption is reducing property tax revenues from fixed rate funds, such as cumulative capital development funds, by 10 to 25 percent</li>\r\n	<li>Reduction in income tax collections -- The State of Indiana reports that individual income tax collections declined by 23 percent for the first four months of 2009.  Your county income taxes are based upon the same taxable income as the State''s.  Assuming that revenue from local income taxes in your area will be similarly affected, that gives you less revenue for operating costs and capital expenditures.  It also gives you less revenue for property tax relief. And we know that less money for property tax relief means higher property taxes and more tax revenue lost to the property tax caps.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn addition, depending on your situation, your tax revenue may be affected by:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>trending â€“ which can go down as well as up,</li>\r\n	<li>delays in collecting and distributing property taxes, and</li>\r\n	<li>property tax delinquencies.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nStrong cash reserves can help withstand these fluctuations, so managing your reserves is crucial.\r\n\r\nNearly every unit of government is facing the challenge of how to do more (or even just stay the same) with less revenue.  The debate always focuses on efficiency.  But what does efficiency really mean?  It means much more than simply cutting your budget. Strategies for Government Efficiency must include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>managing revenues efficiently,</li>\r\n	<li>finding opportunities for cost efficiencies,</li>\r\n	<li>providing services efficiently through consolidation,</li>\r\n	<li>managing capital expenditures and</li>\r\n	<li>growing your tax base.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe next article in this series will cover managing revenues efficiently.  We''ll explain how some fine tuning of the mix of local income taxes could help you increase spendable tax revenue without increasing income tax rates.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance dealing with reduced funding, please contact us.</em>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: Where Did Our Taxes Go?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '498-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:28:15', '2011-01-25 16:28:15', '', 498, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/498-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
