(785, 5, '2011-01-18 19:29:32', '2011-01-18 19:29:32', '<p>It isn''t exactly earth-shattering news right now to say we are in a recession.  And while utilities are somewhat insulated from economic cycles, because everyone needs the essential services utilities provide, they are not immune.  Because of public health and safety considerations utilities rarely go bankrupt and simply cease functioning.  But they can become insolvent, requiring a receiver to come in and take over.  </p>\r\n<p>Depending on the circumstances, enacting a rate increase can take several months.  If yours is a municipal utility, the problem may be compounded if the civil unit is also struggling to balance its own budget.  In the short term you only have two options to adjust for economic conditions: increase revenues or reduce expenditures.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Increase revenues</strong> â€“ Options for increasing revenues include the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Program in smaller, more periodic rate adjustments, which are much easier and meet less resistance. </li>\r\n    <li>Review all hydrants and automatic sprinklers to make sure you are billing for fire protection.</li>\r\n    <li>Review the required customer deposit amounts to ensure they are sufficient to offset bad debts.</li>\r\n    <li>Review your shut-off policy and shorten it if necessary.</li>\r\n    <li>Re-examine the adequacy of non-recurring fees for bad checks, utility reconnection and tap fees (among others).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Decrease expenditures</strong> â€“ You may be able to decrease expenses by:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Review existing supply contracts.  Can you save money on uniforms or group cell phone plans?  Get quotes for your property, casualty and liability insurance; consider raising deductibles or other money-saving risk-management programs.  </li>\r\n    <li>Health insurance; raise deductibles or investigate health savings accounts.  Reconsider whether to pay 100% for spouses and dependents.</li>\r\n    <li>Reduce your personnel costs through attrition, by deferring hiring, limiting wage increases or eliminating overtime. </li>\r\n    <li>Consider outsourcing where practical.  Such areas as meter reading, maintenance, billing or bookkeeping might have value.</li>\r\n    <li>Take advantage of group purchasing power by exploring consortium arrangements to purchase such items as chemicals, vehicles, fuel and office supplies.</li>\r\n    <li>Defer non-essential capital projects and periodic maintenance, if possible.</li>\r\n    <li>Regionalize treatment and supply facilities.  Share certified operators with nearby utilities.</li>\r\n    <li>Buy more fuel-efficient vehicles.</li>\r\n    <li>Investigate possibility reissuing debt at a lower interest rate</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Believe it or not, recessionary times not only hand us challenges, they also open up opportunities. </p>\r\n<p>The challenges come from the scarcity of bank credit, a reduction in growth of your customer base, the lack of development activity, and a corresponding financial strain on your vendors and suppliers.  (Beware that the tough economic times also breed scam artists who see this as their opportunity, too!)</p>\r\n<p>On the bright side, you have the opportunity during recessionary times to make hard decisions you might have avoided before.  You also have the opportunity build goodwill with your customers as you explain cost-saving measures and your efforts to manage rates.  State and federal money is available to fund more infrastructure programs.  RD, SRF, EDA, OCRA and other programs are likely to get additional funding to stimulate the economy over the next several years.  And there is growing recognition of the need for a new construction grants program to improve the country''s aging infrastructure, similar to programs of the 1970s and 1980s.</p>\r\n<p>As you rise to the management challenge of these recessionary times, talk to your largest customers frequently and monitor them for any on-going concerns that could affect your operations.  The revenues of many utilities are heavily concentrated in just a handful of customers.  Extend your financial planning beyond the current year so you are thinking long range.  Also remember to keep your bank balances within FDIC limits.  Although coverage was increased temporarily, at present the limit will revert to $100,000 in January 1, 2010.</p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance with financial and strategic planning for your utility, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Managing Your Utilities in Tough Economic Times', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '535-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 19:29:32', '2011-01-18 19:29:32', '', 535, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/535-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(787, 5, '2011-01-25 16:36:48', '2011-01-25 16:36:48', 'In previous issues of Footnotes we have described a variety of solutions for funding local services, particularly when revenues are reduced.  One solution is to adjust the amount of your Local Option Income Tax (LOIT).  If you need to adjust your LOIT rate, you have a narrow window of opportunity, because, by statute, it must occur between April 1 and July 31.\r\n\r\nEven\r\n\r\nif your LOIT rate has served you well up until now, the current economic landscape may make a rate adjustment an important consideration this year for the following reasons:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Economic conditions will likely reduce revenue, putting additional pressure on your budget</li>\r\n	<li>If your revenue stream is securing debt, reduced revenue may trigger the need for a property tax backup or you may have difficulty in making debt payments.</li>\r\n	<li>Whatever the expected outcomes when you adopted LOITs prior to 2008, HEA1001 has made such a significant change your expected outcomes may not materialize.</li>\r\n	<li>The pending impact of property tax caps in 2009 and 2010 may call for restructuring local income taxes to achieve a more strategic mix â€“ or it may make you consider a new LOIT. For example, many counties have a local homestead credit funded through a LOIT. Homesteads received substantial property tax relief in HEA1001.  Restructuring local income taxes may not only be warranted, restructuring (not necessarily increasing) LOITs may actually reduce the circuit breaker impact.</li>\r\n	<li>Indiana law requires LOIT entities to review each year the method for distributing LOIT property tax relief (in particular the Property Tax Relief LOIT â€“ commonly known as Option B LOIT).  Given the changes HEA1001 will cause from 2009 to 2010, it is very likely your strategy for PTRC allocation should change as well.</li>\r\n	<li>Every governmental unit is concerned about constituents'' combined levels of property and income taxes.  A strategic approach to adjusting or restructuring LOIT will help you achieve the most efficient and effective mix for your situation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<em>If you have any questions or need assistance in determining how adjusting your LOIT rate could affect revenue and your overall tax mix, please contact us.</em>', 'Now Is the Time to Review Local Income Tax Rates', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '541-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-25 16:36:48', '2011-01-25 16:36:48', '', 541, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/541-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(788, 5, '2011-01-18 19:47:39', '2011-01-18 19:47:39', '<p>Revenues for many cities and towns are, or soon will be, declining from property tax caps, late or unpaid property taxes, reduction in tax base, reduction in income taxes, and reduced utility revenues. The demand for services, however, rarely decreases.</p>\r\n<p>It is difficult right now for communities to know with a great degree of certainty what their near-term financial position will be and if that landscape will be sustainable.  Strategic planning is critical to address these questions. </p>\r\n<p>Downsizing the labor force is one of the first strategic steps that may be considered to reduce operational expenses, since labor and costs related to the workforce make up the majority of most budgets.  The impact of downsizing the workforce is more involved than just eliminating salaries or wages.  Before making any decisions, remember that downsizing has related costs as well, including:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Unemployment benefits</li>\r\n    <li>Accrued time, including comp time</li>\r\n    <li>Severance pay</li>\r\n    <li>Outplacement assistance</li>\r\n    <li>Covering the responsibilities of the replaced position (including training costs and overtime)</li>\r\n    <li>Fees for a labor attorney or expanded services from local counsel</li>\r\n    <li>Health insurance â€“ employers are responsible a 65% health insurance subsidy for involuntary terminations from September 2008 through December 2009 due to new COBRA regulations, although the subsidy is later reimbursed through a payroll tax credit (watch the potential cash flow impact).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Study these costs before making downsizing decisions to avoid negative, unintended consequences to both the short-term and long-term cash flow.</p>\r\n<p>After evaluating carefully the financial landscape (immediate, next 24 months, and long-term), you can rationally determine if reductions in force (RIF) are needed.  Your will need to address many issues in the planning and implementation of the downsizing, including:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Consider what skills will be needed in the future, how top talent can be retained, and if services need to be reduced.</li>\r\n    <li>Establish criteria for downsizing decisions.  Will it be by performance?  By seniority?  The criteria cannot be vague, and they must be defensible.</li>\r\n    <li>Develop a list of individuals identified for a possible RIF and review it to ensure the result is not discriminatory by age, race, gender, religion or disability.  Consult with your legal counsel.</li>\r\n    <li>Under the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act of 1990, workers who waive their Age Discrimination Employment Act (ADEA) rights must do so knowingly and voluntarily, and they must have 45 days to consider the agreement.</li>\r\n    <li>Have an action and communication plan for the RIF that covers when and how employees will be notified, how their work will be concluded, and security measures regarding access to facilities, equipment and computer systems.</li>\r\n    <li>A corresponding plan is needed for employees who remain.  Expect low morale and perhaps reduced productivity as people adjust to the new situation.  Have a retention strategy to minimize the possibility that remaining employees leave because they fear for their own future or feel overwhelmed by additional responsibilities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>As you evaluate cost-reduction options, consider other alternatives to a RIF such as: reducing pay with a corresponding reduction in hours, furloughs, alternative work schedules, instituting a hiring freeze, freezing pay rates, reducing benefits, offering incentives for early retirement, or not filling positions created by normal retirements.  Be sure to involve managers and employees in cost-reduction discussions.  As you evaluate work flow process, you may discover efficiencies that can minimize RIFs.</p>\r\n<p>The overall goal is to deliver services to constituents as efficiently as possible.  By evaluating the financial and operational impact of all alternatives, you are poised to make the right strategic decisions.</p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance in evaluating the cost of downsizing, please contact us.</em></p>', 'The Cost of Downsizing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '543-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 19:47:39', '2011-01-18 19:47:39', '', 543, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/543-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(790, 5, '2011-01-18 20:25:18', '2011-01-18 20:25:18', '<p>We knew it was coming.  But large decreases in Net Assessed Values (NAV) are still unwelcome news as these numbers are becoming available.</p>\r\n<p>HEA 1001, passed in the 2008 session of the Indiana General Assembly, expanded the homestead deduction in 2009 by allowing an additional 35 percent reduction.  Here''s a simple example of how that works for a home valued at $100,000:</p>\r\n\r\n<table width="50%" border="1">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td></td>\r\n    <td>2008</td>\r\n    <td>2009</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Gross Assessed Value:<br />Market value</td>\r\n    <td>$100,000</td>\r\n    <td>$100,000</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Standard deduction</td>\r\n    <td>$45,000</td>\r\n    <td>$45,000</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Supplemental deduction</td>\r\n    <td></td>\r\n    <td>$19,250</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Net assessed value</td>\r\n    <td>$55,000</td>\r\n    <td>$35,750</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Multiply this decrease for every homestead in your taxing district, and you can begin to comprehend the full effect.  Based on specific studies and analyses around Indiana, taxing units have seen their NAV reduced by 10 to 25 percent, depending on their particular concentration of homesteads.</p>\r\n<p>In addition, many taxing units have been significantly affected by AV reductions or negative trending from plant shut downs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>NAV reduction has several impacts:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>With the new supplemental deduction, tax liability is shifted from homeowners to other taxpayer classes.</li>\r\n    <li>Revenues from rate-controlled funds such as Capital Project Funds and Cumulative Funds are reduced.</li>\r\n    <li>General Obligation bonding capacity is reduced.</li>\r\n    <li>Counties using local option income taxes to provide property tax credits to homesteads are experiencing very low property tax bills â€“ including some reduced to zero.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>How can you prepare for a significant reduction in NAV for 2009?</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Watch the 1782 Notices for possible limitations; the 2008 budget/rate advertisements may not have anticipated the actual reduction in NAV.</li>\r\n	<li>Given the shift in tax liability, you may want to consider restructuring local income taxes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>If the reduction in NAV is unwelcome news for your governmental unit, call Umbaugh for information and assistance.</p>', 'What Happened to My 2009 Net Assessed Value?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '547-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-18 20:25:18', '2011-01-18 20:25:18', '', 547, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/547-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(791, 5, '2011-01-18 20:28:37', '2011-01-18 20:28:37', '<p>As the 2010 budget preparation cycle begins, it''s time to think about protecting your maximum levy.  Many taxing units face revenue reductions in 2010 when the property tax caps are fully implemented, and due to overall economic conditions and a reduced tax base from expanded homestead credits.</p>\r\n<p>Many of your revenue sources are subject to maximum levy limits.  At budget time, you will try to match expenditures to the reduced revenues you expect.  You may be tempted to complete budget forms and approach hearings in ways that would generate a levy below the maximum, but be very careful before you do that.</p>\r\n<p>Under current rules and regulations, if you reduce maximum levy, you will not get it back in future years.  Reducing your maximum levy may have a lasting negative impact if you can not reach that levy again</p>\r\n<p>In addition, because of the Circuit Breaker legislation, your budget and the property tax revenues you receive are now impacted by the budgets of other taxing units in your tax base.  You will not receive a dollar-for-dollar benefit for reducing revenue loss.</p>\r\n<p>Your best strategy is to complete budget forms and structure your budget cycle to protect the maximum levy.  Recognize, though, that you will not collect the full levy amount because of the property tax caps.  You will need a second budget that reflects the realistic amount you expect to collect.  The second budget will provide a realistic picture as you determine whether you will need cost reductions and/or alternative revenues.</p>', 'Protecting Your Maximum Levy', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '550-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 20:28:37', '2011-01-18 20:28:37', '', 550, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/550-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(792, 3, '2011-01-21 19:00:11', '2011-01-21 19:00:11', '<h2>Our Services for Utilities</h2>\r\n					<p>If only it were as simple as turning on a faucet and letting an endless supply of resources flow to customers. But your job as the utility owner gets more difficult every day. Constantly increasing quality standards, new federal mandates and regulatory compliance are just the beginning. When times are good, you must plan ahead to serve more customers to support economic development.  But when customers are closing their doors, you must reduce operations and budgets - and balance good service with rates your customers can afford. </p>\r\n					<p>Financial management &ndash; UMBAUGH can make your day-to-day financial management easier with:</p>\r\n                    <ul class="left">\r\n                        <li>Accounting Systems Design, Implementation and Training</li>\r\n                        <li>Audit Preparation and Financial Reporting</li>\r\n                        <li>Financial Planning and Budget Assistance</li>\r\n                        <li>Financial Feasibility Studies</li>\r\n                        <li>Financial Management Reports</li>\r\n                        <li>GASB 34 Compliance</li>\r\n                        <li>Litigation Support Services/Expert Testimony</li>\r\n                    </ul>\r\n					<ul class="right">\r\n                        <li>Negotiating Inter-Governmental Agreements</li>\r\n                        <li>Performance Management Studies</li>\r\n                        <li>Privatization Analysis</li>\r\n                        <li>Studies of Impact and Fairness in Utility Wholesale Charges</li>\r\n                        <li>Studies Relating to Purchase of Private Utilities by Municipalities</li>\r\n                        <li>Utility Flow-Through Systems Analysis, Fuel Cost Charges and Tracking</li>\r\n                        <li>Utility Rate Studies and Cost-of-Service Analysis</li>\r\n                    </ul>\r\n\r\n					<p>Capital Planning - Utilities are capital-intensive. Like most municipal utilities, you may have aging infrastructure and equipment, need to grow and improve services or need to comply with ever-changing federal and state mandates. You need to find the resources to make those things happen.  UMBAUGH can help you with:</p>\r\n                    <ul class="left">\r\n                        <li>Long-Range Capital Planning</li>\r\n                        <li>Project Planning and Financial Development</li>\r\n                        <li>Developing and Evaluating Funding Alternatives</li>\r\n                        <li>Projects Financed by Federal Grants and Loans</li>\r\n                    </ul>\r\n					<ul class="right">\r\n                        <li>Capital Investment Funding Through System Development Charges</li>\r\n                        <li>Refinancing Existing Debt</li>\r\n                        <li>Financial Presentations to Elected Officials and the Public</li>\r\n                    </ul>\r\n\r\n					<p>Bond Issuance - Your don''t issue bonds every day, and you''ve got to get it right. The stakes are too high to risk a mistake or miss an opportunity to save. Since UMBAUGH is an independent advisor, our only priority is doing what''s best for the municipal and cooperatively -owned utilities we represent. We can provide:</p>\r\n					<ul class="left">\r\n                        <li>Official Statements and Bond Sale Preparations</li>\r\n                        <li>Presentations to Bond Ratings Agencies</li>\r\n                        <li>Evaluation of Bond Insurance Proposals</li>\r\n                        <li>Competitive Bond Sales and Electronic Bidding Services</li>\r\n                    </ul>\r\n					<ul class="right">\r\n                        <li>Negotiated Bond Sales and Private Placements</li>\r\n                        <li>Coordination of Bond Closings</li>\r\n                        <li>Assistance to the Trustee bank</li>\r\n					</ul>\r\n\r\n					<p>Post Issuance - Unfortunately, paperwork does not go away after the bonds are sold. You as the bond issuer have a great deal of responsibility for reporting and compliance, at a time when you''d much rather pay attention to your bond-funded project. UMBAUGH can take those worries off your plate as well with:</p>\r\n					<ul class="left">\r\n                        <li>In-Progress Construction Reports</li>\r\n                        <li>Arbitrage Rebate Calculations</li>\r\n                        <li>Continuing Disclosure Filings</li>\r\n                    </ul>\r\n					<ul class="right">\r\n                        <li>Post Issuance Tax Compliance</li>\r\n                        <li>Escrow Verifications</li>\r\n                        <li>Parity Reports</li>\r\n					</ul>', 'Utilities', 'Governmental units are constantly seeking new, better and more cost-effective solutions to the demand for energy and other services. UMBAUGH takes a comprehensive approach that begins with constructing a customized financial plan for your utility. We then effectively and clearly communicate the financial plan to help you get the necessary support to make your plan successful.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '213-revision-17', '', '', '2011-01-21 19:00:11', '2011-01-21 19:00:11', '', 213, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/213-revision-17', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(794, 5, '2011-01-18 21:07:17', '2011-01-18 21:07:17', '<p>Like all of you, we are still waiting for the most important bill of any long legislative session: the budget bill.  The budget will not be finalized until the Indiana General Assembly comes back for a special session â€“ and we don''t know yet when that will be.</p>\r\n<p>However, there were bills passed this session that will affect local governmental entities. We have summarized those bills below.  (Note that some bills are still awaiting the Governor''s signature.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>SB 346</strong>:  Beginning July 1, the county auditor will receive a fee of $10 from anyone who files a sales disclosure form for the sale of real property occurring between January 1, 2004 and December 31, 2011.  The auditor will deposit 50 percent in the county sales disclosure fund and 50 percent in the assessment training and administration fund.</p>\r\n<p><strong>SB 448</strong>:  This bill creates a new property tax exemption for Indiana businesses dedicated to computing, networking or data storage activities.  A business is eligible for the exemption if it invests at least $10 million in real and personal property located in Indiana after June 30, 2009, its average employee wage is at least 125 percent of the county average and the fiscal body of the county or municipality approves the exemption. The exemption applies only to the enterprise information technology equipment.</p>\r\n<p><strong>HB 1071</strong>:  This bill makes the model residence deduction retroactive to 2008-pay-2009. An owner is entitled to a 50 percent deduction from the assessed value for 2008-pay-2009 for a model residence first assessed as: (1) a partially completed structure; or (2) a fully completed structure on the March 1, 2008 assessment date and still a model residence on January 1, 2009.   If the 2008-pay-2009 property taxes have already been paid, the person who paid is entitled to a refund of the overpayment.</p>\r\n<p><strong>HB 1094</strong>: This bill makes a real property''s valuation date and assessment date the same beginning in 2010.  County auditors are no longer required to mail an annual information statement to each person liable for property taxes.  Form 11 and the property tax bill must include certain information concerning assessment appeals, including a notice that an appeal requires evidence of the property''s true tax value as of the assessment date.</p>\r\n<p><strong>HB 1096</strong>:  This bill allows two ways to apply for a mortgage deduction: (1) the person recording the mortgage, contract or memorandum may file a statement with the county recorder for real property or the county auditor for personal property mobile homes; or (2) the person claiming the mortgage deduction may file a statement with the county auditor.  </p>\r\n<p><strong>HB 1198</strong>: This bill amended IC 6-1.1-1-11 and 2-7, changing the definition of "personal property," defining "nonbusiness personal property," and addressing levy replacement grants for certain school corporations affected by circuit breaker credits.</p>\r\n<p><strong>HB 1230</strong>:  This bill requires that a notice published in a newspaper must also be posted on the newspaper''s Internet Web site, if the newspaper maintains one. The bill eliminates the requirement for a city to publish the ordinance setting elected city officers'' salaries. It requires all political subdivisions with the power to levy a tax and a budget of $300,000 or more to publish an annual report, if not already required under any other statute.</p>\r\n<p><strong>HB 1344</strong>:  Standard Deduction:  This bill requires sales disclosure forms and property tax bills to include information about the consequences of claiming more than one standard deduction and the procedures for terminating a standard deduction. The bill establishes other filing requirements for a standard deduction.</p>\r\n<p><em>Improper Deductions and Credits</em>: Tax bills for 2010, 2011 and 2012 must include a form for taxpayers to verify certain deductions and credits. The county auditor may terminate deductions or credits for 2012-pay-2013, if an individual does not verify the deductions and credits by January 1, 2013. The county auditor must provide advance notice of a proposed termination.</p>\r\n<p><em>Electronic Tax Statements</em>: This bill permits a county legislative body to transmit property tax bills and related information by e-mail.  The county treasurer and county auditor are responsible for administering the program. </p>\r\n<p><em>Electronic Tax Payments</em>: The bill allows automatic deductions of payments for property taxes and special assessments from any account held by a financial institution, not just from a checking account. Counties are required to distribute revenue from monthly installment property tax collections to political subdivisions at the normal semi-annual distribution date.</p>\r\n<p><strong>HB 1365</strong>:  This allows an owner of permanently flooded land or property accessed by permanently flooded land and not used for agricultural purposes to petition the county assessor for a reassessment.  This is retroactive to January 1, 2008.</p>\r\n<p><strong>HB 1432</strong>:  This bill requires the county auditor to distribute local income tax revenue to other taxing units no more than 10 business days after the county treasurer receives the distribution from the state.</p>\r\n<p>We are grateful to the Association of Indiana Counties for their legislative summaries, which were used as a resource for this article.  If you need more details on any of these new laws, please contact us.  </p>\r\n<p><em>In a future issue we''ll bring you news of the budget bill''s implications shortly after the much-anticipated special session concludes.</em></p>', 'How Did the 2009 General Assembly Affect Your Operations?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '556-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 21:07:17', '2011-01-18 21:07:17', '', 556, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/556-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(797, 3, '2011-01-21 19:13:44', '2011-01-21 19:13:44', '					<h2>Our Services for Schools</h2>\r\n					<p>Financial Management - As a school superintendent or business manager, you create and manage a budget so complex it could perplex a Fortune 500 CEO. Every day, you deal with multiple funding streams from federal, state and local governments, grants and other revenue sources, each with its own set of reporting requirements. Let UMBAUGH ease the strain with:</p>\r\n                        <ul class="left">\r\n                            <li>Accounting Systems Design, Implementation and Training</li>\r\n                            <li>Analytical Cost Studies</li>\r\n                            <li>Audit Preparation and Financial Reporting</li>\r\n                            <li>Budget Preparation and Assistance</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        \r\n                        <ul class="right">\r\n                            <li>Comprehensive Financial Planning</li>\r\n                            <li>GASB 34 Compliance</li>\r\n                            <li>Performance Management Studies</li>\r\n                            <li>Tax Revenue Analysis and Management</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n					\r\n                    <p>Capital Planning - Facilities are always a challenge. If your enrollment''s growing, you need more. If your buildings are old, you need to modernize for technology, replace infrastructure and save energy. And, oh yes, you need the support of your constitents to make that happen, which requires a clear financial plan. UMBAUGH can help you with:</p>\r\n		<ul class="left">\r\n                        <li>Debt Management Studies</li>\r\n                        <li>Long-Range Capital Planning and Implementation</li>\r\n                        <li>Project Planning and Financial Development</li>\r\n                        <li>Developing and Evaluating Funding Alternatives</li>\r\n               </ul>\r\n		<ul class="right">\r\n                        <li>Refinancing Existing Debt</li>\r\n                        <li>Referendum Preparation</li>\r\n			<li>Financial Presentations to Elected Officials and the Public</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n					\r\n                    <p>Bond Issuance - You don''t issue bonds every day, but they are getting more common as schools meet facility needs and raise revenue for operating costs.  Either way, you''ve got to get it right. The stakes are too high to risk a mistake or miss an opportunity to save. Since UMBAUGH is an independent advisor, our only priority is doing what''s best for the local governments we represent. We can provide:</p>\r\n		<ul class ="left">\r\n                        <li>Official Statements and Bond Sale Preparations</li>\r\n                        <li>Presentations to Bond Ratings Agencies</li>\r\n                        <li>Evaluation of Bond Insurance Proposals</li>\r\n                        <li>Competitive Bond Sales and Electronic Bidding Services</li>\r\n                </ul>\r\n                <ul class="right">\r\n                        <li>Negotiated Bond Sales and Private Placements</li>\r\n                        <li>Coordination of Bond Closings</li>\r\n                        <li>Assistance to the Trustee bank</li>\r\n                </ul>\r\n           <p>Post Issuance - Unfortunately, paperwork does not go away after the bonds are sold. You as the bond issuer have a great deal of responsibility for reporting and compliance, at a time when you''d much rather pay attention to your bond-funded project. UMBAUGH can take those worries off your plate as well with:</p>\r\n			<ul class="left">\r\n                        <li>In-Progress Construction Reports</li>\r\n                        <li>Arbitrage Rebate Calculations</li>\r\n                        <li>Continuing Disclosure Filings</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                         <ul class="right">\r\n                        <li>Post Issuance Tax Compliance</li>\r\n                        <li>Escrow Verifications</li>\r\n                        <li>Parity Reports</li>\r\n			</ul>', 'Schools', 'At UMBAUGH, we don''t represent both sides of the table. We represent you as a school district. Our independence from the bond underwriting assures you of the greatest objectivity in analyzing, determining and planning - whether that''s for capital improvements or operating funds.\r\n\r\nWe quickly respond to your needs. At public hearings, we calmly, accurately and professionally answer all the financial questions your constituents - and your board - will have.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '217-revision-14', '', '', '2011-01-21 19:13:44', '2011-01-21 19:13:44', '', 217, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/217-revision-14', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(799, 5, '2011-01-18 21:48:42', '2011-01-18 21:48:42', '<p>As local governments continue to feel the pinch from property tax reform and shrinking income tax revenues, they are searching for alternative ways to fund the infrastructure improvements needed for residential and commercial growth.  Local development impact fees have become popular nationwide and within the state as a funding source.</p>\r\n<p>Indiana enabling legislation defines impact fees as "[A] monetary charge imposed on new development by a unit to defray or mitigate the capital costs of infrastructure that is required by, necessitated by, or needed to serve the new development."  The General Assembly passed the legislation in 1991 and provided guidelines and procedures for local governments to impose impact fees on new development as a way to allow growth to pay for itself.</p>\r\n<p>Nationwide, impact fees are used to pay for schools, libraries, police/fire protection, sewer/water systems, parks and roads.  Indiana allows impact fees to be levied to pay for infrastructure improvements for parks, roads, water, sewers and flood control systems.  Currently, Fishers, Greenwood, Carmel, Noblesville and Zionsville are among the communities using impact fees in a variety of ways.</p>\r\n<p>Communities considering impact fees must develop a rational nexus that establishes new growth as the driver for needed infrastructure upgrades.  Once the community establishes that growth projections will necessitate infrastructure improvements, they may move forward to develop an impact fee for specific infrastructure needs.</p>\r\n<p>The community must develop a Master Plan that establishes level-of-service guidelines for the specific infrastructure.  The Master Plan includes an analysis of current community levels of service and the current and projected (10-year) deficiencies.  If the Master Plan documents that the projected deficiencies are due to growth in the community, then the rational nexus can be established, paving the way to calculate a legal impact fee.</p>\r\n<p>Impact fees are paid by the new development, and may be applied only to infrastructure projects made necessary by the new development.  Typically, the fees are collected when the building permit is issued, held in special accounts and disbursed as outlined in the Master Plan.  </p>\r\n<p>When local governments use impact fees as an alternative funding source for new development infrastructure improvements, they avoid the problem of requiring existing residents to pay for new development.</p>\r\n<p>We are eager to help governments determine the feasibility of using impact fees to meet their funding needs.  Please contact us at footnotes@umbaugh.com for more information.</p>', 'Impact Fees:  Alternative Revenue for Infrastructure Funding', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '564-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-18 21:48:42', '2011-01-18 21:48:42', '', 564, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/564-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(801, 5, '2011-01-18 21:53:12', '2011-01-18 21:53:12', '<p><em>Fourth article in a series.</em></p>\r\n<p>As details of the stimulus package in the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 have unfolded, it is clear that local communities will need to find local matching funds for their proposed infrastructure projects to improve bridges, roads, transit, energy and local water, wastewater and storm water systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We expect $4.3 billion for these types of projects in Indiana: $650 million for roads and bridges, $100 million for water quality, $80 million for public transit and $70 million for energy.  Additional dollars from competitive grants may become available. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>While you may not have finalized all the funding match details of your proposed projects, you can''t afford to wait until your projects are chosen to start planning for the match. To receive priority consideration, you will need to hit the ground running and have a good idea of the funding mix that will be available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Cash on hand</strong> -- Having cash available for the match is a quick and easy solution, but most communities do not have excess cash balances right now.  Even if you have cash on hand, you may decide that given today''s economic circumstances you''d rather hang on to cash balances to they can be available for other needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>New debt</strong> â€“ If you can''t match the federal stimulus funding with cash, your other option for a match is new debt.  In general, communities cannot simply go to the bank for a loan.  Specific procedures and requirements for issuing new debt are spelled out by various statutes.  There will be ordinances and resolutions to adopt and notices to issue, and you must allow sufficient periods of time for remonstrance, petitions or even a referendum.  Issuing debt is not a quick process, and that''s why you need to plan ahead. Get your team on board early, including an engineer, a grant administrator, a financial advisor and bond and local counsel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When it comes to stimulus projects, your project will only be "shovel ready" if you are prepared to be "funding match ready" as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In our next article, we''ll discuss the options and advantages of each of the two forms of new debt, revenue-supported bonds and property tax supported debt.</p>', 'Finding matching funds for your stimulus projects', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '566-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-18 21:53:12', '2011-01-18 21:53:12', '', 566, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/566-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(803, 5, '2011-01-19 14:16:07', '2011-01-19 14:16:07', '<p>Third article in a series.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As predicted, the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 was passed and signed in February, and it contains an Economic Recovery Package â€“ or stimulus package â€“ with several provisions to help local communities rebuild their infrastructure â€“ bridges, roads and local water and wastewater systems.</p>\r\n<p>Details are being worked out, and there is still much that is unknown about how much money will be available in Indiana and how the stimulus funds will be distributed.</p>\r\n<p>Here is what we know at this point in time:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><strong>If you haven''t done so, enter your potential projects on the www.bsu.edu/cber Web site</strong>.  The deadline for entering projects or making changes is <strong>noon March 9</strong>.  This is not a grant application; it is a support and coordination tool, but it is important to enter your project information.  Include Indiana Department of Transportation projects as well as State Revolving Fund (SRF) projects.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Not all projects will be funded</strong>.  As of late last week, 6,800 projects had been entered and more are expected.  </li>\r\n    <li><strong>Priority will be given to projects that are ready to proceed, that leverage private investment and that stimulate job creation</strong>.  Most approved projects will still need to fund a minimum local match of 20 to 30 percent.  </li>\r\n    <li><strong>No money is going to the State</strong>.  All monies will be distributed through existing federal programs which are very competitive nationwide.  State agencies such as Indiana Economic Development Corporation (IEDC) and the Indiana Association of Regional Councils will serve as subject matter experts, guide projects to the most appropriate funding sources and help maximize the amount of federal dollars flowing to Indiana.  (Note that stimulus money for schools has a different process and will be distributed to the State.)</li>\r\n    <li><strong>There will be a significant amount available for 2008 flood recovery programs</strong> if you are in one of the counties approved for 2008 disaster assistance.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>The analysis for potential projects will begin March 20.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Communities that want serious consideration should continue working to develop their project(s), because projects that can be implemented quickly will definitely have an advantage.</p>', 'Deadlines Looming As Stimulus Package Details Unfold', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '577-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 14:16:07', '2011-01-19 14:16:07', '', 577, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/577-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(805, 5, '2011-01-25 18:12:41', '2011-01-25 18:12:41', 'Third article in a series.\r\n\r\nAs predicted, the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 was passed and signed in February, and it contains an Economic Recovery Package â€“ or stimulus package â€“ with several provisions to help local communities rebuild their infrastructure â€“ bridges, roads and local water and wastewater systems.\r\n\r\nDetails are being worked out, and there is still much that is unknown about how much money will be available in Indiana and how the stimulus funds will be distributed.\r\n\r\nHere is what we know at this point in time:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>If you haven''t done so, enter your potential projects on the www.bsu.edu/cber Web site</strong>.  The deadline for entering projects or making changes is <strong>noon March 9</strong>.  This is not a grant application; it is a support and coordination tool, but it is important to enter your project information.  Include Indiana Department of Transportation projects as well as State Revolving Fund (SRF) projects.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Not all projects will be funded</strong>.  As of late last week, 6,800 projects had been entered and more are expected.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Priority will be given to projects that are ready to proceed, that leverage private investment and that stimulate job creation</strong>.  Most approved projects will still need to fund a minimum local match of 20 to 30 percent.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>No money is going to the State</strong>.  All monies will be distributed through existing federal programs which are very competitive nationwide.  State agencies such as Indiana Economic Development Corporation (IEDC) and the Indiana Association of Regional Councils will serve as subject matter experts, guide projects to the most appropriate funding sources and help maximize the amount of federal dollars flowing to Indiana.  (Note that stimulus money for schools has a different process and will be distributed to the State.)</li>\r\n	<li><strong>There will be a significant amount available for 2008 flood recovery programs</strong> if you are in one of the counties approved for 2008 disaster assistance.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>The analysis for potential projects will begin March 20.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCommunities that want serious consideration should continue working to develop their project(s), because projects that can be implemented quickly will definitely have an advantage.', 'Deadlines Looming As Stimulus Package Details Unfold', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '577-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:12:41', '2011-01-25 18:12:41', '', 577, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/577-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
