chedule be optional or mandatory?</li>\r\n    <li>How will the schedule impact paid holidays and paid leave?  </li>\r\n    <li>How will you provide equity for employees on the alternative and traditional schedules?</li>\r\n    <li>Who will be eligible for the alternative work schedule and who makes that determination?</li>\r\n    <li>What kind of training will be needed for supervisors and employees?</li>\r\n    <li>Will we need different record keeping requirements and evaluation methods?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Continuous monitoring is critical to the success of the new schedule and will help ensure programs are aligned with your goals and expectations.</p>\r\n<p>We are all waiting to see what the future will bring.  Additional economic and legislative changes could increase the need to adapt you service delivery model.  Additional economic challenges could reduce property and income tax revenues.  Services and structure of county government could change dramatically as ideas from the Kernan/Shepard report are implemented.  All of these changes may make alternative work schedules a desirable strategy to adjust to new ways of doing business.</p>', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '579-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-19 15:13:33', '2011-01-19 15:13:33', '', 579, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/579-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(813, 5, '2011-01-25 18:30:05', '2011-01-25 18:30:05', '<em>(Part 2 of a 2-part series)</em>\r\n\r\nLocal government officials in many communities are finding it increasingly difficult to fund public safety services with existing levels of revenues and property tax.  Establishing a fire territory is an option that can provide a new revenue stream for fire services. If your community is considering establishing a fire territory, it is a good idea to begin the process now to meet the statutory deadline of March 1, 2010 to have a fire territory beginning in 2011.\r\n\r\nThe following are excerpts from an interview with James VanGorder. Chief VanGorder has been a fire chief in Zionsville since 1997 for both the volunteer fire department and the Town''s fire department. In 2007, he was appointed to his current position as the full-time fire chief of the Zionsville Fire Territory.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q:</strong> What are positive and negative changes that have occurred since the fire territory was established?\r\n\r\n<strong>A:</strong> A positive change is that the fire department was able to move from a part-time, standby department to a full-time department with 40 employees.  The one negative thing was the removal of the three-year operating levy phase-in, which took away some flexibility for future fire territories.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q:</strong> Did you meet much resistance from fire fighters or taxpayers while forming the fire territory?\r\n\r\n<strong>A:</strong> The response was mostly favorable.  We conducted 13 public meetings to present the Department''s strategic plan and the financial/taxpayer impact of the territory.  It was important to keep all parties well educated and well informed.  In addition to the public meetings, we held bi-monthly working group meetings with Fire Department, Town and Township officials.  In the end, everyone agreed that a fire territory was a good idea and the benefits outweighed the costs.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q:</strong> What are major issues to consider when forming a fire territory?\r\n\r\n<strong>A:</strong> Two major issues we faced were the formation of the fire territory board and the position of fire chief.  Since those were concerns of both parties, we confronted those issues up front and resolved them in a professional manner by listening and working together to come up with a mutually agreeable solution.\r\n\r\nFiguring out who was to be on the fire territory board was a difficult decision because there were only two taxing units involved and three positions to fill.  After much discussion, we decided to have one person represent each taxing unit and the third board member would be mutually agreed upon.  If we could not agree on the appointee, the Town and the Township would alternate in choosing the board member.\r\n\r\nThere were concerns that one taxing unit would have all control over the fire chief position.  To resolve the problem, we included a section in the establishing ordinance which said the fire chief could be removed at any time by majority vote of the fire territory board.\r\n\r\nTo read the first part of Chief VanGorder''s interview, see the November 11 issue of Footnotes.  Umbaugh has assisted many local entities with feasibility studies to determine if a fire territory would be advantageous.  We understand the nuances, government levy issues, tips to make a new arrangement successful and pitfalls to avoid.', 'Don''t Burn Through the Deadline to Establish A Fire Territory For 2011: Key Perspectives from a Fire Chief', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '593-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:30:05', '2011-01-25 18:30:05', '', 593, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/593-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(814, 5, '2011-01-19 18:08:08', '2011-01-19 18:08:08', '<p><strong>(Part 1 of a 2-part series)</strong></p>\r\n<p>Local government officials in many communities are finding it increasingly difficult to fund public safety services with existing levels of revenues and property tax.  Establishing a fire territory is an option that can provide a new revenue stream for fire services. If your community is considering establishing a fire territory, it is a good idea to begin the process now to meet the statutory deadline of March 1, 2010 to have a fire territory beginning in 2011.</p>\r\n<p>The following are excerpts from an interview with James VanGorder. Chief VanGorder has been a fire chief in Zionsville since 1997 for both the volunteer fire department and the Town''s fire department. In 2007, he was appointed to his current position as the full-time fire chief of the Zionsville Fire Territory.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q:</strong>  Why did the Town form a fire territory?</p>\r\n<p><strong>A:</strong>  It was formed primarily for two reasons: 1) to provide funding for fire operations in a rapidly growing community that was finding it increasingly difficult to pay for and maintain an acceptable level of fire services and 2) to establish mutual governance and direct oversight of the fire department.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q:</strong>  What is the biggest advantage of forming a fire territory?</p>\r\n<p><strong>A:</strong>  It allows multiple taxing units to participate jointly in oversight and governance of the fire department.  In addition, it allows flexibility in financing operations, governance and long-range planning.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Q:</strong>  What was your experience with having other taxing units come on board with the fire territory and what advice would you give on this topic?  </p>\r\n<p><strong>A:</strong>  The key is open communication.  Early in the process, the Town and Township officials met to identify concerns, and we worked together as a group to develop creative ways to resolve the issues.  Fortunately, the fire territory law is broad, which allows a great deal of flexibility in structuring the fire territory. A common misconception is that when a fire territory is formed, fire departments are disbanded and volunteer fire contracts are eliminated.  This simply is not true.  The current structure and contractual agreements can remain the same.  </p>\r\n<p>Umbaugh has assisted many local entities with feasibility studies to determine if a fire territory would be advantageous.  We understand the nuances, government levy issues, tips to make a new arrangement successful and pitfalls to avoid.  If you have questions or need assistance, please contact us.</p>', 'Don''t Burn Through The Deadline To Establish A Fire Territory For 2011 Key Perspectives From A Fire Chief', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '602-revision-5', '', '', '2011-01-19 18:08:08', '2011-01-19 18:08:08', '', 602, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/602-revision-5', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(817, 5, '2011-01-19 17:46:10', '2011-01-19 17:46:10', '<p>Part 2</p>\r\n<p>Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds are two new financing tools created by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act â€“ commonly known as the federal stimulus program.  If you missed the general description of these bonds that allow you to finance projects at lower interest costs, please see our October 28 issue of Footnotes.  </p>\r\n<p>Because these two allocations are available only through the end of 2010, they are most applicable for projects that are already in the planning or approval stages.  All of the normal Indiana statutes for obtaining project approval still apply, including petition and remonstrance or referendum.  </p>\r\n<p>Both of these new funding mechanisms must be used in areas designated as recovery zones.  County Commissioners have the authority to define the geographic area that constitutes a recovery zone â€“ and some have chosen to designate the entire county.  County Commissioners also have the authority to decide which projects will be allowed to use the county''s allocations for these programs.  If a city or county does not use its full allocation, those allocations may revert to the state for use in other parts of Indiana.</p>\r\n<p>If you have a project at the local level you think might be appropriate for Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds or Recovery Zone Facility Bonds, make your County Commissioners aware of it as soon as possible.  They will be reviewing options and making decisions about the allocation, and you want your project to be among those considered.</p>\r\n<p>If your particular area has an allocation that is too low for the project (or projects) you have in mind, consider reaching out to your neighboring communities or counties and taking a regional approach to pool your allocations to achieve a project that you could not accomplish individually.</p>\r\n<p>As we have all seen, interest rates and bond markets can change very quickly.  Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds may or may not be the most cost-efficient means of financing at any given time, but they should be evaluated when you assemble your project''s funding package.</p>\r\n<p>We at Umbaugh can help you determine the allocation amount available for your area, evaluate what projects are appropriate for these bonds, calculate the advantages of various financing mechanisms and help you implement the most cost-effective financing to put your locality on the road to economic recovery.</p>\r\n<p>If you have questions about Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds, please contact us.</p>', 'Save Money For a Limited Time Only: Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '600-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 17:46:10', '2011-01-19 17:46:10', '', 600, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/600-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(819, 5, '2011-01-19 19:13:26', '2011-01-19 19:13:26', '<p>At the risk of sounding like a late-night TV commercial, let me introduce you to a limited-time offer that may have financial benefits for your area.  Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds are two new financing tools created by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act â€“ commonly known as the federal stimulus program.  </p>\r\n<p>These two financing mechanisms do not provide money for projects, but they may allow you to finance projects at lower interest costs.</p>\r\n<p>The U.S. Treasury allocated $313 million in Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and $469 million in Recovery Zone Facility Bonds for Indiana.  They further made allocations to large cities (Indianapolis, Evansville, Fort Wayne and South Bend) and to each county based on impact from the economic down turn as measured by unemployment and foreclosure rates, among other factors.  Eighty nine of Indiana''s 92 counties qualify for these programs and received allocations for each type of financing from the U.S. Treasury.</p>\r\n<p>Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds are for public projects.  These bonds are sold at taxable interest rates, but 45% of the interest will be paid by a subsidy from the U.S. Treasury, and 55% is paid by the local governmental unit issuing the bonds.  In the current market, this is a lower effective rate than tax-exempt financing.  They are similar to Build America Bonds, but the Build America Bond interest subsidy is only 35%.</p>\r\n<p>Recovery Zone Facility Bonds are for private projects.  They are similar to the Industrial Revenue Bonds (IRBs) in that they give private companies access to tax-exempt financing rates.  The main difference from traditional IRBs is that the types of entities eligible for this type of financing is greatly expanded. The most likely use for Recovery Zone Facility Bonds is to finance building or renovating private facilities that will create new jobs.  The local governmental entity is the issuer of the bonds, but the private company provides the security on the bonds.</p>\r\n<p>In out next newsletter, we will go into more depth as to how or when these new financing tools should be considered.  In the meantime, if you need information on what allocations your County received or; if you have questions about the use Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds, please contact us.</p>', 'Save Money For a Limited Time Only: Recovery Zone Economic Development Bonds and Recovery Zone Facility Bonds', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '612-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 19:13:26', '2011-01-19 19:13:26', '', 612, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/612-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(820, 5, '2011-01-19 19:14:21', '2011-01-19 19:14:21', '<p>If you read the titles of documents lining your bookshelf surely there is a budget or two, probably several audits and just maybe your government''s strategic plan.  Now, the real question: how thick is the dust on these items?</p>\r\n<p>After you examine process improvement (see Sept. 30 issue of Footnotes), we recommend you either take your strategic plan off the shelf or implement a strategic planning process.  Strategic plans are valuable tools for outlining and understanding your priorities and improving in the eyes of your constituents.  Over time, the underlying theories and recognized best practice approaches to strategic planning have evolved and improved in three major phases.</p>\r\n<p>Originally, strategic planning was performed almost exclusively by executives and governing boards, and they developed goals and strategies away from operations.  Staff participated only in the execution -- when they became responsible for providing the services.  Eventually, the absence of practical expertise and knowledge became major pitfalls.  Plan development was disconnected from plan execution, and the resulting plan lacked employee buy-in and failed to deliver outcomes.</p>\r\n<p>Leaders seeking new approaches turned to whole systems, where all with a stake in the outcome of the plan participated in creating it â€“ allowing for the influence of diverse perspectives and resulting in more honest recognition of challenges and goals.  Executives and boards still had a significant role to play, as their ongoing leadership is critical, but plan development and implementation remained disconnected.</p>\r\n<p>The third phase endures today: broad participation is encouraged in stating where the government should go and specifically how it will get there â€“ including how progress can be evaluated.  Staff input is commonly valued for action planning and defining measurement.  By instilling accountability, this form of strategic planning offers leaders an opportunity to first define success and then measure it.  </p>\r\n<p>To become high impact tools and steer clear of that dusty bookshelf, the strategic plan must continue to evolve with the integration of detailed action plans (with defined responsibility and timelines) as well as performance measures. </p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance with process improvement or strategic planning, Umbaugh partners with Sikich, a leading provider of professional services in the Midwest serving government, business and not-for-profit organizations. Please contact us.</em></p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: An Evolving Model for High Impact Strategic Planning', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '614-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 19:14:21', '2011-01-19 19:14:21', '', 614, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/614-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
