(822, 5, '2011-01-25 18:48:23', '2011-01-25 18:48:23', 'If you read the titles of documents lining your bookshelf surely there is a budget or two, probably several audits and just maybe your government''s strategic plan.  Now, the real question: how thick is the dust on these items?\r\n\r\nAfter you examine process improvement (see Sept. 30 issue of Footnotes), we recommend you either take your strategic plan off the shelf or implement a strategic planning process.  Strategic plans are valuable tools for outlining and understanding your priorities and improving in the eyes of your constituents.  Over time, the underlying theories and recognized best practice approaches to strategic planning have evolved and improved in three major phases.\r\n\r\nOriginally, strategic planning was performed almost exclusively by executives and governing boards, and they developed goals and strategies away from operations.  Staff participated only in the execution -- when they became responsible for providing the services.  Eventually, the absence of practical expertise and knowledge became major pitfalls.  Plan development was disconnected from plan execution, and the resulting plan lacked employee buy-in and failed to deliver outcomes.\r\n\r\nLeaders seeking new approaches turned to whole systems, where all with a stake in the outcome of the plan participated in creating it â€“ allowing for the influence of diverse perspectives and resulting in more honest recognition of challenges and goals.  Executives and boards still had a significant role to play, as their ongoing leadership is critical, but plan development and implementation remained disconnected.\r\n\r\nThe third phase endures today: broad participation is encouraged in stating where the government should go and specifically how it will get there â€“ including how progress can be evaluated.  Staff input is commonly valued for action planning and defining measurement.  By instilling accountability, this form of strategic planning offers leaders an opportunity to first define success and then measure it.\r\n\r\nTo become high impact tools and steer clear of that dusty bookshelf, the strategic plan must continue to evolve with the integration of detailed action plans (with defined responsibility and timelines) as well as performance measures.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance with process improvement or strategic planning, Umbaugh partners with Sikich, a leading provider of professional services in the Midwest serving government, business and not-for-profit organizations. Please contact us.</em>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: An Evolving Model for High Impact Strategic Planning', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '614-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-25 18:48:23', '2011-01-25 18:48:23', '', 614, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/614-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(823, 5, '2011-01-19 19:28:47', '2011-01-19 19:28:47', '<p>Indiana Office of Community and Rural Affairs (OCRA) is proposing grant funding for numerous types of projects in counties declared eligible for Federal Disaster Funding.</p>\r\n<p>Eighty two of Indiana''s 92 counties were federally declared disaster areas in 2008 due to severe flooding in northern Indiana (DR-1740) early in the year, tornados and severe flooding in late May and early June (DR-1766), and severe flooding in northern Indiana from the remnants of Hurricane Ike in early September (DR-1975).  The state experienced an estimated $1.9 billion in damage to public infrastructure, housing and farmland.  Damage to Indiana''s infrastructure alone is estimated at $325 million.</p>\r\n<p>The State of Indiana recently released a "substantial amendment" to its Action Plan for Disaster Recovery.  The amendment will guide the distribution of an additional $253,340,079 of Community Development Block Grant Disaster Recovery Funding to meet housing, infrastructure, business, public service, public facility and other needs in the 82 affected counties.</p>\r\n<p>Indiana Office of Community and Rural Affairs is proposing grant funding for numerous types of projects in 2010 to counties declared eligible for Federal Disaster Funding.</p>\r\n<p>While many of the details are still unknown, the categories most interesting to units of local government are an additional:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Nearly $25 million for stormwater drainage projects ($1 million maximum grant)</li>\r\n    <li>$50 million for water and wastewater projects (SRF/USDA-RD approved  projects)</li>\r\n    <li>$30 million for water and wastewater small projects ($1 million maximum grant)</li>\r\n    <li>$25 million for dam/levee improvements (Distributed at OCRA''s discretion)</li>\r\n    <li>$15 million for waterway debris removal</li>\r\n    <li>$20 million for community economic development (case-by-case determination)</li>\r\n    <li>$6 million for clearance/demolition ($500,000 maximum grant)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Another $13 million is available for floodplain/green space acquisition, $5 million for community revitalization, $23 million for owner-occupied rehabilitation and $28 million for multi-family rental housing.</p>\r\n<p>If your area is still struggling to recover from 2008 weather events, this is your opportunity to request grant funding.  Eligible projects will either have sustained damage or be vital to the economic recovery of the area.</p>\r\n<p>Each project category area has its own priorities and award limits.  In many cases grant applications will be accepted and awards made until funding is no longer available ("non-competitive").  Other categories will award grants in competitive funding rounds.</p>\r\n<p>More information from OCRA is available at www.ocra.IN.gov or 800-824-2476.</p>\r\n<p>If you have projects and need assistance, please contact us.</p>', 'Additional Disaster Recovery Funding Announced for Areas Affected by 2008 Flooding', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '616-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 19:28:47', '2011-01-19 19:28:47', '', 616, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/616-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(825, 5, '2011-01-19 19:44:40', '2011-01-19 19:44:40', '<p>All organizations achieve excellence by satisfying three core expectations: meeting customer needs, providing quality products and services, and employing efficient operations.  The best tools to meet such expectations are strategic planning, performance measurement and process improvement.  </p>\r\n<p>A process is how work gets accomplished.  As service demands change, the processes that produce those services must also evolve.  Without constant re-evaluation, processes stagnate â€“ resulting in increased costs, poor quality, inefficient service delivery and constituent dissatisfaction.</p>\r\n<p>Several widely used methods can improve your processes, including: Business Process Reengineering, Six Sigma, Lean, and Total Quality Management. But don''t let the buzz-word terminology turn you off, because all these programs have common steps that can be used by your governmental unit in any process-improvement effort.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Plan and organize</strong> â€“ Identify a leader to support and guide the effort, charter a team to perform the evaluation and make recommendations, set a mission, define the project scope, and analyze customer needs and concerns.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Map</strong> â€“ Plot out detailed flow charts of all current process steps and requirements.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Identify and Analyze</strong> â€“ Look at time constraints and quality problems, evaluate structural process issues, and analyze individual process steps.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Recommend</strong> â€“ Outline all potential opportunities for improvement.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Implement</strong> â€“ Meet with stakeholders to review draft recommendations, assign responsibility for specific actions, implement improvements, and ensure results by gathering data and feedback and checking progress.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Given the number of hours and resources allocated to producing services, organizations typically put little thought into the underlying process, but the efficiency of the process determines the success of meeting constituents'' needs and expectations.  Simply put, process improvement is an excellent tool for optimizing your efficiency. </p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance with process improvement or strategic planning, Umbaugh partners with Sikich, a leading provider of professional services in the Midwest serving government, business and not-for-profit organizations. Please contact us.<em></p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: The Process-Oriented Organization', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '618-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-19 19:44:40', '2011-01-19 19:44:40', '', 618, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/618-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(826, 5, '2011-01-19 19:45:31', '2011-01-19 19:45:31', '<p>New economic data suggests that the nearly two-year recession the country has been weathering is now over according to the Federal government.  This is good news, but most experts acknowledge that times will continue to be financially challenging for the foreseeable future.  In fact, it is likely that we will continue to see companies consolidating or closing facilities -- or declaring bankruptcy in some instances.</p>\r\n<p>In many communities across the state, municipal utilities provide service to large customers that generate a significant amount of the utility''s annual revenues.  Keep in mind that "large" and "significant" are relative terms.  A $20,000-per-year customer means more to a utility with annual revenues of $100,000 than it does to a utility with annual revenues of $10 million.  Situations where the loss of a large customer would seriously impact the ongoing ability of the utility to meet its financial requirements need to be monitored closely and proactively managed.  Talk to company representatives often so you are not surprised by a sudden reduction or departure.  In some cases, the utility may be able to employ strategies to assist the large customer.  If your customer has already made the difficult decision to leave, it''s too late to analyze potential options, so keep your lines of communication open and active.</p>\r\n<p>If you need assistance with analyzing options to help retain a large customer or if you are dealing with the impact of a recent departure of a major industry, please contact us.</p>', 'Monitor the Economic Health of Your Large Utility Customers', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '621-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 19:45:31', '2011-01-19 19:45:31', '', 621, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/621-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(827, 5, '2011-01-21 19:31:24', '2011-01-21 19:31:24', '<p>Just like a child waiting for a promised gift to arrive in the mail, school districts and local governments in parts of Indiana are still anxiously awaiting semiannual property tax receipts that traditionally arrive in June and December.  Even worse, entities in some parts of the state know the distributions are still far away because tax bills haven''t been sent to taxpayers yet.  Meanwhile, payrolls and utilities must still be paid and services must still be provided.</p>\r\n<p>Unless you can draw on cash reserves indefinitely, you will have to borrow to meet cash flow needs using temporary loan warrants.  Borrowing doesn''t reflect badly on your financial management.  It is a nearly universal necessity in parts of the state where tax collections have been delayed.</p>\r\n<p>A warrant is specific to a particular fund.  Schools normally borrow against the collections for the General Fund, the Transportation Fund, the Capital Projects Fund, the Debt Service and Pension Debt Service Fund.  The principal of the warrant is payable from the designated fund, but schools have the option to pay the interest from the Debt Service Fund.  The option of paying interest from a Debt Service fund is not available to other governmental entities.  However, libraries, fire departments, cities and other local governmental units are experiencing the same need for tax anticipation warrants. </p>\r\n<p>State law limits the principal of a warrant to 80 percent of the semiannual property tax distribution that is dedicated to paying the warrant.  As long as 80 percent of property taxes are collected, the warrant holder will be repaid.  Although achieving 80 percent of collections is somewhat of a concern in these challenging times, historically it is very rare for collections to be less than 90 percent.  Additional federal guidelines apply to the warrant amounts, and you will need to apply both federal and state tests before establishing the amount for your warrant.</p>\r\n<p>The credit analysis for a tax anticipation warrant will include current financial information, the assessed valuation in your taxing district, the percentage of property tax collections in recent years, and a list of the largest current taxpayers in the taxing district.  Growth projections and fund balances are not relevant since the warrant is a first lien on the distribution of property taxes or state aid distributions.  </p>\r\n<p>Since state law has removed school districts'' General Funds from the local property tax levy, current warrants for school General Funds are issued against state tuition support distributions and are subject to the same 80 percent limitation.</p>\r\n<p>A warrant must mature in the same year it was issued. If property tax collections will be later than December 31, it will be necessary to issue warrants initially with a December 31 maturity, and refund them later with a new maturity date.</p>\r\n<p>If your unit of government needs tax anticipation warrants to fulfill financial obligations before tax collections come in, Umbaugh can help with:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Preparing cash flow projections</li>\r\n    <li>Preparing a term sheet to explain all loan terms in easily understood language</li>\r\n    <li>Preparing a bid form</li>\r\n    <li>Sending the documents above to potential purchasers, along with legal documents prepared by bond counsel</li>\r\n    <li>Coordinating and hosting a competitive sale</li>\r\n    <li>Summarizing the bid results and determining the lowest bidder</li>\r\n    <li>Distributing the after-sale letter with wire transfer and closing instructions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>If you need help with a tax anticipation warrant, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Tax Anticipation Warrants Nearly A Necessity With Late Property Tax Distributions', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '623-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-21 19:31:24', '2011-01-21 19:31:24', '', 623, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/623-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(829, 5, '2011-01-21 10:43:53', '2011-01-21 10:43:53', '<p>The first four parts of this series have covered how to structure sufficient revenue from your existing tax base to continue to provide the services your constituents expect.  This article goes beyond that to examine increasing your tax base.  </p>\r\n<p>Growth in assessed value minimizes total property tax rates and the revenue losses from associated with the new tax caps.  Growth in your employment base helps offset the natural swings in local income tax revenues that result from shifts in the economy.  Growth of investment and employment are both necessary to provide a stable source of tax revenue, and economic development can accomplish both.</p>\r\n<p>No one should ever "give away the farm" in attracting economic development.  Most localities have been smart about matching their incentives to the potential benefits that the economic development can deliver.  But in the current economic environment, the incentives must be strategic and precise to produce the economic benefit you''re hoping for.</p>\r\n<p>There is no "one size fits all" formula to follow.  Instead, you should develop flexible incentive guidelines that consider:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>the level of investment,</li>\r\n	<li>the probable term of investment,</li>\r\n	<li>the number of jobs created and</li>\r\n	<li>the value of the payrolls created or retained.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Use a tiered approach to tax abatements so you offer longer abatement periods only to those projects with largest investments, more jobs and higher payrolls.   Use that same tiered approach to determine the amount of the investment that will qualify for abatement.</p>\r\n<p>You can apply a tiered approach to the use of tax increment financing (TIF) as well:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Limit TIF use to those projects with larger investments, more jobs and higher payrolls. </li>\r\n	<li>Limit the amount of investment captured by the TIF allocation area.</li>\r\n	<li>Consider using TIF for only those projects that develop infrastructure capacity that can attract additional future investment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The benefits of economic development don''t happen overnight.  It takes time to produce the desired results, but the long-term benefits of increased revenue from income and property taxes are clear.  With the new restrictions on tax increment allocation areas brought by HEA 1001 in 2008 and challenging economic conditions, the old ways of approaching economic development no longer apply.  But if you are smart and strategic, the economic benefits of minimizing the impact of property tax caps, keeping local services funded and keeping property taxes low are worth the effort.</p>\r\n<p>Remember that one of the most important factors in business location decisions is quality of life.  If reductions in your traditional revenue sources are causing you to consider cutting back services, remember that if cuts adversely affect the quality of life too severely, you will hurt your competitive position in economic development opportunities.   </p>\r\n<p><em>If you have questions or need assistance with structuring economic development incentives, please contact us.</em></p>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: Grow Your Tax Base', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '627-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-21 10:43:53', '2011-01-21 10:43:53', '', 627, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/627-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(830, 5, '2011-01-25 19:13:00', '2011-01-25 19:13:00', '<div>\r\n<p id="internal-source-marker_0.6940877556335181"><em>Part 5 in a series</em></p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nThe first four parts of this series have covered how to structure sufficient revenue from your existing tax base to continue to provide the services your constituents expect.  This article goes beyond that to examine increasing your tax base.\r\n\r\nGrowth in assessed value minimizes total property tax rates and the revenue losses from associated with the new tax caps.  Growth in your employment base helps offset the natural swings in local income tax revenues that result from shifts in the economy.  Growth of investment and employment are both necessary to provide a stable source of tax revenue, and economic development can accomplish both.\r\n\r\nNo one should ever "give away the farm" in attracting economic development.  Most localities have been smart about matching their incentives to the potential benefits that the economic development can deliver.  But in the current economic environment, the incentives must be strategic and precise to produce the economic benefit you''re hoping for.\r\n\r\nThere is no "one size fits all" formula to follow.  Instead, you should develop flexible incentive guidelines that consider:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>the level of investment,</li>\r\n	<li>the probable term of investment,</li>\r\n	<li>the number of jobs created and</li>\r\n	<li>the value of the payrolls created or retained.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUse a tiered approach to tax abatements so you offer longer abatement periods only to those projects with largest investments, more jobs and higher payrolls.   Use that same tiered approach to determine the amount of the investment that will qualify for abatement.\r\n\r\nYou can apply a tiered approach to the use of tax increment financing (TIF) as well:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Limit TIF use to those projects with larger investments, more jobs and higher payrolls.</li>\r\n	<li>Limit the amount of investment captured by the TIF allocation area.</li>\r\n	<li>Consider using TIF for only those projects that develop infrastructure capacity that can attract additional future investment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe benefits of economic development don''t happen overnight.  It takes time to produce the desired results, but the long-term benefits of increased revenue from income and property taxes are clear.  With the new restrictions on tax increment allocation areas brought by HEA 1001 in 2008 and challenging economic conditions, the old ways of approaching economic development no longer apply.  But if you are smart and strategic, the economic benefits of minimizing the impact of property tax caps, keeping local services funded and keeping property taxes low are worth the effort.\r\n\r\nRemember that one of the most important factors in business location decisions is quality of life.  If reductions in your traditional revenue sources are causing you to consider cutting back services, remember that if cuts adversely affect the quality of life too severely, you will hurt your competitive position in economic development opportunities.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance with structuring economic development incentives, please contact us.</em>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency: Grow Your Tax Base', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '627-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-25 19:13:00', '2011-01-25 19:13:00', '', 627, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/627-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
