(831, 5, '2011-01-20 16:06:30', '2011-01-20 16:06:30', '<p>It goes without saying that Indiana public schools are facing current and possibly future significant revenue challenges.  First you have the recent State budget reductions and a rumored second round of reductions later this year.  Then you have property tax caps -- coupled with the 35% supplemental Homestead Credit, which has reduced net assessed valuations -- therefore decreasing certain property-tax-supported school corporation funds.</p>\r\n<p>Less publicized than the State budget cuts, schools'' Capital Project Funds began being negatively impacted in 2009 by the new 35% Homestead Credit.  Most revenue reductions range from 10% to 20%, with additional reductions possible from property tax caps.  These reductions have already forced some schools to make difficult choices within their current capital project plans.</p>\r\n<p>What is the answer to fulfilling growing technology needs when you have a decrease in available Capital Projects Fund revenue?  Delaying needed improvements only delays the inevitable and surely costs more and compounds the problem in future years.</p>\r\n<p>One approach schools should consider is expanding the capital planning process.  The Department of Local Government Finance currently requires schools to prepare a three-year capital planning budget on an annual basis.  To be a more effective tool, the plan could be expanded to five, seven or ten years and also incorporate the Debt Service Fund as part of a master capital plan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are several benefits to expanding the planning horizon and including the debt service fund in the overall process:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>You will identify future capital needs that exceed the capacity of the Capital Projects Fund and identify planned funding sources for all improvements.</li>\r\n    <li>You will develop a tailored debt service plan to supplement the Capital Projects Fund, if needed.</li>\r\n    <li>It will create capacity and flexibility within the Capital Projects Fund.</li>\r\n    <li>A review of current debt service payments will identify timing opportunities if current debt is rolling off or the current debt structure has a step-down in annual payments.</li>\r\n    <li>You will develop an overall debt service strategy to maintain the current level of payments while you structure and plan for future needs.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Developing a combined capital projects fund and debt service master plan can yield benefits and provide additional funding.  Planning will also assist the district in controlling and maintaining its debt service levy.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>If you have questions or would like help developing a combined capital projects fund and debt service master plan, contact us.</p>', 'A Strategy to Deal with Schools'' Reduced Capital Project Funds', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '645-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-20 16:06:30', '2011-01-20 16:06:30', '', 645, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/645-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(833, 5, '2011-01-25 19:23:23', '2011-01-25 19:23:23', '<div><em>Part 2 in a series</em></div>\r\nThe circuit breaker property tax credits that voters will be asked to approve as part of the Indiana Constitution in November limit each taxpayer''s total property tax bill to a fixed percentage of the property''s value, before deductions.  Once a property taxpayer reaches this limit, they pay no more in property taxes, creating a "hard cap" on total effective property tax rates.  The resulting shortfalls in property tax collections are shared among all taxing units in proportion to their respective tax rate.\r\n\r\nSince local governmental units can''t borrow or increase property tax rates to replace the shortfall in revenues, it is essential for local governmental units and school districts to predict the amount of credits to be allocated to each of your funds.  For a variety of reasons, projections from the State have been unpredictable at best.  Even if revenue loss projections were accurate statewide, your area might deviate significantly from state averages.\r\n\r\nYour budget must recognize that not all of the property taxes levied will be collected.  You need a method to predict these shortfalls while you''re in the budget preparation process, because actual amounts from the county auditor will not be available until tax bills are prepared.\r\n\r\nBeyond the annual budgeting process, you will need to develop a forecast of revenues and expenditures for the next three to five years to identify potential revenue shortfalls.  Consider managing your budget to achieve a targeted fund balance by year end to give you a cushion to deal with any volatility in revenue.  The targeted fund balance should reflect adequate working capital, debt service requirements and capital plans.  It should also consider the uncertainly of future property tax collections and income tax receipts.\r\n\r\nYou will need to prioritize your needs.  For example, if you need to borrow money for capital projects, you''ll need to establish whether a new debt levy will be inside these limits (which may cause you to hit property tax caps) or if it is better to seek voter approval of the new levy through a referendum.\r\n\r\nProjects under $2 million may be funded by property tax supported bonds.  That debt service, however, will fall within the circuit breaker tax cap limits.  Bond repayment approved by a voter referendum is outside of the tax caps.\r\n\r\nAs revenue from state sales tax lagged at the end of 2009, we saw a number of school districts put public questions on the May primary ballot, asking voters to approve local property taxes for additional operating revenue.\r\n\r\nWe will probably see an increase in referendums as the full impact of property tax credits is felt â€“ not just from schools, but from libraries and other governmental units.\r\n\r\nIn our next article in this series, we''ll explore seemingly unintended consequences of the property tax caps.\r\n\r\nIf you would like help in projecting the effect of property tax caps in your area, finding cost efficiencies, consolidations, managing capital expenditures or growing your tax base, please contact us.', 'Planning Ahead â€“ What If Tax Caps Are Here To Stay', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '649-revision-4', '', '', '2011-01-25 19:23:23', '2011-01-25 19:23:23', '', 649, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/649-revision-4', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(834, 5, '2011-01-20 18:37:05', '2011-01-20 18:37:05', '<p>Now that July is upon us, local governmental units have started preparing 2011 budgets.  This series of articles will assist you with the complexities of transitioning revenue streams and the often-changing budgeting procedures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your budget must be done on time without exception.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The deadlines from last year remain in effect for 2011 budget preparation.  Work backward from the November 1 adoption deadline and to give yourself enough time to meet all the target dates in the approval process.*</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>September 2 - Deadline for 1st publication</li>\r\n    <li>September 9 - Deadline for 2nd publication</li>\r\n    <li>September 17 (or at least 45 days before the taxing unit adopts its budget) - Deadline for submitting the budget to your County Council</li>\r\n    <li>October 17 (or at least 15 days before the taxing unit adopts its budget) - Deadline for County Council to review the taxing unit''s budget and issue its non-binding recommendations</li>\r\n    <li>October 19 - Deadline to file an excess levy appeal with the DLGF (excluding shortfall appeal)</li>\r\n    <li>October 22 - Deadline for public hearing</li>\r\n    <li>November 1- Deadline for budget adoption</li>\r\n    <li>November 3 - Deadline to submit budget documents to the County Auditor</li>\r\n    <li>December 30 - Deadline to file a shortfall excess levy appeal with the DLGF</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>* Note: This is the general timetable.  Exceptions and differences exist, such as for Appointed Boards and Special Districts.  Please refer to the specific budget adoption requirements for your taxing unit.</p>\r\n<p>It is always a good idea to seek assistance or have someone take a second look at your budget before its adoption, especially in view of the current budget complexities.  If you have questions or need assistance in preparing your budget, please contact us.</p>', '2011 Budget Calendar', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '653-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-20 18:37:05', '2011-01-20 18:37:05', '', 653, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/653-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(835, 5, '2011-01-25 19:27:25', '2011-01-25 19:27:25', '<div><em>Part 1 in a series</em></div>\nNow that July is upon us, local governmental units have started preparing 2011 budgets.  This series of articles will assist you with the complexities of transitioning revenue streams and the often-changing budgeting procedures.\n\nYour budget must be done on time without exception.\n\nThe deadlines from last year remain in effect for 2011 budget preparation.  Work backward from the November 1 adoption deadline and to give yourself enough time to meet all the target dates in the approval process.*\n<ul>\n	<li>September 2 - Deadline for 1st publication</li>\n	<li>September 9 - Deadline for 2nd publication</li>\n	<li>September 17 (or at least 45 days before the taxing unit adopts its budget) - Deadline for submitting the budget to your County Council</li>\n	<li>October 17 (or at least 15 days before the taxing unit adopts its budget) - Deadline for County Council to review the taxing unit''s budget and issue its non-binding recommendations</li>\n	<li>October 19 - Deadline to file an excess levy appeal with the DLGF (excluding shortfall appeal)</li>\n	<li>October 22 - Deadline for public hearing</li>\n	<li>November 1- Deadline for budget adoption</li>\n	<li>November 3 - Deadline to submit budget documents to the County Auditor</li>\n	<li>December 30 - Deadline to file a shortfall excess levy appeal with the DLGF</li>\n</ul>\n* Note: This is the general timetable.  Exceptions and differences exist, such as for Appointed Boards and Special Districts.  Please refer to the specific budget adoption requirements for your taxing unit.\n\nIt is always a good idea to seek assistance or have someone take a second look at your budget before its adoption, especially in view of the current budget complexities.  If you have questions or need assistance in preparing your budget, please contact us.', '2011 Budget Calendar', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '653-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-25 19:27:25', '2011-01-25 19:27:25', '', 653, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/653-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(836, 5, '2011-01-20 18:38:22', '2011-01-20 18:38:22', '<p>Since our country just celebrated Independence Day, this is an opportune time to explain why we at Umbaugh value our independence as well.</p>\r\n<p>The meltdown of many formerly respected financial institutions and a top accounting firm delivered a dramatic lesson in the last few years.  When an accounting firm is too close to the entities it represents, it''s difficult â€“ if not impossible â€“ to give objective advice.</p>\r\n<p>At Umbaugh, our goal has always been to give independent advice not influenced by what''s best for Umbaugh; instead our advice is based solely on what''s best for our clients. We don''t have a financial interest in our clients or what we are proposing or advising, other than the fees for our services provided.  We don''t work on contingency fees; we don''t buy the bonds we''re working on.  We either decline to represent clients if there is a conflict of interest, or we disclose a potential conflict.  We serve as advisors to our clients, but we are not part of management and do not make any management decisions for our clients.  For example, our firm serves as a controller for certain cities or towns.  If we issue financial statements for these cities and towns, we must disclose that we assisted in posting those entries and are therefore not independent with respect to the financial statements.</p>\r\n<p>We are also big believers in the quality review process.  Although our practice is very different from most CPA firms, we nonetheless operate as a CPA firm.  Every three years, we submit our firm''s reports for a peer review by other CPAs in a program administered by the Indiana CPA Society and defined by the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants (AICPA).  Although not every CPA firm submits to the peer review process, we believe it is an important process to ensure the quality and accuracy of our work.  We are pleased to report that we just completed another successful peer review process earlier this year.</p>\r\n<p>In the two intervening years between peer reviews, we conduct our own internal review of quality practices.  On a day-to-day basis, we follow the rules, checklists, procedures and forms that make up our quality control process.  All financial work is scheduled to ensure our work receives proper review by experienced partners and principals supervising any work performed by our staff.</p>\r\n<p>Every day clients judge Umbaugh by the quality of our work.  We believe you must have standards to do a quality job -- whether that is accounting or our financial advisory practice.  That''s why quality and independence are so important to us.</p>', 'The Importance of Independence', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '655-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-20 18:38:22', '2011-01-20 18:38:22', '', 655, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/655-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
