or 2011.\n\nGiven the complexities and changes, it is always a good idea to have someone take a second look at your budget before its adoption.  If you have additional questions or need assistance in preparing your budget, please contact us.', '2011 Budget Preparation - Some Helpful FAQ''s', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '838-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-25 20:19:43', '2011-01-25 20:19:43', '', 838, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/838-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(841, 5, '2011-01-25 15:22:13', '2011-01-25 15:22:13', '<p>Wind farms are a relatively new form of economic development with unique financial considerations for both private and public entities. For private land owners, lease terms and liability protection are important factors to consider. For public entities, other aspects rise to the top of the priority list.</p>\r\n<p>Every project is unique. When deciding whether to pursue wind farms in your community, your top priorities should be protecting the infrastructure (both now and in the future), creating economic development agreements to create "win-win" scenarios, and ensuring open communication -- both internally as well as to the public.</p>\r\n<p>If you are considering wind turbines for your area, the tax abatement, tax base and tax rate implications will be essential elements. There are significant tax breaks associated with wind farms in Michigan. These projects are subject to Industrial Facility Tax, but may be partially exempt from some taxing authorities such as school districts. Investment in wind farm technology is primarily considered to be personal property. It is therefore necessary to work closely with company representatives and Michigan Economic Development Corporation for appropriate treatment.</p>\r\n<p>Because the construction of wind turbines requires extensive use of road and bridges, infrastructure protection is an important consideration.  A road use agreement is critical to protect the municipality''s infrastructure and define liability and traffic flow during construction. Key components of a road use agreement include a detailed map of roads, bridges and intersections to be used for construction and a process to determine existing conditions and identify county-regulated drains that may be affected.</p>\r\n<p>The municipality will need to reach an economic development agreement with the wind farm developer. Wind farms may take significant acreage and therefore reduce or eliminate opportunities for other economic development to occur within the project area. You will want to be compensated for this to generate funds to promote, encourage and create other types of economic development in other areas of the county.  The amount and timing of these payments need to be negotiated and defined.  Payments should not be considered payments in lieu of taxes or any type of "property tax;" they should be treated as miscellaneous revenue or for a specific use.  Your agreement may allocate these payments to schools, libraries, towns, fire departments or other units.</p>\r\n<p>You will also need to have a decommissioning plan in place prior to construction to protect the county and its constituents. The plan should include provisions and details for removal of towers, footings and access roads and returning the area to as near the same condition as possible if the wind generation project is terminated. Financial assurances need to be covered, and you should establish a schedule to review the decommissioning plan periodically.</p>\r\n<p>While alternative energy, and specifically wind farm development, seems to be gaining momentum; there are certainly very important financial aspects to consider for your community.  If Umbaugh''s experience in working through these issues would be helpful in your community, or if you have questions, please contact us.</p>', 'Alternative Energy Sources as Economic Development', 'Wind farms are a relatively new form of economic development with unique financial considerations for both private and public entities. For private land owners, lease terms and liability protection are important factors to consider. For public entities, other aspects rise to the top of the priority list.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '638-revision-7', '', '', '2011-01-25 15:22:13', '2011-01-25 15:22:13', '', 638, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/638-revision-7', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(842, 5, '2011-01-19 21:14:21', '2011-01-19 21:14:21', '<p>During the budget preparation season you will often hear budget myths and misconceptions in addition to the common questions we answered in the last issue of Footnotes.  This article helps you sort out the myths from the facts as you prepare your 2011 budget.</p>\r\n<p>Myth #1: The DLGF keeps cutting my budget.</p>\r\n<p>Fact: The Department of Local Government Finance (the DLGF) does not exist to arbitrarily make budget cuts to taxing units in Indiana.  The purpose of the DLGF is to make sure everyone follows the law regarding local government funding and property tax assessment.  If a taxing unit cannot afford the budget it''s proposing, it should not be a surprise when the 1782 Notice and Budget Order come back with budget reductions.  Especially in this time of circuit breaker credits and decreasing revenues, each taxing unit should know when there will be a temporary cash flow shortage or a structural budget deficit and react accordingly.  A monthly cash flow and forward-looking projections are highly recommended financial planning tools to prevent being surprised by a 1782 Notice and Budget Order.</p>\r\n<p>Myth #2: Use it, encumber it or lose it.</p>\r\n<p>Fact: A DLGF-approved budget is permission to spend.  When a taxing unit receives an order with an approved budget, this approved amount does not appear in the checking account of the taxing unit.  It is the maximum amount that may be spent without additional permission from the council, board or the DLGF.  In a personal bank account, money that is not spent stays in the account.  This is also true of taxing units.  If an appropriation is not spent, the money stays in the bank account to fund a cash balance or another appropriation.  The appropriation will expire at the end of the budget year, but there will be a new one at the beginning of the next budget year.  Appropriations may be encumbered only through a purchase order or contract.</p>\r\n<p>Myth #3: Budget to the max to get the max.</p>\r\n<p>Fact: Simply put, the maximum levy isn''t contingent upon a taxing unit''s budget; it is based on a statutory calculation performed by the DLGF.  This means the DLGF does not take budget estimates into account when calculating a maximum levy.  Make your budget estimates realistic, and base them on what your unit can actually afford.  However, it is important to note that the current statutory limitation encourages taxing units to set a high tax levy and tax rate to get the maximum levy.</p>\r\n<p>Given the complexities and changes, it is always a good idea to have someone take a second look at your budget before its adoption.  If you have additional questions or need assistance in preparing your budget, please contact us.</p>', 'Three Common Budgeting Myths', 'During the budget preparation season you will often hear budget myths and misconceptions in addition to the common questions we answered in the last issue of Footnotes.  This article helps you sort out the myths from the facts as you prepare your 2011 budget.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '635-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-19 21:14:21', '2011-01-19 21:14:21', '', 635, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/635-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
