(844, 5, '2011-01-19 21:10:50', '2011-01-19 21:10:50', '<p>The State Budget Agency announced in early August that local income tax distributions are down for 2011 by an average of 16% statewide.  With so many people unemployed or underemployed the income tax decrease is not entirely unexpected, but it is still unwelcome news.  It signals that economic recovery is still inconsistent, and these new reduced income tax numbers also will have a negative effect on local governments as they prepare 2011 budgets.</p>\r\n<p>The first action you should take is to base your budget projections for 2011 on lower income tax revenues â€“ and that''s probably in addition to other income reductions you''ve already experienced in 2010.  You should be receiving your 2011 income tax certifications from the State in the very near future.</p>\r\n<p>The second, but not so obvious, action step is to plan for circuit breaker credits to be much higher if you''re in a county that uses income taxes for property tax relief, including County Adjusted Gross Income Tax (CAGIT) and the new Local Option Income Taxes (LOIT).  When sweeping property tax reform legislation was enacted in the 2008 session of the Indiana General Assembly, the same bill allowed localities to quickly reconsider or restructure LOITs as a way to make up for lost revenue or to provide dollar-for-dollar property tax relief.  If you depend on LOIT revenue to provide property tax relief, and those collections are down, it will alter the result you were anticipating.  Any circuit breaker estimates you have been using may no longer be reliable due to this larger than expected reduction in income tax revenues.  This means that fewer property tax dollars will be available for public services in 2011. A reduction in local income tax collections may result in a reduction in property tax collections as well.</p>\r\n<p>Finally, if you have issued bonds, you will need to compare the new income tax reductions to your upcoming bond payments to determine if you will receive enough revenue to make those payments.  If you expect a shortfall and you have a property tax backup, that property tax levy will need to be advertised and included in your 2011 budget.</p>\r\n<p>If you need assistance with projecting revenues and forecasting budgets in light of the reduced local income tax distributions, please contact us.</p>', 'Reductions In State Income Tax Distributions Deliver Unwelcome News For Local Governments At Budget Time', 'The first action you should take is to base your budget projections for 2011 on lower income tax revenues â€“ and that''s probably in addition to other income reductions you''ve already experienced in 2010.  You should be receiving your 2011 income tax certifications from the State in the very near future.\r\n\r\nThe second, but not so obvious, action step is to plan for circuit breaker credits to be much higher if you''re in a county that uses income taxes for property tax relief, including County Adjusted Gross Income Tax (CAGIT) and the new Local Option Income Taxes (LOIT).  When sweeping property tax reform legislation was enacted in the 2008 session of the Indiana General Assembly, the same bill allowed localities to quickly reconsider or restructure LOITs as a way to make up for lost revenue or to provide dollar-for-dollar property tax relief.  If you depend on LOIT revenue to provide property tax relief, and those collections are down, it will alter the result you were anticipating.  Any circuit breaker estimates you have been using may no longer be reliable due to this larger than expected reduction in income tax revenues.  This means that fewer property tax dollars will be available for public services in 2011. A reduction in local income tax collections may result in a reduction in property tax collections as well.</p>\r\n<p>Finally, if you have issued bonds, you will need to compare the new income tax reductions to your upcoming bond payments to determine if you will receive enough revenue to make those payments.  If you expect a shortfall and you have a property tax backup, that property tax levy will need to be advertised and included in your 2011 budget.</p>\r\n<p>If you need assistance with projecting revenues and forecasting budgets in light of the reduced local income tax distributions, please contact us.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '631-revision-2', '', '', '2011-01-19 21:10:50', '2011-01-19 21:10:50', '', 631, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/631-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(845, 5, '2011-01-25 15:49:34', '2011-01-25 15:49:34', 'Across Indiana, local governmental entities are facing a <strong>half billion dollar reduction</strong> in income due to property tax caps, and additional reductions from the expansion of the homestead exemption and lower income tax collections in a down economy.  Finding new efficiencies to operate on less income is much more than simply cutting your budget, you also must manage revenues efficiently.\r\n\r\nEnacting new local option income taxes (LOIT) to replace property taxes, can reduce the amount of property tax lost to the tap caps by lowering property tax levies and total tax rates.\r\n\r\nAs an example, the chart at left shows the effect of circuit breaker tax credits. In this sample, local governments will lose $2.5 million using current property values.  With property values increasing as in the past, the loss to circuit breaker credits is reduced to $2.2 million.  But remember that property values can trend downward as well as upward.  If property values decrease, the loss from property taxes could be greater.\r\n\r\nIn this same scenario, if the local government enacts a .5% LOIT rate that generates $2.8 million in revenue, the loss from property tax caps is reduced to $1.1 million if the LOIT-funded property tax relief is distributed just to qualified residential properties and to $1.3 million if distributed uniformly.\r\n\r\n<hr />When combined with property tax relief, a new LOIT can also provide new money for public safety.  A public safety LOIT of .25% can generate an estimated $1.4 million in our example.\r\n\r\nChanging the mix of local income taxes may increase total revenues available to taxing units without increasing the total income tax rate. Changes to local income taxes that may increase spendable tax revenue without increasing income tax rates include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Eliminating the local COIT Homestead Credit.  Some of these local credits were enacted before the state adopted credits, so the local credits may no longer be needed in your area.  The final chart at right shows the potential effect of eliminating COIT Homestead Credits.  The $3+ million in increased COIT revenue is partially offset by the decrease in property tax revenues as circuit breaker credits increase, but it still produces additional revenue of nearly $1.5 million.</li>\r\n	<li>Replacing a portion of a CAGIT tax, designed for property tax relief, with an EDIT tax, producing new spendable revenue.</li>\r\n	<li>Shifting LOIT credits from Homestead Credits to either qualified residential credits or uniform credits.  Oftentimes, circuit breaker tax credits benefit do not benefit the majority of homeowners.</li>\r\n	<li>Eliminating the CEDIT inventory replacement rate used for additional homestead credits in exchange for other local option income taxes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBecause many of these revenues are interdependent, finding the right mix of local income taxes will require running some "what if" scenarios for your area.\r\n\r\nThe next article in this series will cover opportunities for cost efficiency.\r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need assistance dealing with reduced funding, please contact us.</em>', 'Strategies for Government Efficiency Part 2: Managing Revenues Efficiently', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '494-revision-7', '', '', '2011-01-25 15:49:34', '2011-01-25 15:49:34', '', 494, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/494-revision-7', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(846, 5, '2011-01-25 20:35:45', '2011-01-25 20:35:45', 'The State Budget Agency announced in early August that local income tax distributions are down for 2011 by an average of 16% statewide.  With so many people unemployed or underemployed the income tax decrease is not entirely unexpected, but it is still unwelcome news.  It signals that economic recovery is still inconsistent, and these new reduced income tax numbers also will have a negative effect on local governments as they prepare 2011 budgets.\r\n\r\nThe first action you should take is to base your budget projections for 2011 on lower income tax revenues â€“ and that''s probably in addition to other income reductions you''ve already experienced in 2010.  You should be receiving your 2011 income tax certifications from the State in the very near future.\r\n\r\nThe second, but not so obvious, action step is to plan for circuit breaker credits to be much higher if you''re in a county that uses income taxes for property tax relief, including County Adjusted Gross Income Tax (CAGIT) and the new Local Option Income Taxes (LOIT).  When sweeping property tax reform legislation was enacted in the 2008 session of the Indiana General Assembly, the same bill allowed localities to quickly reconsider or restructure LOITs as a way to make up for lost revenue or to provide dollar-for-dollar property tax relief.  If you depend on LOIT revenue to provide property tax relief, and those collections are down, it will alter the result you were anticipating.  Any circuit breaker estimates you have been using may no longer be reliable due to this larger than expected reduction in income tax revenues.  This means that fewer property tax dollars will be available for public services in 2011. A reduction in local income tax collections may result in a reduction in property tax collections as well.\r\n\r\nFinally, if you have issued bonds, you will need to compare the new income tax reductions to your upcoming bond payments to determine if you will receive enough revenue to make those payments.  If you expect a shortfall and you have a property tax backup, that property tax levy will need to be advertised and included in your 2011 budget.\r\n\r\nIf you need assistance with projecting revenues and forecasting budgets in light of the reduced local income tax distributions, please contact us.', 'Reductions In State Income Tax Distributions Deliver Unwelcome News For Local Governments At Budget Time', 'The first action you should take is to base your budget projections for 2011 on lower income tax revenues â€“ and that''s probably in addition to other income reductions you''ve already experienced in 2010.  You should be receiving your 2011 income tax certifications from the State in the very near future.\r\n\r\nThe second, but not so obvious, action step is to plan for circuit breaker credits to be much higher if you''re in a county that uses income taxes for property tax relief, including County Adjusted Gross Income Tax (CAGIT) and the new Local Option Income Taxes (LOIT).  When sweeping property tax reform legislation was enacted in the 2008 session of the Indiana General Assembly, the same bill allowed localities to quickly reconsider or restructure LOITs as a way to make up for lost revenue or to provide dollar-for-dollar property tax relief.  If you depend on LOIT revenue to provide property tax relief, and those collections are down, it will alter the result you were anticipating.  Any circuit breaker estimates you have been using may no longer be reliable due to this larger than expected reduction in income tax revenues.  This means that fewer property tax dollars will be available for public services in 2011. A reduction in local income tax collections may result in a reduction in property tax collections as well.</p>\r\n<p>Finally, if you have issued bonds, you will need to compare the new income tax reductions to your upcoming bond payments to determine if you will receive enough revenue to make those payments.  If you expect a shortfall and you have a property tax backup, that property tax levy will need to be advertised and included in your 2011 budget.</p>\r\n<p>If you need assistance with projecting revenues and forecasting budgets in light of the reduced local income tax distributions, please contact us.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '631-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-25 20:35:45', '2011-01-25 20:35:45', '', 631, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/631-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
