(848, 5, '2011-01-25 19:58:09', '2011-01-25 19:58:09', 'Since our country just celebrated Independence Day, this is an opportune time to explain why we at Umbaugh value our independence as well.\r\n\r\nThe meltdown of many formerly respected financial institutions and a top accounting firm delivered a dramatic lesson in the last few years.  When an accounting firm is too close to the entities it represents, it''s difficult â€“ if not impossible â€“ to give objective advice.\r\n\r\nAt Umbaugh, our goal has always been to give independent advice not influenced by what''s best for Umbaugh; instead our advice is based solely on what''s best for our clients. We don''t have a financial interest in our clients or what we are proposing or advising, other than the fees for our services provided.  We don''t work on contingency fees; we don''t buy the bonds we''re working on.  We either decline to represent clients if there is a conflict of interest, or we disclose a potential conflict.  We serve as advisors to our clients, but we are not part of management and do not make any management decisions for our clients.  For example, our firm serves as a controller for certain cities or towns.  If we issue financial statements for these cities and towns, we must disclose that we assisted in posting those entries and are therefore not independent with respect to the financial statements.\r\n\r\nWe are also big believers in the quality review process.  Although our practice is very different from most CPA firms, we nonetheless operate as a CPA firm.  Every three years, we submit our firm''s reports for a peer review by other CPAs in a program administered by the Indiana CPA Society and defined by the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants (AICPA).  Although not every CPA firm submits to the peer review process, we believe it is an important process to ensure the quality and accuracy of our work.  We are pleased to report that we just completed another successful peer review process earlier this year.\r\n\r\nIn the two intervening years between peer reviews, we conduct our own internal review of quality practices.  On a day-to-day basis, we follow the rules, checklists, procedures and forms that make up our quality control process.  All financial work is scheduled to ensure our work receives proper review by experienced partners and principals supervising any work performed by our staff.\r\n\r\nEvery day clients judge Umbaugh by the quality of our work.  We believe you must have standards to do a quality job -- whether that is accounting or our financial advisory practice.  That''s why quality and independence are so important to us.', 'The Importance of Independence', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '655-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-25 19:58:09', '2011-01-25 19:58:09', '', 655, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/655-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(849, 5, '2011-01-19 21:25:21', '2011-01-19 21:25:21', '<p><strong>Part 3 in a series</strong></p>\r\n<p>In November Indiana voters will be asked to vote on whether or not to make the new property tax caps part of the Indiana Constitution.  In our previous articles in this series we''ve dealt with budget planning and revenue issues for governmental units and school districts.  Property tax caps have three side effects you may not have anticipated.</p>\r\n<p>1.  Tax caps will increase dialog with your end users.  Living with property tax caps for the long haul will force all governmental units and school districts to do a better job of communicating with constituents.  Voters will have the ability to decide whether projects get funding.  So it behooves you to explain budgets and needs and get public input long before a financial issue gets to the voting booth.  It also presents the opportunity to involve your constituents in some strategic planning about service expectations.  How many police officers do we need?  What do we want our fire department response time to be?  Can we get by with less snow plowing or fewer street lights?  Is it acceptable to have fewer course offerings or larger class sizes?  Your constituents need to be educated and have a say in these difficult decisions before it becomes a critical issue or a question at the ballot box. </p>\r\n<p>2.  Tax caps may make you more creative.  This option does not apply to school districts, but local governmental units may wish to change their mix of local income taxes to increase spendable tax revenue without increasing income tax rates.  For example, eliminating the County Option Income Tax (COIT) Homestead Credit if you have one will increase your circuit breaker tax credits, but it will provide more usable revenues.  Replacing a portion of a CAGIT tax with an EDIT tax may provide more usable tax dollars.  Shifting LOIT credits from Homestead Credits to either Qualified Residential Credits or Uniform Credits may reduce revenue loss from circuit breaker tax credits. Or eliminate the CEDIT inventory replacement rate used to provide additional homestead credits and exchange it for other local option income taxes.  These changes may sound like a shell game, but they are perfectly good tools to benefit your operations without increasing rates for taxpayers.</p>\r\n<p>3.  Tax caps will increase your awareness of what other taxing units are doing.  Now more than ever, local taxing units and school districts are in this situation together.  One unit raising its tax rate could trigger tax caps and reduce income for all other units.  You can call this keeping an eye on your competitors for tax revenue â€“ or approach it in a spirit of friendly cooperation, but one way or another you need to know what others have planned.  Because of this increased interdependence, you''ll be spending more time getting to know other governmental units.</p>\r\n<p>If you would like help in projecting the effect of property tax caps in your area, strategic planning or exploring options to replace lost revenue, please contact us.</p>', 'Managing Your City or Town if Tax Caps Are Here to Stay', 'In November Indiana voters will be asked to vote on whether or not to make the new property tax caps part of the Indiana Constitution.  In our previous articles in this series we''ve dealt with budget planning and revenue issues for governmental units and school districts.  Property tax caps have three side effects you may not have anticipated.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '633-revision-3', '', '', '2011-01-19 21:25:21', '2011-01-19 21:25:21', '', 633, 'http://dev.umbaugh.com/633-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
